00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Hi, thanks for having me over.

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:08.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, the last time we spoke, it was about your wonderful book, India Moving, which I

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:12.960
[Amit Varma]: keep recommending to people because I just think it deserves to be more widely read and

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:17.000
[Amit Varma]: more specifically, because it gave me so many insights into my own country.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:18.620
[Amit Varma]: So many TIL moments.

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:21.420
[Amit Varma]: And that, of course, took sort of a long time in the making.

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:26.000
[Amit Varma]: On the other hand, this marvelous book that you have now written has happened in the space

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:27.000
[Amit Varma]: of a few months.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, tell me the story of how that came about.

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:34.080
[Guest]: Yeah, it's just, you know, if you told me in Jan that I would write a book by December

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:36.480
[Guest]: on pandemics, you know, I would have laughed.

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:40.640
[Guest]: And in a way, I'm still laughing because it's just a series of events which happened this

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:43.760
[Guest]: year that, you know, ultimately culminated in the book.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:48.560
[Guest]: But really, the starting point is, of course, that, you know, when I was writing on migration,

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:51.720
[Guest]: even my PhD thesis, you know, I was coming across cholera.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:52.720
[Guest]: I was coming across plague.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:53.720
[Guest]: I was coming across influenza.

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:58.680
[Guest]: In fact, even my PhD thesis in 2012, you know, I have this map of population growth rate

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:00.760
[Guest]: in 1911 to 21.

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:05.800
[Guest]: So I clearly knew some of these interesting things about these pandemics because I'd encountered

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:08.440
[Guest]: them before in my research on migration.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:12.640
[Guest]: But obviously, I'd not done, you know, any, I'd never written a research paper on pandemics.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:17.240
[Guest]: I'd never really followed up on that initial interest, but I had been scraping through

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:19.000
[Guest]: material wherever I went.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.720
[Guest]: I was at the British Library, you know, many years back doing archival research.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:24.840
[Guest]: And there's a report on cholera in 1867.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:26.680
[Guest]: And I kind of got that photocopy.

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:31.360
[Guest]: So I had certain material, and the starting point of this project was really March 11th,

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:35.320
[Guest]: 12th, you know, when the WHO declared it to be a pandemic.

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:39.560
[Guest]: And I, in fact, actually tweeted a bit, you know, on influenza impact on India, and it

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:41.780
[Guest]: got a fair amount of traction.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:44.720
[Guest]: And one of the things I very quickly realized was, you know, first, there's actually no

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:50.320
[Guest]: book written on influenza in India, which is the greatest demographic disaster ever

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:51.760
[Guest]: in human history, actually.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.640
[Guest]: I mean, 20 million people dying in a few months.

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:56.200
[Guest]: It's never happened before.

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.280
[Guest]: So this was, you know, something truly unique.

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:01.560
[Guest]: Somebody had to write it.

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:06.720
[Guest]: And then, you know, as the book starts off with this dialogue with my son, my son actually

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:10.640
[Guest]: asked me, you know, what's this whole thing about pandemics, was it happening in the past?

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:11.640
[Guest]: And I said, yes.

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:15.680
[Guest]: And, you know, he pointed out that influenza was also mentioned in the Tintin.

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:19.480
[Guest]: And I realized that, you know, there's some ways in which the memory is stored.

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:24.280
[Guest]: But overall, you know, unless it's the Black Death of Europe in the 14th century, where

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:28.400
[Guest]: a lot of books have been written, or even the influenza, you know, there's a book by

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:31.240
[Guest]: John Barry on the influenza.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:35.760
[Guest]: India has one small paragraph in a 500 page book, when half the deaths of that pandemic

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:37.080
[Guest]: happened in India.

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:41.120
[Guest]: So India was really underserved in the current research.

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:44.960
[Guest]: And the fact that in all three pandemics, cholera, plague, influenza in the century

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:49.840
[Guest]: between roughly 1817 and 1920, India was at the epicenter.

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:53.760
[Guest]: And this just really struck me in March that, you know, somebody really has to be writing

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:54.760
[Guest]: about this.

00:06:54.760 --> 00:06:59.040
[Guest]: And then, you know, I quickly realized that I was in a unique position to do it, because

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:03.160
[Guest]: I had already assembled this massive mortality statistic database as part of my interest

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:05.080
[Guest]: in economics and history.

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:08.160
[Guest]: And so I started analyzing that database, and I could see the trends, when is mortality

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:09.640
[Guest]: rising, and so on.

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:14.160
[Guest]: So that gave me more confidence that, you know, I could do something on this.

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:20.160
[Guest]: And then coupled with, you know, the fact that a lot of the databases on this are actually

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:21.720
[Guest]: freely available online.

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:26.200
[Guest]: So the Wellcome Trust has, you know, all these pictures and reports freely available online.

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:29.320
[Guest]: So that kind of reduced the transaction costs of doing research.

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:32.640
[Guest]: And typically, you know, a project in history would take many, many years, you sit in archives

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:33.640
[Guest]: and so on.

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:37.280
[Guest]: But I realized that at least some of it was easily doable.

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:41.760
[Guest]: So then I think in about April, you know, I kind of said, okay, this is a potential

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:42.760
[Guest]: project.

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:45.360
[Guest]: Of course, it would not be possible without family support.

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:50.440
[Guest]: You know, the amount of hours that put into writing consecutively meant, I mean, I should

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:53.560
[Guest]: really thank my wife and son for giving me that space to just go out there.

00:07:53.560 --> 00:07:58.560
[Guest]: I think I would say 100 days of just literally nonstop work, you know, coupled with then,

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:01.000
[Guest]: of course, many more months of post production, and so on.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:02.680
[Guest]: So it's been a crazy year for everyone.

00:08:02.680 --> 00:08:04.160
[Guest]: It's been a crazy year for me.

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:06.840
[Guest]: In the process, also, I lost a friend.

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:10.680
[Guest]: So the book is dedicated to a friend who's a librarian of Ahmedabad.

00:08:10.680 --> 00:08:14.120
[Guest]: And it's really thanks to, again, the library of Ahmedabad, you know, that we could actually

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:15.120
[Guest]: get a lot of this material.

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:19.080
[Guest]: So it's a combination of amazing teamwork, which kind of got the book and I really wanted

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:20.560
[Guest]: it out in 2020.

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:22.240
[Guest]: You know, that would have had a nice ring to it.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:26.640
[Guest]: So finally, the last month, you know, December 2020 is when we could get it out.

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:30.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, what's crazy about this is that your book is by no means a quickie in the

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:31.800
[Amit Varma]: sense is immaculately researched.

00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:36.280
[Amit Varma]: And what I do, what I like to do whenever I read nonfiction is I'll go over to the footnotes,

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:39.520
[Amit Varma]: whenever I find something interesting and look at where that's from and look at sort

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:44.080
[Amit Varma]: of the bibliography and you just read a bunch of books while doing this not just books in

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:49.640
[Amit Varma]: terms of historical books, books on previous epidemics slash pandemics.

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:53.960
[Amit Varma]: But even you know, you've quoted throughout your book from different novels and literary

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:56.760
[Amit Varma]: works and all of that very aptly.

00:08:56.760 --> 00:09:03.200
[Amit Varma]: So I simply have to then ask you about, you know, what are your processes of knowledge

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:08.160
[Amit Varma]: management, for example, like how many books if I may ask, did you read during this period?

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:09.880
[Amit Varma]: How many books do you normally read?

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:11.980
[Amit Varma]: How many did you read during this period?

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:17.040
[Amit Varma]: And what are your sort of methods or hacks for compressing this kind of data gathering

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:18.880
[Amit Varma]: and knowledge gathering?

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:20.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, all of that?

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:21.440
[Guest]: Great question.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:26.160
[Guest]: There's no doubt I've read more books in 2020 than any year of my life.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:31.200
[Guest]: And I love to read, you know, so this is definitely a year of massive, massive amount of reading,

00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:34.600
[Guest]: not just the number of books, but also research articles, papers and so on.

00:09:34.600 --> 00:09:40.440
[Guest]: Now, well, you know, the book has like 800 footnotes, and it cites over 400 studies.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:43.960
[Guest]: But I should say that, you know, does that mean I have read each and every book cover

00:09:43.960 --> 00:09:44.960
[Guest]: to cover?

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:45.960
[Guest]: That's impossible.

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:51.360
[Guest]: That's impossible for anybody to read, say 300 books, you know, that's just impossible.

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:56.920
[Guest]: So a lot of books, of course, I quickly realized what is the really important part of it.

00:09:56.920 --> 00:09:58.960
[Guest]: And really, you know, get that into the book.

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:02.520
[Guest]: So for example, there's a great book called everyday technologies, which is about really

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:04.200
[Guest]: technology history of India.

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:07.720
[Guest]: But there's this amazing part on plague, where there's a reference in this book about how

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:12.880
[Guest]: the tailors of Singer manufacturing company, you know, which is a multinational based in

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:18.280
[Guest]: India, they had this particular issue of tailors dying because of the plague in late 19th century.

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:19.280
[Guest]: And I just got that reference.

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:22.040
[Guest]: Now, it just so happens that I've read this book in the past.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:25.880
[Guest]: But there are many books in which very quickly, as a researcher, you know, you can go through

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:30.040
[Guest]: the index, you're looking for plague, cholera, influenza, these are the three pandemics.

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:33.000
[Guest]: And if you're not, if you get it, you're lucky, right.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.440
[Guest]: So I would also say I've gone through many more books which are not cited, just to find

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:41.360
[Guest]: out if they mentioned plague, cholera, or influenza.

00:10:41.360 --> 00:10:44.160
[Guest]: But in the process, I had to read certain quote, the first book, let me tell you the

00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:45.160
[Guest]: process.

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:50.280
[Guest]: The first book I read, was this Cambridge encyclopedia of human diseases, right, because

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:53.360
[Guest]: I had to tell myself, look, I don't know anything about medical science.

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:54.360
[Guest]: I'm not a scientist.

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:55.360
[Guest]: I'm not a biologist.

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:58.920
[Guest]: And I'm looking at this literally from a trained economist who's getting into history.

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:00.920
[Guest]: That's, you know, that's my background.

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: So I said have to be at least, I should not get the science drastically wrong, you know,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
[Guest]: so I had to read it.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.880
[Guest]: So this is a 1000 page book, you know, which came out in 1993, obviously, there's no updates

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:13.880
[Guest]: in that.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:17.560
[Guest]: But this is supposed to be the canonical book on medical history.

00:11:17.560 --> 00:11:21.440
[Guest]: And so those 1000 pages gave me like this nice quick summary of all the major diseases

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:24.320
[Guest]: of the world, major medical schools.

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:25.320
[Guest]: So that was the starting point.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:29.720
[Guest]: And then some of the canonical books on cholera, canonical books on plague, and unfortunately

00:11:29.720 --> 00:11:33.600
[Guest]: influenza, literally nothing has been written on India, you know, so there's really no book

00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:34.600
[Guest]: on India.

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:39.480
[Guest]: Similarly, with plague and cholera, you know, David Arnold has a book.

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:41.240
[Guest]: So that was useful to start with.

00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:44.240
[Guest]: And then he's done wonderful work, even in the recent days.

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:48.600
[Guest]: So then slowly after that, of course, for a writer, you want to tie up the basic academic

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:53.960
[Guest]: blocks with literary references with, you know, variety of things, newspaper archives,

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:57.200
[Guest]: which are easily accessible, at least from our library.

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:58.480
[Guest]: But there are a lot of chance discoveries.

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:01.400
[Guest]: So I was, you know, literally one finding thinking, you know, they're not enough first

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:03.840
[Guest]: person references in what I'm doing right now.

00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:08.240
[Guest]: It's becoming a drab sort of statistical kind of analysis.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:09.640
[Guest]: And I was just looking at my bookshelf.

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:15.200
[Guest]: And there it was, you know, Smriti Chitre, which is this Marathi autobiography by Lakshmi

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:20.200
[Guest]: by Tilak, written in the 1930s, and translated in English just a few years back by Shanta

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:21.560
[Guest]: Gokhale.

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:24.960
[Guest]: And there it was, there was a first person reference about plague.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:29.740
[Guest]: And unknown even to Shanta Gokhale, who translated the book, the disease Manmodi was nothing

00:12:29.740 --> 00:12:31.920
[Guest]: but this great influenza epidemic of 1918.

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:36.040
[Guest]: And I just, it was a eureka moment that, you know, I said, she's talking about influenza

00:12:36.040 --> 00:12:39.560
[Guest]: 1918, which is the greatest disaster in a first person account, because that family

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:40.960
[Guest]: went through that.

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:43.940
[Guest]: So I got these amazing references purely out of chance.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:48.280
[Guest]: So I think the writer's thing is then about putting these things in a nice sort of a story.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:50.720
[Guest]: But the big story is very clear.

00:12:50.720 --> 00:12:56.000
[Guest]: This was a period where we are told in India, is the rise and fall of British rule.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.520
[Guest]: And yet what I was finding is in the day to day lives of people, I mean, they were less

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:03.680
[Guest]: scared of the British than infectious disease, because it's like today, you know, we have

00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:05.920
[Guest]: concerns with the politics and so on.

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:09.760
[Guest]: But the primary concern over here is trying not to get this disease.

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:11.840
[Guest]: And that's pretty much how Indians were looking at this.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:15.800
[Guest]: And the numbers were stark, you know, we're saying about 70 million people globally died

00:13:15.800 --> 00:13:19.360
[Guest]: of these three pandemics, 40 million in India alone.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:22.920
[Guest]: These are numbers greater than the wars fought in this period.

00:13:22.920 --> 00:13:27.320
[Guest]: More people died in India in influenza than all of the people who died on the battlefields

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:28.720
[Guest]: of World War One.

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:33.640
[Guest]: So putting all that together, you know, I thought I had a fair amount of kind of work

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:35.720
[Guest]: cut ahead for me.

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:41.820
[Guest]: But luckily, access to resources was relatively easy, because I live on a university campus.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:45.240
[Guest]: So that's, I think, I think there are various things that cut down transaction costs of

00:13:45.240 --> 00:13:46.240
[Guest]: doing research.

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:51.120
[Guest]: As I said, amazing library team, they got me really rare, even manuscripts from, you

00:13:51.120 --> 00:13:54.560
[Guest]: know, just talking with other libraries, they have this fantastic interlibrary ties.

00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:58.360
[Guest]: So clearly, if you're not in a university setting, obviously, I think the transaction

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:02.160
[Guest]: costs are much, much higher, but not a chance encounter.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:08.440
[Guest]: You know, I was in South Park Street Cemetery in Calcutta, which is a burial ground, literally

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:12.320
[Guest]: few days before the lockdown, a few more days, and I'll be stuck in Calcutta, and this book

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:13.320
[Guest]: will probably never happen.

00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:16.200
[Guest]: You know, it's just so happened that came back to Ahmedabad.

00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:20.840
[Guest]: But South Park Street Cemetery, my economist training, you know, I saw this book at the

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:21.900
[Guest]: counter.

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:23.920
[Guest]: And that was the registry of all the deaths out there.

00:14:23.920 --> 00:14:26.880
[Guest]: Now, at that point, I didn't know I was going to write a book on pandemics, but I picked

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:29.720
[Guest]: up that book, I bought it, and I got it to a spreadsheet.

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:32.880
[Guest]: This is what all economists will do, you know, put it in a spreadsheet.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:38.400
[Guest]: And there it was, because I wanted some evidence that 1817, a lot of people said this was an

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:41.040
[Guest]: important year, and the book starts on this year.

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:45.200
[Guest]: You know, how do you show that 1817 is, there were a lot of deaths in 1817.

00:14:45.200 --> 00:14:48.000
[Guest]: One is by saying, people said that something happened in that year.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:53.520
[Guest]: But ideally, you would like to see like a trend line, you'd want to have pre 1817 data,

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:56.200
[Guest]: and then show that 1817 things jump up.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:58.300
[Guest]: And there it was, I got this digitized.

00:14:58.300 --> 00:15:01.440
[Guest]: And this is the burial grounds in Calcutta where cholera struck mid time.

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:03.200
[Guest]: And it's a flat line before 1817.

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:04.520
[Guest]: And it spikes up.

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:09.000
[Guest]: So the number of burials recorded in South Park Street Cemetery conforms to what people

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.640
[Guest]: are saying then, you know, about which years cholera struck very, very nicely, not just

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:13.640
[Guest]: for 1817.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:15.640
[Guest]: But you know, for the next 50 years.

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:20.600
[Guest]: So again, a chance encounter, literally a walk through that cemetery, picking up a book,

00:15:20.600 --> 00:15:23.040
[Amit Varma]: and then that becomes a useful source.

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:27.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'll kind of stick on the subject for just a moment before we get to the book.

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:30.840
[Amit Varma]: Once you're sort of, you're doing all of this reading, how do you organize the knowledge

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.000
[Amit Varma]: that you're taking from there?

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there a special software that you use many of these, I'm guessing, especially

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:39.720
[Amit Varma]: if you're getting them from the library, they'll be like physical books?

00:15:39.720 --> 00:15:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Is there a software?

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:42.640
[Amit Varma]: How do you organize all of this knowledge?

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:43.640
[Amit Varma]: How do you manage all of that?

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:46.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I would say I'm quite old fashioned that way.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.160
[Guest]: I know they are, you know, specialized software.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:51.040
[Guest]: I'm sure I can do research more efficiently than what I'm doing right now.

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:53.600
[Guest]: I'm old fashioned in the sense I use a spreadsheet.

00:15:53.600 --> 00:15:57.680
[Guest]: So I, you know, I put all my thoughts in a spreadsheet.

00:15:57.680 --> 00:16:01.960
[Guest]: And you know, I have lines put in bold, which I don't want to miss over.

00:16:01.960 --> 00:16:05.040
[Guest]: And what I can miss, you know, it's not in bold.

00:16:05.040 --> 00:16:08.800
[Guest]: But what I definitely do is, you know, like in this project, kind of try to collect all

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:10.120
[Guest]: the basic literature.

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:14.120
[Guest]: So what I made a list of about 500 studies, which I said I have to go through, even if

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:17.280
[Guest]: I don't read each of them cover to cover, I should be aware of what they're saying.

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:19.400
[Guest]: And so I put those 500 studies, you know, worksheet.

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:22.280
[Guest]: So it's a reference sheet, and that's going to be, by the way, next week, it's, there's

00:16:22.280 --> 00:16:26.320
[Guest]: a supplement to this book, which is going to go online, it's a working paper.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:28.800
[Guest]: And so that will have a list of, you know, all the studies.

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:31.040
[Guest]: So I did, I made that first.

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:34.160
[Guest]: And so I knew what, you know, I was working within.

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:39.640
[Guest]: And then, you know, after that, the spreadsheet kind of helps sort your ideas, kind of saying,

00:16:39.640 --> 00:16:41.640
[Guest]: okay, this is the flow.

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:42.640
[Guest]: It was all nebulous.

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.800
[Guest]: You know, when I started in March, I really didn't know what is, I all I knew is that

00:16:45.800 --> 00:16:49.480
[Guest]: there can be three chapters, core chapters of the book, which is going to clear up like

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:53.400
[Guest]: an influenza, and then maybe an introductory chapter and a concluding chapter kind of reflecting

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:54.400
[Guest]: on COVID-19.

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:58.040
[Guest]: But then beyond that, you know, how do you write a colera, this colera is almost a hundred

00:16:58.040 --> 00:16:59.440
[Guest]: year pandemic.

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:01.360
[Guest]: So it's really pick and choose.

00:17:01.360 --> 00:17:05.040
[Guest]: You can't talk about each and every year, you can't talk about each and every country.

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest]: So you really have to select.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:12.200
[Guest]: And so my process of selection then is, like in the book on migration is demographic, that

00:17:12.200 --> 00:17:15.080
[Guest]: is, where did it have the largest impact?

00:17:15.080 --> 00:17:18.720
[Guest]: So obviously India had the largest impact and India gets covered the most, but in cholera,

00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:23.600
[Guest]: I devote some time to Egypt, you know, because Egypt had the largest, like 10% of its population

00:17:23.600 --> 00:17:24.600
[Guest]: was wiped out.

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:28.080
[Guest]: So as a percentage of population, Egypt was the most affected.

00:17:28.080 --> 00:17:30.880
[Guest]: So you know, it affected US, it affected Mexico.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:33.280
[Guest]: So I try to then cover those regions which are most affected.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:37.200
[Guest]: And I think that's the pattern in all the chapters, that is the regions most affected

00:17:37.200 --> 00:17:38.440
[Guest]: by the pandemics.

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:42.440
[Guest]: So if you talk of plague, not just Bombay, no, most of plague literature in Bombay on

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:44.360
[Guest]: India is Bombay city.

00:17:44.360 --> 00:17:48.200
[Guest]: And this book, probably the first time, you know, it's really expanding that thing because

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:51.480
[Guest]: Bombay city was a really small part of India's plague encounter.

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:56.480
[Guest]: The bulk of it was the Bombay presidency, Punjab, UP, outside Bombay, the bulk of it

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:57.480
[Guest]: was rural India.

00:17:57.480 --> 00:18:00.520
[Guest]: You know, people think of plague as being a Bombay incident, the bulk of it was actually

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:01.640
[Guest]: rural India.

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:06.840
[Guest]: So that's the sort of sorting process to try and get the big picture, where is it actually

00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:09.760
[Guest]: affected, and then trying to get literature which has looked at that.

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:13.680
[Guest]: And where it's not been written, then to actually dig up sources, go to newspaper archives and

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:18.280
[Guest]: a variety of other things to kind of hold reports, vaccination records and a variety

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:19.440
[Guest]: of things.

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:25.080
[Guest]: And along the way, discover a lot, you know, so some of it has been done by medical historians.

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:27.160
[Guest]: So I looked at that literature very closely.

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:32.440
[Guest]: But beyond that, you know, to your question about efficient management of information,

00:18:32.440 --> 00:18:34.820
[Guest]: I don't think I'm terribly efficient.

00:18:34.820 --> 00:18:38.520
[Guest]: But there is some method, I think, in this, you know, research process.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:39.520
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:40.840
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to the book now.

00:18:40.840 --> 00:18:45.200
[Amit Varma]: And before we start talking about pandemics per se, there was a broader question, which

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:50.000
[Amit Varma]: I thought I should ask at the start, because it really intrigued me and struck me, you

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.600
[Amit Varma]: know, how we normalize all the progress that we make in terms of technology or standards

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:56.280
[Amit Varma]: of living or whatever.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:19:00.640
[Amit Varma]: And I was, you know, struck by when you wrote the following words about mass mortality,

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:05.640
[Amit Varma]: where you wrote, quote, once upon a time, we barely lived before we died, we would celebrate

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:08.880
[Amit Varma]: on average only 25 birthdays in our lifetimes.

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And we rarely grew old enough to see our grandchildren.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:17.040
[Amit Varma]: Mass mortality through war, famine, natural disasters, and epidemics was a way of life.

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:22.080
[Amit Varma]: We began to live longer only when we fought fewer wars, understood how to fight famines,

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:27.240
[Amit Varma]: grew resilient to natural disasters, and learned how to control the spread of disease, stop

00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:28.240
[Amit Varma]: quote.

00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:32.480
[Amit Varma]: And at different points in the book, when you talk about, you know, specific pandemics

00:19:32.480 --> 00:19:37.400
[Amit Varma]: or even diseases, we see how you could not take life for granted.

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:41.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, at one point, when you're writing about smallpox, you write, quote, there's

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:45.320
[Amit Varma]: an old saying in India common in the 19th century, that children were not counted as

00:19:45.320 --> 00:19:50.240
[Amit Varma]: permanent members of the family until they had encountered smallpox once and survived,

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:51.240
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:55.320
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, later, when you're sort of talking about another pandemic, you quote

00:19:55.320 --> 00:20:00.360
[Amit Varma]: David Gilmore in the British in India, saying, quote, one visitor reported that he had twice

00:20:00.360 --> 00:20:05.160
[Amit Varma]: lunched with men whose burials he had been invited to attend before supper the same day,

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:09.640
[Amit Varma]: when an epidemic arrived at a station, people began measuring their lives in ours.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:13.800
[Amit Varma]: They went to the club each evening apprehensive to know who was missing from the night before.

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:18.080
[Amit Varma]: Death was so familiar to the British in India, so quick and so frequent that they hardly

00:20:18.080 --> 00:20:20.440
[Amit Varma]: seemed room for prolonged grief.

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:24.720
[Amit Varma]: If an officer died on campaign, his belongings were auctioned as soon as the funeral was

00:20:24.720 --> 00:20:25.720
[Amit Varma]: over.

00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:29.760
[Amit Varma]: Horses, clothes, revolver, even his cooking pot and his water bottle, stop quote, you

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:33.920
[Amit Varma]: know, and it kind of struck me that back in the day and pandemics weren't obviously the

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:35.400
[Amit Varma]: only threat to life.

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:39.320
[Amit Varma]: It was almost a fact of life that when you are young itself, your friends are going to

00:20:39.320 --> 00:20:40.920
[Amit Varma]: start dying on you.

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:46.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, you have such huge amounts of people and we are possibly one of the few generations,

00:20:46.840 --> 00:20:50.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, over the last few decades that we don't have to kind of deal with this.

00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:55.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, the mortality rate, the average lifespan used to be 25 a few decades ago,

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:59.120
[Amit Varma]: and now it's 70 and we can take certain things for granted.

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:04.360
[Amit Varma]: So in your reading of history, I mean, it seems to me that this then hangs over everything.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:09.360
[Amit Varma]: It hangs over everything that people do, the way they live their lives, the way they behave.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:14.080
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what are your sort of thoughts on this as a historian kind of coming across

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:15.080
[Amit Varma]: this?

00:21:15.080 --> 00:21:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, this layer of sort of likely mortality where, you know, you can't take

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:25.200
[Amit Varma]: long life for granted as we all do, that simply isn't there for most of human history.

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:30.160
[Guest]: You know, before 1920, I mean, this book ends in 1920, because that's the transition point

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:34.240
[Guest]: when you look at India's death data, India's death rate starts falling only after 1920.

00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:38.800
[Guest]: But before 1920 in India, and of course, before certain periods, say 1850s in Britain and

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:44.800
[Guest]: so on, you know, death rates, we're talking of something like 50 per 1000, 5% of the population

00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:45.800
[Guest]: dying every year.

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:46.800
[Guest]: Now, those are very, very high numbers.

00:21:46.800 --> 00:21:51.240
[Guest]: That's about 10 times higher than what we are living with today, right?

00:21:51.240 --> 00:21:54.640
[Guest]: And the worst part of that death rate is infant mortality, right?

00:21:54.640 --> 00:21:58.760
[Guest]: So it's also the fact that most people who died actually in a year were actually small

00:21:58.760 --> 00:22:02.880
[Guest]: kids, which is also a great achievement of the last 100 years of getting you know, those

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:03.960
[Guest]: rates down.

00:22:03.960 --> 00:22:08.680
[Guest]: So for example, when I walked around this South Park Street Cemetery in Calcutta, you

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:10.320
[Guest]: see these tombs, right?

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:12.920
[Guest]: And when you walk past them, you think, okay, these are the guys who've died.

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:16.840
[Guest]: And when you look at the data, 20% of those deaths were actually kids.

00:22:16.840 --> 00:22:18.360
[Guest]: So they're actually buried out there.

00:22:18.360 --> 00:22:22.200
[Guest]: But you don't really think when you walk in a cemetery of kids who died in such large

00:22:22.200 --> 00:22:23.200
[Guest]: numbers.

00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:24.640
[Guest]: And that's pretty much human history.

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:27.360
[Guest]: You know, there are theories that say, you know, you know, there's some bad periods and

00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:28.360
[Guest]: so on.

00:22:28.360 --> 00:22:31.880
[Guest]: But all the evidence is pointing out that there's no real epoch in human history where

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:34.320
[Guest]: people live for 100 years and so on.

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:37.480
[Guest]: I mean, of course, you have few individuals, you know, who live for a long time, like in

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:41.720
[Guest]: the age of pandemics, the two people who, you know, live for nearly 100 years coinciding

00:22:41.720 --> 00:22:45.280
[Guest]: with the period I'm mentioning is Dada Bhai Naoroji, you know, Dinyar Patel has a nice

00:22:45.280 --> 00:22:46.280
[Guest]: book on this.

00:22:46.280 --> 00:22:49.920
[Guest]: But he survives the entire age of pandemics, you know, it's perfectly his life is just

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:50.920
[Guest]: about that.

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:53.000
[Guest]: He dies in a year or two before influenza, you know.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.160
[Guest]: So but almost 90 plus years in that period.

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:56.920
[Guest]: The other one is Florence Nightingale.

00:22:56.920 --> 00:22:58.840
[Guest]: She also lives for almost 100 years.

00:22:58.840 --> 00:22:59.840
[Guest]: So these are outliers.

00:22:59.840 --> 00:23:05.840
[Guest]: But the average person, you know, cannot expect to live more than 25 years in India.

00:23:05.840 --> 00:23:10.240
[Guest]: So there's even this concept of a grandparent, you know, obviously, people are marrying young,

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:13.440
[Guest]: so you're becoming potentially grandparents at the age of 40 or 50.

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:14.960
[Guest]: But you don't live that long.

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:19.480
[Guest]: So it's this whole notion that, you know, today we can see our grandparents and so on.

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:21.840
[Guest]: It's a very modern day concept.

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:23.040
[Guest]: Because mortality was so high.

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:24.040
[Guest]: And why was it so high?

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:28.160
[Guest]: Of course, like I mentioned, you know, there's war, there are these other things, but fundamentally

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:29.160
[Guest]: epidemics.

00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:30.160
[Guest]: Right.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:31.880
[Guest]: And so the big killers of history is Malaria.

00:23:31.880 --> 00:23:35.960
[Guest]: Okay, so in India, at least, you know, more people have died from malaria than probably

00:23:35.960 --> 00:23:37.600
[Guest]: anything else.

00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:42.320
[Guest]: But then you had these chance epidemics like cholera, or, you know, plague and influenza,

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:44.320
[Guest]: which we call as pandemics.

00:23:44.320 --> 00:23:49.560
[Guest]: But then variety of other things, you know, diarrhea, then tuberculosis, you know, a big

00:23:49.560 --> 00:23:51.120
[Guest]: killer.

00:23:51.120 --> 00:23:56.920
[Guest]: And ultimately, all of this is linked with nutrition, you know, the healthier we are,

00:23:56.920 --> 00:24:00.520
[Guest]: even if there was plague, you could survive it, to a certain extent.

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:06.120
[Guest]: So at the base of mortality is how well are you eating food as simple as that.

00:24:06.120 --> 00:24:10.600
[Guest]: And in a world where you had famines, where your whole economy was completely rain fed

00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:15.640
[Guest]: or, you know, rain dependent, especially in India, a slight sort of, you know, bad rainfall

00:24:15.640 --> 00:24:17.800
[Guest]: meant people would start starving.

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:21.800
[Guest]: And even if you're not going to die out of complete starvation, the disease would act

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:23.200
[Guest]: upon under nutrition.

00:24:23.200 --> 00:24:26.680
[Guest]: And that has huge salience today, you know, because we're saying that, you know, this

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:31.360
[Guest]: is the year where the average Indian has actually got poorer nutrition, even the latest data

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:34.800
[Guest]: suggests kind of, you know, not so great.

00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:38.520
[Guest]: What it means is that if you don't get your basic nutrition levels up, there's always

00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:42.680
[Guest]: going to be a, you know, this impact of infectious disease is going to be that much more.

00:24:42.680 --> 00:24:45.880
[Guest]: And that is why it was so, so stark, you know, before 1920.

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:50.320
[Guest]: So after 1920, it improved precisely because nutrition kind of improved a little bit, but

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:54.760
[Guest]: also because the better control of, you know, certain diseases, which, and that's, I would

00:24:54.760 --> 00:24:59.280
[Guest]: say, you know, the great achievement of the last hundred years is precisely this, what

00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:04.760
[Guest]: Angus Deaton calls the great escape, you know, this rise in well-being, really life expectancy,

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:09.840
[Guest]: the fact that people can live, you know, for almost 70 years now in India, the life expectancy

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:14.800
[Guest]: at birth compared to it being 25 and falling, you know, for some years in the early 20th

00:25:14.800 --> 00:25:18.920
[Guest]: century is the remarkable achievement of modern science.

00:25:18.920 --> 00:25:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And is it fair to say that, you know, the 19th century in a sense was the period that

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:29.720
[Amit Varma]: you write off, in fact, specifically 1817 to 1920, almost as such is like, if you were

00:25:29.720 --> 00:25:34.480
[Amit Varma]: pandemics personified, you would think that this is an optimal time for you to exist.

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:38.360
[Amit Varma]: Because on the one hand, you suddenly have globalization and travel everywhere.

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:40.640
[Amit Varma]: So all of these things can spread.

00:25:40.640 --> 00:25:44.520
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, modern medicine hasn't yet caught up with all of this.

00:25:44.520 --> 00:25:48.760
[Amit Varma]: And it is in that sweet spot where these things they're spreading faster than ever.

00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:53.040
[Amit Varma]: But science hasn't figured out what is causing them, leave alone how to cure them.

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:54.040
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:56.880
[Guest]: Like think about the railways, you know, so much fascination with the railways.

00:25:56.880 --> 00:26:01.200
[Guest]: And that obviously, any transport, I mean, one link between my first book and the second

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:04.600
[Guest]: book is that, you know, you cannot have a pandemic without some migration.

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:07.680
[Guest]: I mean, that's the link between pandemics and migration.

00:26:07.680 --> 00:26:12.120
[Guest]: And there's no doubt that obviously, some transport would have, you know, carried out,

00:26:12.120 --> 00:26:17.000
[Guest]: you know, these infectious diseases, though, having said that, even some of these diseases

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.560
[Guest]: also travel just by, you know, when people are walking.

00:26:19.560 --> 00:26:24.400
[Guest]: So it's not that you had to have modern transport to have a pandemic in the first place.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:27.480
[Guest]: But let's take railways, you know, people are fascinated by the railways.

00:26:27.480 --> 00:26:31.840
[Guest]: But at the same time, over time, as these diseases intensified, there was no doubt that,

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:35.920
[Guest]: you know, there was some sort of negative fallout because of the railways in spreading

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:36.920
[Guest]: diseases.

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:40.760
[Guest]: So you're absolutely right, this globalization, all the things which are celebrated in the

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:41.760
[Guest]: 19th century, right?

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:44.160
[Guest]: I mean, this is the birth of the modern world.

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:47.600
[Guest]: One of the reasons this book, you know, I mentioned this in the first chapter, you have

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:50.680
[Guest]: on the one hand, say, Christopher Billy's The Birth of the Modern World, this is a grand

00:26:50.680 --> 00:26:54.840
[Guest]: project of, you know, the rise of the modern world between 1789, the French Revolution

00:26:54.840 --> 00:26:59.720
[Guest]: and 1914, First World War, then you have the Eric Hobsbawm series, you know, Age of Empire,

00:26:59.720 --> 00:27:02.880
[Guest]: Age of Capital, and, you know, all these grandstanding books.

00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:07.200
[Guest]: And yet both these series don't or because they're Eurocentric, you know, most of that

00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:12.000
[Guest]: stuff is comes from a European view, epidemics and pandemics are really not part of that

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:13.000
[Guest]: story.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.000
[Guest]: Right.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.240
[Guest]: And that's one of the things, if you wrote European history of the 14th century, you

00:27:16.240 --> 00:27:19.040
[Guest]: would have to talk about the plague, the Black Death.

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:23.700
[Guest]: And so this is where actually this book comes in, because it's pitched at this idea that

00:27:23.700 --> 00:27:28.480
[Guest]: this is an age of pandemics, pandemics affect, of course, most parts of the world, but it

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:35.280
[Guest]: had a disproportionate impact on Asia, and within Asia, disproportionate impact on India.

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:40.440
[Guest]: And that is why this overall century of progress seen from the Western prism, you know, America

00:27:40.440 --> 00:27:41.440
[Guest]: is surging ahead.

00:27:41.440 --> 00:27:45.200
[Guest]: You know, they go from a population of something like five to 10 million to 100 million by

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:47.080
[Guest]: the end of this time period.

00:27:47.080 --> 00:27:48.080
[Guest]: Europe is surging ahead.

00:27:48.080 --> 00:27:51.520
[Guest]: And typically the Indian views, you know, colonialism kind of dented India's prospects

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:52.520
[Guest]: and so on.

00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:56.440
[Guest]: Actually, what this book is arguing is that pandemics was also a constraining factor.

00:27:56.440 --> 00:28:00.080
[Guest]: The fact that we could not do business in the first place as much as what the West could

00:28:00.080 --> 00:28:03.040
[Guest]: do was because we had these pandemics in the first place.

00:28:03.040 --> 00:28:07.000
[Guest]: It's actually right, you know, this is an interesting period of history, because on

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:11.280
[Guest]: the one hand, there's this dramatic revolution, what we call is the first and second Industrial

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:12.560
[Guest]: Revolution.

00:28:12.560 --> 00:28:16.040
[Guest]: And yet, on the other hand, you have this, you know, massive spread of diseases.

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:18.680
[Guest]: And the West is continuously concerned, you know, when you see what they're talking about

00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:23.780
[Guest]: cholera plague, the memory of them is the Black Death, you know, it's a memory which

00:28:23.780 --> 00:28:26.540
[Guest]: stays on for five centuries or six centuries.

00:28:26.540 --> 00:28:29.600
[Guest]: And they don't want that to happen, because the Black Death, you know, wiped out one third

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:34.080
[Guest]: of Europe by most estimates, which is a huge percentage, you know, one third of a big region

00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:35.880
[Guest]: as Europe dying out.

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:39.800
[Guest]: And so why the Black Death had registered in the European consciousness, somehow this

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:44.760
[Guest]: period 1817 to 1920, it's kind of completely escaped memory, you know, it's not really

00:28:44.760 --> 00:28:46.720
[Guest]: even recorded well in our history.

00:28:46.720 --> 00:28:49.600
[Guest]: And that's one of the reasons why the book was written.

00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:53.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the things that struck me, and I had no idea that, you know, that it

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:57.920
[Amit Varma]: would be the case to this extent, that pandemics actually shaped our history, like, as we'll

00:28:57.920 --> 00:29:02.880
[Amit Varma]: go on to discuss in detail, each of the three pandemics that you talked about, obviously,

00:29:02.880 --> 00:29:08.200
[Amit Varma]: changed economics and society, but also had a massive impact on politics, especially the

00:29:08.200 --> 00:29:12.400
[Amit Varma]: plague, you know, we keep reading about the battle between the extremists and the moderates

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:13.400
[Amit Varma]: in the Congress.

00:29:13.400 --> 00:29:18.320
[Amit Varma]: But it was, you know, the plague had a big part in that coming about, which was quite

00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:19.320
[Amit Varma]: surprising to me.

00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:22.800
[Amit Varma]: And you also kind of point out how during this period, you know, which is sometimes

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:27.400
[Amit Varma]: called the Great Divergence, because this is where Asia's share of world GDP falls from

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:29.480
[Amit Varma]: like 50% to 20%.

00:29:29.480 --> 00:29:34.040
[Amit Varma]: And what you point out is that during this time, mainly because of these pandemics, Asia's

00:29:34.040 --> 00:29:39.760
[Amit Varma]: population, share of the world population also fell from 65 to 50, which obviously,

00:29:39.760 --> 00:29:45.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, had a role in that fall in GDP as well, and is a major part and yet you're right,

00:29:45.080 --> 00:29:49.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, whatever histories I have read of these times in these periods, and especially

00:29:49.080 --> 00:29:53.160
[Amit Varma]: of India, you know, historians will hardly mention all of this.

00:29:53.160 --> 00:29:58.560
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like in our everyday lives, we kind of take disease for granted, like I just

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:02.920
[Amit Varma]: recorded an episode yesterday, which will actually release after yours, in which my

00:30:02.920 --> 00:30:08.880
[Amit Varma]: guest pointed out that every day America is losing as many people to COVID-19 as they

00:30:08.880 --> 00:30:10.560
[Amit Varma]: lost during 9-11.

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:16.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, and yet one is so incredibly visible, and the other is, you know, it gets normalized

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:17.360
[Amit Varma]: very fast.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:20.200
[Amit Varma]: And it is not one big event, which makes for great television.

00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:23.080
[Amit Varma]: So it kind of just gets lost.

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:28.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, early in the book, you point out about, you know, your two core arguments during

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:30.960
[Amit Varma]: the book, and you've actually elaborated on them in the last few minutes.

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And one is that, you know, you want to place these pandemics in the global historiography,

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:40.240
[Amit Varma]: as you put it, for a layperson like me, you know, what do you mean by global historiography?

00:30:40.240 --> 00:30:44.080
[Amit Varma]: Like, is what you're saying that, you know, the historical narratives that have emerged

00:30:44.080 --> 00:30:49.800
[Amit Varma]: of the grand themes that shape society have to perforce to speak about these pandemics?

00:30:49.800 --> 00:30:50.800
[Guest]: Is that what you mean?

00:30:50.800 --> 00:30:51.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:30:51.800 --> 00:30:54.800
[Guest]: So global historiography is used by historians, it's another way of saying the narrative,

00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:55.800
[Guest]: right?

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:59.280
[Guest]: So for example, what is the, you know, what is the most important thing that we remember

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:01.640
[Guest]: of say, the 1700s of India, right?

00:31:01.640 --> 00:31:04.800
[Guest]: And it's about this tussle between the Mughals and this disintegration.

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:10.200
[Guest]: So that's the historiography, Mughal decline, East India Company ascent, and the Marathas.

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:13.720
[Guest]: This is probably the defining historiography of this period.

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:18.120
[Guest]: Now, if somebody comes and tells you that, look, this is happening, yes, but there's

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:19.120
[Guest]: something else.

00:31:19.120 --> 00:31:24.280
[Guest]: There were actually, hypothetically, five major earthquakes, which hit the 1700s, which

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:26.200
[Guest]: actually nobody's talked about right now.

00:31:26.200 --> 00:31:28.720
[Guest]: And it's actually those earthquakes, which tilted the balance of power between these

00:31:28.720 --> 00:31:29.720
[Guest]: three things.

00:31:29.720 --> 00:31:33.560
[Guest]: You know, that's the kind of stuff I think, which what this book is doing, that is, there

00:31:33.560 --> 00:31:36.920
[Guest]: is certain things which actually happened, you know, I'm not inventing these diseases,

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:41.600
[Guest]: they happen, you know, all these people died, unfortunately, in large numbers.

00:31:41.600 --> 00:31:48.080
[Guest]: Yet the dominant narrative of the 19th century, right, in the West is one of ascendancy, right?

00:31:48.080 --> 00:31:49.800
[Guest]: It is one of empire building.

00:31:49.800 --> 00:31:55.600
[Guest]: So imperialism, as one is in nationalism, another one, right, globalization.

00:31:55.600 --> 00:31:59.680
[Guest]: This is a period, especially from the 1850s onwards, massive trade to GDP ratios start

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:00.680
[Guest]: rising.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:04.680
[Guest]: We're at city building, urbanization, right?

00:32:04.680 --> 00:32:06.880
[Guest]: So these are, this is the historiography.

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:09.960
[Guest]: So when we talk of global history, of course, this is not happening all around the world,

00:32:09.960 --> 00:32:12.560
[Guest]: but this is happening in the West, right?

00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:16.280
[Guest]: And I would say that the major historiography of the 19th century is imperialism, right?

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:20.200
[Guest]: Because this is a time when empires really grow, and by the late 19th century, even Africa

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:24.600
[Guest]: is almost completely colonized after this, you know, Berlin conference and so on.

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:29.600
[Guest]: So in this whole value, if you have to look at especially India, let's start with India,

00:32:29.600 --> 00:32:32.640
[Guest]: the historiography is one of British ascendancy, right?

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:35.360
[Guest]: So 19th century as a world of British ascendancy.

00:32:35.360 --> 00:32:40.880
[Guest]: And what I'm arguing is actually that the sort of an important event running through

00:32:40.880 --> 00:32:43.480
[Guest]: this thing is pandemics.

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:48.240
[Guest]: Now it is true that they did not actually use the word pandemics in the 19th century.

00:32:48.240 --> 00:32:51.420
[Guest]: The word pandemic out of these three diseases really applies to influenza.

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:56.320
[Guest]: So if you see the Indian government reports, the pandemic word comes for influenza, play

00:32:56.320 --> 00:32:57.920
[Guest]: people are using it, but not so much.

00:32:57.920 --> 00:33:01.000
[Guest]: So the operative word is epidemics, right?

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:05.560
[Guest]: But one way of actually seeing the 19th century, the historiography is actually that people

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:06.560
[Guest]: are really scared.

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:09.560
[Guest]: Of course, they're scared of each other, fighting wars and so on, but they're really scared

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:11.160
[Guest]: of diseases.

00:33:11.160 --> 00:33:14.360
[Guest]: And new diseases, which they have no clue about.

00:33:14.360 --> 00:33:18.680
[Guest]: So one way of saying is, you know, and why this particular period, you know, I'm trying

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:23.440
[Guest]: to make this argument in this book, you can say death rates were always high before 1920.

00:33:23.440 --> 00:33:27.360
[Guest]: One of the things I'm pointing out is that actually death rates started increasing.

00:33:27.360 --> 00:33:30.160
[Guest]: Even from those high death rates, you know, they started actually increasing towards the

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:32.680
[Guest]: late 19th century.

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:35.960
[Guest]: And that, you know, a lot of political events actually were shaped.

00:33:35.960 --> 00:33:39.240
[Guest]: Much of the book also talks about, you know, important political events, which was shaped

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:41.200
[Guest]: by these pandemics itself.

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:46.360
[Guest]: So what I want to do in this book is to give a more central role for pandemics in global

00:33:46.360 --> 00:33:47.680
[Guest]: history.

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:51.840
[Guest]: It's true that they did not, you know, these pandemics did not kill too many people in

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:56.360
[Guest]: Europe, in North America, but it killed a lot of people in Asia, and it killed a lot

00:33:56.360 --> 00:33:57.920
[Guest]: of people in India.

00:33:57.920 --> 00:34:01.360
[Guest]: So there is really, I mean, even if you think of World War One, you know, it had such few

00:34:01.360 --> 00:34:05.920
[Guest]: casualties outside of Europe, yet we called it, we call it World War One.

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:09.360
[Guest]: You know, there's this word attached to it called world.

00:34:09.360 --> 00:34:13.520
[Guest]: So that's something similar to what I want to do out here, that the fear of this pandemic

00:34:13.520 --> 00:34:14.880
[Guest]: was there throughout the world.

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:18.520
[Guest]: The Americans were concerned about what they call as Indian cholera, just as today they

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:20.420
[Guest]: call it the Chinese virus, you know.

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:26.040
[Guest]: And so around the world, India was also not known just for, you know, the British rule,

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:29.280
[Guest]: but as a source of diseases, like how we look at China today.

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:33.880
[Guest]: And so this kind of also looks at global history in new light, that is different parts of the

00:34:33.880 --> 00:34:38.240
[Guest]: world, so it also impacted geopolitics, that is, you know, how countries were perceiving

00:34:38.240 --> 00:34:39.760
[Guest]: each other.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:42.520
[Guest]: One part of that story was actually epidemics.

00:34:42.520 --> 00:34:44.040
[Guest]: So that's what I mean by historiography.

00:34:44.040 --> 00:34:45.040
[Guest]: What is the narrative?

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:48.920
[Guest]: And the standard narrative right now is imperialism, nationalism, globalization.

00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:52.560
[Guest]: And what I want to argue is that, you know, epidemics was also there in this, in this

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:53.560
[Guest]: picture.

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:58.680
[Guest]: And especially these three pandemics of cholera, plague and influenza, which definitely affected

00:34:58.680 --> 00:34:59.680
[Guest]: India a lot.

00:34:59.680 --> 00:35:04.800
[Guest]: I do have, you know, my subtitle of the book has the word world in it, yet any reader who,

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:08.760
[Guest]: you know, reads this book is going to realize that most of this book is about India.

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:11.760
[Guest]: But I do that because most of the deaths were in India.

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:16.080
[Guest]: But it's a fact that it did touch upon many parts of the world, from Russia, from Egypt,

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:21.040
[Guest]: to even Brazil, where, you know, some part of the population was wiped out.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:24.480
[Guest]: And you know, there's a book, Love in the Time of Cholera, you know, Marquez would not

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:27.480
[Guest]: have written that book if cholera was not such a defining period.

00:35:27.480 --> 00:35:31.920
[Guest]: And cholera emerged from India in at least some, you know, some form or the other.

00:35:31.920 --> 00:35:37.840
[Guest]: So that's the whole idea of putting pandemics in 19th and early 20th century, what historians

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:38.840
[Guest]: call historiography.

00:35:38.840 --> 00:35:44.440
[Amit Varma]: And your other core focus, which you talk about is also the building of collective memory,

00:35:44.440 --> 00:35:49.280
[Amit Varma]: as you put it in the sense that you argued that, you know, quote, the age of pandemics

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:53.440
[Amit Varma]: has been forgotten in the country most affected by it, India, and there is value in remembering

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:58.760
[Amit Varma]: it as a major event, just as the Black Death plague pandemic of the 14th century is registered

00:35:58.760 --> 00:36:01.760
[Amit Varma]: in European consciousness to this day.

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:02.760
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:06.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, at another point where you're talking about the historical context of such

00:36:06.760 --> 00:36:13.320
[Amit Varma]: epidemics, you speak about how in the Arthashastra, you know, Kautilya writes about, you know,

00:36:13.320 --> 00:36:18.400
[Amit Varma]: the four great threats to life, which are war, natural disasters, famines and epidemics.

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:23.680
[Amit Varma]: And yet epidemics is like fourth in his list of priority, and it's not taken so seriously.

00:36:23.680 --> 00:36:24.680
[Amit Varma]: Why do you think that is?

00:36:24.680 --> 00:36:28.360
[Amit Varma]: Why do we forget, you know, 20 million people dying?

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And that too, when it was a, you know, 6.4% of India's population, then, as you point

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:34.680
[Amit Varma]: out, is a big deal.

00:36:34.680 --> 00:36:36.720
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, why do we tend to forget?

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:41.240
[Amit Varma]: Is it because they are individual lives and individual stories, and there's like, no kind

00:36:41.240 --> 00:36:44.680
[Amit Varma]: of mass representation or a grand narrative of that sort?

00:36:44.680 --> 00:36:48.440
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, you know, how is memory, how is any memory preserved?

00:36:48.440 --> 00:36:49.440
[Guest]: One, storytelling.

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:52.440
[Guest]: I mean, why is it that we, you know, still narrate the Mahabharata and Ramayana from

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:55.720
[Guest]: generation to generation, that memory is kept alive.

00:36:55.720 --> 00:37:00.240
[Guest]: Nobody's telling us, you know, narratives of plague and cholera as bedtime stories any

00:37:00.240 --> 00:37:01.240
[Guest]: longer.

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:03.240
[Guest]: One is, of course, that it's negative.

00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:04.240
[Guest]: It's about death.

00:37:04.240 --> 00:37:05.240
[Guest]: So you want to forget it.

00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:06.240
[Guest]: Right.

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:10.160
[Guest]: So that's one attribute of why we don't want to hold on to negative memories and you want

00:37:10.160 --> 00:37:12.440
[Guest]: to hold on to more such positive memories.

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:17.560
[Guest]: Two, there is no identifiable enemy, as with, say, a war, right?

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:23.560
[Guest]: So in a war, or like, you know, look at influenza, you know, 19, April 1919, you had the Jallianwala

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:24.560
[Guest]: Bagh tragedy.

00:37:24.560 --> 00:37:25.560
[Guest]: Right.

00:37:25.560 --> 00:37:26.560
[Guest]: That has been memorialized.

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:29.400
[Guest]: You know, there's, there's a whole thing attached with it.

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:30.400
[Guest]: Right.

00:37:30.400 --> 00:37:33.600
[Guest]: I mean, if you go there today, there's a particular, you know, monument, you have these hundred

00:37:33.600 --> 00:37:35.840
[Guest]: year anniversary events.

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:39.240
[Guest]: Nobody was, you know, commemorating hundred years of influenza, which killed, you know,

00:37:39.240 --> 00:37:40.600
[Guest]: 20 million Indians.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:43.760
[Guest]: But for Jallianwala Bagh tragedy, it killed a few hundred Indians.

00:37:43.760 --> 00:37:46.720
[Guest]: But the, the, the memory is so much stronger.

00:37:46.720 --> 00:37:47.720
[Guest]: Why there's a clear enemy.

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:48.720
[Guest]: Right.

00:37:48.720 --> 00:37:53.840
[Guest]: It was the British in that case, with influenza, you know, H1N1A is not really an enemy the

00:37:53.840 --> 00:37:55.520
[Guest]: public is going to sort of take.

00:37:55.520 --> 00:37:57.640
[Guest]: So clearly identifiable enemies.

00:37:57.640 --> 00:38:04.720
[Guest]: I'd also point out, you know, compared to wars or natural disasters, right, which affect

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:09.400
[Guest]: both capital and labor, that is, it not only kills people, it kills the actual building

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:13.120
[Guest]: and, you know, it, it destroys buildings, it destroys monuments.

00:38:13.120 --> 00:38:18.560
[Guest]: So in historical recording as well, people noted down, you know, the destruction of Rome,

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:21.240
[Guest]: the destruction of Delhi, for example.

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:26.120
[Guest]: Now with an epidemic, you know, the city, the physical stock of the city doesn't fall.

00:38:26.120 --> 00:38:28.440
[Guest]: It's just people kind of withering away in that.

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:31.840
[Guest]: It could be the case that the epidemic sparks a revolution, then there's mayhem in that,

00:38:31.840 --> 00:38:34.480
[Guest]: but otherwise a pure epidemic just takes labor.

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:36.280
[Guest]: It doesn't affect capital.

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:39.100
[Guest]: And that means in historical recording, it's not glamorous enough.

00:38:39.100 --> 00:38:40.100
[Guest]: It's not spectacular.

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:45.040
[Guest]: And so that's why historians often have failed to actually systematically document these

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:46.040
[Guest]: epidemics.

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:50.840
[Guest]: So I think that's one of the reasons, inadequate memorialization.

00:38:50.840 --> 00:38:54.720
[Guest]: So I pointed out, like, if you want to know something about plague and so on, if you look

00:38:54.720 --> 00:38:58.880
[Guest]: closely enough, there might be some markers like the Hafkin Institute in Bombay, you know,

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:04.120
[Guest]: is one memory because Hafkin was this great scientist who was associated with both cholera

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:05.120
[Guest]: and plague in India.

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:08.360
[Guest]: So there's an institute in his honor, but nobody would associate Hafkin with pandemics

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:09.360
[Guest]: and so on today.

00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:14.560
[Guest]: There's a statue in South Bombay of, you know, Vigas, who was the first guy who spotted plague

00:39:14.560 --> 00:39:15.560
[Guest]: in Bombay.

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:21.640
[Guest]: There's a statue, you know, there's a statue, but nobody's really thinking of that statue

00:39:21.640 --> 00:39:27.540
[Guest]: outside of metro cinema as, you know, a memory of the plague back then.

00:39:27.540 --> 00:39:33.920
[Guest]: And so one of the things that might be, you know, useful is, you know, it's an open question

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:38.080
[Guest]: whether we need to have museums on these epidemics or something like that, but definitely it

00:39:38.080 --> 00:39:39.080
[Guest]: has to be taught.

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:43.760
[Guest]: You know, I feel it has to be taught in our history curriculums in the sense and especially

00:39:43.760 --> 00:39:44.760
[Unknown]: in medical schools.

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:48.920
[Guest]: You know, and what I'm really amazed is that this is not being taught in medical schools.

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:49.920
[Guest]: Right.

00:39:49.920 --> 00:39:50.920
[Guest]: So, okay.

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:55.120
[Guest]: You know, there's a straw man argument that, you know, just because, you know, we say that,

00:39:55.120 --> 00:39:57.560
[Guest]: you know, this is not taught to us in history.

00:39:57.560 --> 00:40:00.560
[Guest]: I have my sympathies with people who write history textbooks because simply put, we cannot

00:40:00.560 --> 00:40:01.840
[Guest]: put everything in the textbook.

00:40:01.840 --> 00:40:03.800
[Guest]: You know, some things have to be left out.

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:04.800
[Guest]: So, okay.

00:40:04.800 --> 00:40:07.400
[Guest]: You don't want to put this history in classical textbooks, that's fine.

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:11.520
[Guest]: But medical students, they have to be exposed to this idea that India went through this

00:40:11.520 --> 00:40:14.000
[Guest]: massive, you know, episode once.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:17.280
[Guest]: And it should definitely inspire them to not only research the past, but also use some

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:19.600
[Guest]: of those lessons, you know, for today.

00:40:19.600 --> 00:40:20.600
[Guest]: So memory is important.

00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:23.840
[Guest]: And that's what the book is trying to push, that we need to build collective memory, not

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:28.040
[Guest]: only of our past, you know, major pandemics, and that can happen in multiple ways.

00:40:28.040 --> 00:40:31.960
[Guest]: For example, so many health officials in the last 40 years, you know, have devoted their

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:36.480
[Guest]: lives to eradicating polio, for example, before that smallpox.

00:40:36.480 --> 00:40:39.240
[Guest]: They should write their autobiographies, or they should write their memoirs, you know,

00:40:39.240 --> 00:40:43.920
[Guest]: because that would be of tremendous, you know, use for public health people going forward

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:47.560
[Guest]: as to how did we manage to eradicate polio, that was such a great success story.

00:40:47.560 --> 00:40:50.160
[Guest]: So there need to be books written on that, for example.

00:40:50.160 --> 00:40:55.360
[Guest]: So if not movies, and that's expecting too much, you know, or even like a day of the

00:40:55.360 --> 00:41:00.040
[Guest]: year to remember, you know, contributions of nurses, doctors, police people, mortuary

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:01.320
[Guest]: workers and so on.

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:06.320
[Guest]: I think just basic introduction of some of these themes in curricula will help, you know,

00:41:06.320 --> 00:41:11.400
[Guest]: that's the grand hope of this book, that some of this gets picked up in history textbooks,

00:41:11.400 --> 00:41:14.600
[Guest]: if not the main cluster in history textbook, you know, at least medical school textbooks,

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:19.080
[Guest]: or at least be taught as a course in medical schools, that this is, you know, an important

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:20.080
[Guest]: aspect of this.

00:41:20.080 --> 00:41:24.280
[Guest]: Because I can tell you, in Europe, kids grow up knowing what is the Black Death.

00:41:24.280 --> 00:41:29.320
[Guest]: Black Death is now an interesting event in general history, right?

00:41:29.320 --> 00:41:32.200
[Guest]: And I think this period demands such attention.

00:41:32.200 --> 00:41:35.320
[Guest]: Because for us, this period is just about British rule, you know, and I think there's

00:41:35.320 --> 00:41:39.880
[Guest]: something something beyond British rule, which, in fact, took many more lives than British

00:41:39.880 --> 00:41:40.880
[Guest]: rule themselves.

00:41:40.880 --> 00:41:41.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:41:41.880 --> 00:41:45.680
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, one of the things that kind of, again, struck me about your book

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:50.720
[Amit Varma]: is that, you know, what we sort of have a vague idea of how the Black Death and how

00:41:50.720 --> 00:41:55.760
[Amit Varma]: plagues shaped, you know, European history, in a sense, you know, the three pandemics

00:41:55.760 --> 00:42:00.000
[Amit Varma]: of these hundred years, it's a similar thing to India, for example, in Europe, you talk

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:04.680
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, the Black Death, court is said to have had consequences that are open

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:08.600
[Amit Varma]: to debate, such as laying the foundation for the rise of Europe, the Renaissance movement,

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:13.080
[Amit Varma]: the Protestant Reformation, and even accelerating anti semitism, stop court.

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And later, you talk about all the different consequences at that time, like inequality,

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:21.320
[Amit Varma]: like in northern Europe, more women went into the workforce.

00:42:21.320 --> 00:42:25.440
[Amit Varma]: And of course, anti semitism continued rising because Jews were blamed for the pandemic

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:30.580
[Amit Varma]: in court, Aragon, Provence, Catalonia, Switzerland, Rhineland, and southern Germany.

00:42:30.580 --> 00:42:35.600
[Amit Varma]: So you have these major sort of trends happening and the pandemic played a part in that.

00:42:35.600 --> 00:42:40.920
[Amit Varma]: Was it kind of a surprise to you to realize the extent of the role that pandemic played

00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:41.920
[Amit Varma]: in history?

00:42:41.920 --> 00:42:44.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, at one point in your book, you write about how while researching your

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:49.280
[Amit Varma]: previous book, you put together this map, tell me a little bit about that map.

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:53.120
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you point to it as a sort of a moment of revelation.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:55.960
[Amit Varma]: Was there kind of more to it than that?

00:42:55.960 --> 00:42:59.600
[Amit Varma]: And did some of it perhaps come after you had started work on the book?

00:42:59.600 --> 00:43:04.720
[Guest]: Yeah, no, you know, that map that you're referring to, it's a simple district level map of India,

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:10.040
[Guest]: which shows population growth rates between 1911 and 1921.

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:14.880
[Guest]: So on this particular map, when I, you know, drew this population growth rate map, it was

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:19.360
[Guest]: really stuck because most of India actually registered negative, you know, growth rates.

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:23.320
[Guest]: So it wasn't like one region pulling down the overall population growth, that most of

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:28.840
[Guest]: India, that one decade, you know, I plotted these maps from 1901 to now, every decade.

00:43:28.840 --> 00:43:31.320
[Guest]: So they were about 10 or 11 maps.

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:32.880
[Guest]: And they were all positive growth rates.

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:36.140
[Guest]: And this one decade, the population of India fell, right.

00:43:36.140 --> 00:43:37.680
[Guest]: And there's no doubt as to why that happened.

00:43:37.680 --> 00:43:40.080
[Guest]: It was the influence of 1918.

00:43:40.080 --> 00:43:44.360
[Guest]: And when I looked at that map, you know, I said, how is it that there's no book on this?

00:43:44.360 --> 00:43:46.840
[Guest]: This was back then, you know, in 2012.

00:43:46.840 --> 00:43:50.520
[Guest]: And out of interest, I read, there's one or two research papers, since then, Siddharth

00:43:50.520 --> 00:43:54.840
[Guest]: Chandra is a health economist, he's done some work, interesting work on it.

00:43:54.840 --> 00:43:58.880
[Guest]: But very, I mean, you can count in single digits, you know, the amount of research done

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:01.600
[Guest]: in on influenza in India.

00:44:01.600 --> 00:44:03.560
[Guest]: And it was a big mystery.

00:44:03.560 --> 00:44:07.280
[Guest]: But I didn't follow it up back then, because I got more interested in migration.

00:44:07.280 --> 00:44:10.360
[Guest]: And that's what I worked on for most part of the last decade.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:14.600
[Guest]: And that kind of map really came back, when I was in looking at these, you know, mortality

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:20.000
[Guest]: statistics in March, I literally went back to the map, and kind of started exploring.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:23.240
[Guest]: In fact, you know, one of the things which is coming out with the book, as I mentioned,

00:44:23.240 --> 00:44:24.440
[Guest]: is a supplement.

00:44:24.440 --> 00:44:28.680
[Guest]: And the supplement has, so how can I say that India lost 20 million people in influenza?

00:44:28.680 --> 00:44:34.120
[Guest]: In fact, this is now my estimate, based on a certain method, which I'm using to calculate,

00:44:34.120 --> 00:44:35.120
[Guest]: you know, influenza losses.

00:44:35.120 --> 00:44:38.160
[Guest]: So that's going to come out in a supplement in the coming week.

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:42.440
[Guest]: And what I do out there is look, again, you know, at this district level data, and kind

00:44:42.440 --> 00:44:45.160
[Guest]: of estimate the population shortfall.

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:47.120
[Guest]: So there's a lot of regulatory movements.

00:44:47.120 --> 00:44:50.640
[Guest]: And this idea that, you know, pandemics, like you mentioned, the Black Death, they can have

00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:51.640
[Guest]: consequences.

00:44:51.640 --> 00:44:55.600
[Guest]: So throughout this book, I was trying to understand, no, influenza happened, 20 million people

00:44:55.600 --> 00:44:58.240
[Guest]: die, there must be some consequences.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:02.720
[Guest]: And at least one debate, interestingly, took place by two great economists, you know, Theodore

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:04.440
[Guest]: Schultz and Amartya Sen.

00:45:04.440 --> 00:45:06.640
[Guest]: And this was in 1967.

00:45:06.640 --> 00:45:10.520
[Guest]: And they had a debate, this was, both of them eventually won the Nobel Prizes.

00:45:10.520 --> 00:45:13.320
[Guest]: But they actually had a debate on the impact of influenza on India.

00:45:13.320 --> 00:45:17.160
[Guest]: They had this debate on, is there surplus labor in Indian agriculture or not?

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:20.920
[Guest]: So the idea being, you know, if so many people die out, can agricultural productivity still

00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:21.920
[Guest]: hold?

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:23.400
[Guest]: And so it's a very interesting debate that they had back then.

00:45:23.400 --> 00:45:26.640
[Guest]: There's some now research on influenza and, you know, its impact.

00:45:26.640 --> 00:45:30.480
[Guest]: But throughout the book, there's some which I definitely believe had a massive impact.

00:45:30.480 --> 00:45:33.920
[Guest]: Now, we can talk about that labor movements and so on.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:38.000
[Guest]: But there's some also, which I talk, call a speculative, as of now, in the realm of

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:42.360
[Guest]: speculation as to, you know, what was the impact, what are the consequences of this

00:45:42.360 --> 00:45:44.960
[Guest]: pandemic, you know, going forward.

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:48.200
[Guest]: And one of them, which I'm very excited about, and I hope to do more research on, is that

00:45:48.200 --> 00:45:49.880
[Guest]: it really changes India's urban trajectory.

00:45:49.880 --> 00:45:54.320
[Guest]: You know, these pandemics have a disproportionate impact on cities in North India.

00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:58.600
[Guest]: And we know for a fact that what are some of the largest cities of India in, you know,

00:45:58.600 --> 00:46:01.600
[Guest]: in the early 20th century were Lucknow, Inhabad, and so on.

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:04.480
[Guest]: And they are nowhere on India's urban landscape today.

00:46:04.480 --> 00:46:10.200
[Guest]: So a potential reason for this relative decline of, you know, some dynamic cities of the early

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:12.840
[Guest]: 20th century was actually pandemics.

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:16.000
[Guest]: So that's one of the sort of, you know, just like people say Renaissance is because of

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.000
[Guest]: Black Death.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:19.700
[Guest]: These are big questions, you know, big sort of grand theories.

00:46:19.700 --> 00:46:20.700
[Guest]: But interesting hypothesis.

00:46:20.700 --> 00:46:23.920
[Guest]: I don't think anybody's really got the data right now to prove them.

00:46:23.920 --> 00:46:24.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:46:24.920 --> 00:46:28.840
[Amit Varma]: And I guess there are never like absolute answers like, yes, this caused the Renaissance.

00:46:28.840 --> 00:46:30.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, everything is multifactorial.

00:46:30.880 --> 00:46:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And this stuff kind of plays into all of that.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:37.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of now, you know, begin with the narrative of the book.

00:46:37.240 --> 00:46:39.320
[Amit Varma]: And let's talk about cholera.

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:46.320
[Amit Varma]: But before we talk about cholera, give me a context of, you know, what 1817 is like,

00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:47.960
[Amit Varma]: give me a context of the time.

00:46:47.960 --> 00:46:52.800
[Amit Varma]: Like we know that the East India Company rules less than a third of the landmass of the subcontinent.

00:46:52.800 --> 00:46:58.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, Calcutta, Bombay and Madras are your key sites of commerce, as you point out.

00:46:58.120 --> 00:47:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Your publishers HarperCollins are formed in that year, effectively.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.840
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sort of a context of what is the world like?

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Are people traveling?

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:06.920
[Amit Varma]: What is trade like?

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:09.160
[Amit Varma]: What are the kind of lives people live?

00:47:09.160 --> 00:47:14.040
[Amit Varma]: So we can then sort of look at the ground on which, you know, everything begins.

00:47:14.040 --> 00:47:15.040
[Guest]: Sure.

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:17.200
[Guest]: The first thing to note is that there's no railways, right?

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:21.520
[Guest]: That's a big part which happens post 1825, and it really comes to the UK.

00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:25.640
[Guest]: So this is a world with no railways, where, like the earlier 2000 years, the fastest way

00:47:25.640 --> 00:47:29.680
[Guest]: to get across the subcontinent is the speed of the horse, or you could, you know, go down

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:34.360
[Guest]: the Ganga in terms of waterborne navigation, which is still highly prevalent.

00:47:34.360 --> 00:47:38.960
[Guest]: This is a world where movement and migration is happening a bit, but movement, a lot of

00:47:38.960 --> 00:47:40.800
[Guest]: it is happening for pilgrimages.

00:47:40.800 --> 00:47:44.400
[Guest]: And these are large scale pilgrimages, people going in large groups across the subcontinent

00:47:44.400 --> 00:47:48.880
[Guest]: across and which are the major pilgrimage centers, but they continue to be the major

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:52.560
[Guest]: ones today, whether it's Tirupati in the south, or Haridwar in the north, and, you know, different

00:47:52.560 --> 00:47:53.560
[Guest]: places and Mecca.

00:47:53.560 --> 00:47:58.880
[Guest]: So many people from India actually making this journey to Mecca, even in 1817.

00:47:58.880 --> 00:48:02.120
[Guest]: They were around 1 billion human beings in 1817.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:05.160
[Guest]: So today the population is, you know, seven times more than that.

00:48:05.160 --> 00:48:09.080
[Guest]: And about 60% of that was in India and China, you know, so about 400 million in China and

00:48:09.080 --> 00:48:11.320
[Guest]: more than 200 million in India.

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:16.840
[Guest]: And the population of US in 1817 was about the size of Calcutta today, right?

00:48:16.840 --> 00:48:22.360
[Guest]: So it's literally nothing in 1817, everything, I mean, think of American history, you know,

00:48:22.360 --> 00:48:26.360
[Guest]: it really starts off in terms of some demography by the late 19th century, when there's this

00:48:26.360 --> 00:48:28.920
[Guest]: mass transatlantic migration.

00:48:28.920 --> 00:48:33.400
[Guest]: But before that, it's a really tiny sort of Republic, we have the slave trade still on

00:48:33.400 --> 00:48:38.040
[Guest]: in some pockets, but there's growing pressure to quash the slave trade.

00:48:38.040 --> 00:48:42.720
[Guest]: In India, the British, the East India Company is on the rise.

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:43.720
[Guest]: But it's only in 1818.

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:47.000
[Guest]: So 1817, they've still not managed to defeat the Marathas.

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:51.040
[Guest]: So that is also in balance of, you know, this tentatively sort of poised, but they've got

00:48:51.040 --> 00:48:55.360
[Guest]: the East India Company does operate through these three ports of Bombay, Madras, and Calcutta,

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:57.000
[Guest]: which are doing fairly well.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:01.400
[Guest]: And the Ottoman Empire is there, but it's not doing, you know, too well.

00:49:01.400 --> 00:49:05.320
[Guest]: There's a guy called Muhammad Ali Pasha, who's rising up in Egypt.

00:49:05.320 --> 00:49:08.400
[Guest]: There's the Saud dynasty in Arabia, there's the Qing dynasty in China, they've not yet

00:49:08.400 --> 00:49:09.400
[Guest]: fought the Opium War.

00:49:09.400 --> 00:49:13.880
[Guest]: So China, that's still a proud imperial sort of, you know, rulers in that time, there's

00:49:13.880 --> 00:49:16.160
[Guest]: the Qajar dynasty in Persia.

00:49:16.160 --> 00:49:19.680
[Guest]: And as you pointed out, you know, Harper Collins, or Harper Brothers, as they were called the

00:49:19.680 --> 00:49:25.480
[Guest]: publisher of this book, also started in 1817, just a coincidence out there.

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:26.800
[Amit Varma]: So this is this is really the background.

00:49:26.800 --> 00:49:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:32.960
[Amit Varma]: So it's a book on pandemics arising out of what happened in the pandemic year, essentially.

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:36.320
[Amit Varma]: And you know, cholera is not something new, you've pointed out in your book about how

00:49:36.320 --> 00:49:40.600
[Amit Varma]: it had, in fact, been in what we today call India, even as you know, long before this

00:49:40.600 --> 00:49:46.040
[Amit Varma]: in 1543, where, you know, it was there in Portuguese ruled Goa, where they had a rule

00:49:46.040 --> 00:49:49.640
[Amit Varma]: that okay, every time somebody dies, we shall have a ringing of the bells.

00:49:49.640 --> 00:49:53.720
[Amit Varma]: And then so many people started dying that it became a cacophony, and they kind of had

00:49:53.720 --> 00:49:55.360
[Amit Varma]: to put an end to it.

00:49:55.360 --> 00:50:01.160
[Amit Varma]: And you've spoken about how in 1757, Ahmad Shah Durrani's army was affected by it in 1783,

00:50:01.160 --> 00:50:03.880
[Amit Varma]: 20,000 people died in Haridwar, and all of that.

00:50:03.880 --> 00:50:07.320
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about cholera, like what is cholera?

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:09.680
[Amit Varma]: What was known about it at the time?

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:12.960
[Amit Varma]: What sort of, you know, happens when one gets cholera?

00:50:12.960 --> 00:50:14.960
[Amit Varma]: How fast does it spread all of these things?

00:50:14.960 --> 00:50:16.160
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a good question.

00:50:16.160 --> 00:50:18.440
[Guest]: So you know, what is cholera?

00:50:18.440 --> 00:50:21.320
[Guest]: The best way to understand that is firstly in terms of symptoms.

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:23.600
[Guest]: So if you get cholera, you know, what happens to you?

00:50:23.600 --> 00:50:27.960
[Guest]: So likely, almost any illness, there's some amount of headache, okay, you start feeling

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:32.480
[Guest]: dizzy, but the classic symptom of cholera is what we would call is loose motions, or

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:36.720
[Guest]: you know, basically, watery stools, but classically rice water stools.

00:50:36.720 --> 00:50:39.920
[Guest]: This is the classic description, clinical description of cholera.

00:50:39.920 --> 00:50:43.160
[Guest]: Dehydration, you know, that's what's happening with cholera.

00:50:43.160 --> 00:50:47.080
[Guest]: That is, you're losing a lot of fluids from your body, you know, especially through bowel

00:50:47.080 --> 00:50:48.080
[Guest]: movement.

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:50.560
[Guest]: And that's one of the things about cholera, you know, because it really shocks societies

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:53.000
[Guest]: wherever it appeared, because literally you have to go to the toilet.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:56.040
[Guest]: I mean, that's what we're talking about in this disease.

00:50:56.040 --> 00:50:58.440
[Guest]: Now are there references to cholera before 1817?

00:50:58.440 --> 00:50:59.440
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:50:59.440 --> 00:51:02.320
[Guest]: You know, so it's not something which is completely new in 1817.

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:07.320
[Guest]: Historians have pointed out that even in Ayurvedic traditions, people call this particular thing

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:11.960
[Guest]: called Vishu Chika as the closest equivalent to cholera.

00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:13.920
[Guest]: Not another sort of disease, a diarrhea.

00:51:13.920 --> 00:51:15.800
[Guest]: I mean, we use the word diarrhea today.

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:19.040
[Guest]: Today, hardly anyone talks about cholera, but there are certain differences.

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:23.560
[Guest]: So both of them have similar symptoms, but cholera was far more deadlier.

00:51:23.560 --> 00:51:27.360
[Guest]: And often patients would also turn blue because of massive dehydration.

00:51:27.360 --> 00:51:32.640
[Guest]: So you know, turning blue was also part of the sort of folklore around the disease.

00:51:32.640 --> 00:51:35.600
[Guest]: And case fatality rates were more than 50%.

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:39.920
[Guest]: And this is a nice number to know, because it was kind of observed in different settings.

00:51:39.920 --> 00:51:44.120
[Guest]: So what does that mean for, you know, the lay reader right now is that out of 100 people

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:47.000
[Guest]: who get the disease, about more than 50 would die, right?

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:48.920
[Guest]: So that is what we're calling case fatality.

00:51:48.920 --> 00:51:52.300
[Guest]: So in COVID-19 today, we're saying it's about one to 2%, right?

00:51:52.300 --> 00:51:54.220
[Guest]: But it's much more violent than cholera.

00:51:54.220 --> 00:51:59.680
[Guest]: But cholera's case fatality rate at that time was much more than 50%.

00:51:59.680 --> 00:52:00.680
[Guest]: And there are references.

00:52:00.680 --> 00:52:06.480
[Guest]: So the words for cholera before ranged from Morikshi, which was used in Goa.

00:52:06.480 --> 00:52:11.240
[Guest]: Like I said, Vishu Chika is the closest equivalent in Ayurvedic tradition and Haiza.

00:52:11.240 --> 00:52:13.920
[Guest]: So Haiza is like Unani practice, you know.

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:16.960
[Guest]: So in the Arabic world, as well as, you know, Muslim practitioners, health practitioners

00:52:16.960 --> 00:52:18.840
[Guest]: in India, Haiza was the form.

00:52:18.840 --> 00:52:23.640
[Guest]: So for example, if you read this book by Munshi Premchand, you know, called Idga, the father

00:52:23.640 --> 00:52:27.880
[Guest]: of that kid, Hameed, you know, it's a very famous story, dies of Haiza, right?

00:52:27.880 --> 00:52:31.480
[Guest]: So Haiza is what is known out there.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:35.880
[Guest]: In fact, that chapter starts with this particular quote by a Hakeem, you know, Syed Amaldar Hussain,

00:52:35.880 --> 00:52:41.640
[Guest]: who says, Bahut bade doctor miya Haiza ki surat dekhte hai, to unki rooh kaap utti hai.

00:52:41.640 --> 00:52:45.140
[Guest]: And that tells you the kind of thing that doctors are scared to kind of treat patients

00:52:45.140 --> 00:52:48.440
[Guest]: with this, because nobody really knows how to treat.

00:52:48.440 --> 00:52:51.480
[Guest]: So the mystery of cholera is really the fact that you couldn't treat it.

00:52:51.480 --> 00:52:55.360
[Guest]: I think that's the mystery about any diseases that it's, you know, it's so hard to treat

00:52:55.360 --> 00:52:56.360
[Guest]: it.

00:52:56.360 --> 00:53:00.340
[Guest]: And by the 1700s, the first English references to cholera come about.

00:53:00.340 --> 00:53:04.940
[Guest]: So you can see the word cholera, and it's called cholera morbis, for some reason, in

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:06.680
[Guest]: British medical circles.

00:53:06.680 --> 00:53:09.440
[Guest]: And that's really what sticks on.

00:53:09.440 --> 00:53:14.400
[Guest]: And so in 1817, when it kind of, you know, breaks out, it's clear to medical practitioners

00:53:14.400 --> 00:53:16.480
[Guest]: in India that this is cholera.

00:53:16.480 --> 00:53:20.480
[Guest]: But what takes them completely off guard is its virulence.

00:53:20.480 --> 00:53:26.160
[Guest]: So you know, so the same diseases, it's been recorded in pilgrimage sites, it's been recorded

00:53:26.160 --> 00:53:29.360
[Guest]: as, you know, devastating Haridwar in the 1780s.

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:35.000
[Guest]: So stuff happening before 1817, yet in 1817, when it strikes, it goes across the subcontinent

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:36.560
[Guest]: very fast.

00:53:36.560 --> 00:53:38.320
[Guest]: And that's why 1817 is different.

00:53:38.320 --> 00:53:44.960
[Guest]: So the most accepted reason for why 1817 and why not earlier, is that there's some sort

00:53:44.960 --> 00:53:47.920
[Guest]: of a mutation in the strain of cholera.

00:53:47.920 --> 00:53:52.920
[Guest]: We now know cholera is caused by bacteria, that's a different bacteria, and in a virus

00:53:52.920 --> 00:53:53.920
[Guest]: and so on.

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:58.880
[Guest]: So it's a bacteria, which is later, much later, much we talk more than a century later called

00:53:58.880 --> 00:54:00.600
[Guest]: is cholera vibrio.

00:54:00.600 --> 00:54:05.840
[Guest]: So today, I mentioned the symptoms of cholera, and cholera vibrio is a sort of agent.

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:11.000
[Guest]: But what happens from 1817, for almost 100 years, is a really fascinating story of people

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.760
[Guest]: trying to get to grips with this disease.

00:54:13.760 --> 00:54:17.480
[Guest]: And the whole debate on its transmission, how is it spreading?

00:54:17.480 --> 00:54:21.640
[Guest]: You know, today, at least we're lucky to know some elements of transmission, though, during

00:54:21.640 --> 00:54:25.280
[Guest]: the year, you know, we move from being obsessed about surface transmission.

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:28.820
[Guest]: Now people say, you know, there's not so much surface transmission, it's more of airborne.

00:54:28.820 --> 00:54:34.320
[Guest]: But you saw these debates this year, back then, the fundamental, across medical schools

00:54:34.320 --> 00:54:40.320
[Guest]: in the world, the idea was that, you know, bad air or impure air, what the British call

00:54:40.320 --> 00:54:44.720
[Guest]: as miasma, was the reason for every disease, forget just cholera.

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:47.480
[Guest]: And so cholera is an environmental problem.

00:54:47.480 --> 00:54:51.480
[Guest]: That is, if you have filth, if you have dirt, you will get cholera.

00:54:51.480 --> 00:54:54.600
[Guest]: That was the causal sort of relationship in 1817.

00:54:54.600 --> 00:54:55.600
[Guest]: So that's the sort of background.

00:54:55.600 --> 00:54:56.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:54:56.600 --> 00:54:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, no, it's fascinating.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:55:02.520
[Amit Varma]: And just the way people talk of super spreaders today, and, you know, we were quick to blame

00:55:02.520 --> 00:55:06.840
[Amit Varma]: the Tablighi Jamaat a few months back, you know, the same shit was happening back then,

00:55:06.840 --> 00:55:10.920
[Amit Varma]: like you point out about how, at one point, you say, quote, Puri and many other pilgrimage

00:55:10.920 --> 00:55:15.960
[Amit Varma]: sites were perceived by Europeans in the 19th century, in the way many see Chinese wet markets

00:55:15.960 --> 00:55:17.540
[Amit Varma]: of meat in 2020.

00:55:17.540 --> 00:55:20.640
[Amit Varma]: That is, as places that generate pandemic, stop, quote.

00:55:20.640 --> 00:55:25.080
[Amit Varma]: And you speak about how, you know, both Hindu and Muslim pilgrimages were blamed for it.

00:55:25.080 --> 00:55:28.080
[Amit Varma]: There was even an outbreak in Mecca, where many people died.

00:55:28.080 --> 00:55:34.280
[Amit Varma]: And in 1866, the International Sanitary Conference in Constantinople, as it was then blamed Puri

00:55:34.280 --> 00:55:35.280
[Amit Varma]: and Mecca.

00:55:35.280 --> 00:55:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And I want to kind of go back to this question of trying to figure out what causes it, like,

00:55:42.600 --> 00:55:45.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, one thing you point out is that really, it's only by the middle of the 20th

00:55:45.800 --> 00:55:51.280
[Amit Varma]: century that oral rehydration therapy comes about and people kind of figure out what to

00:55:51.280 --> 00:55:54.120
[Amit Varma]: do about cholera, and it isn't such a big deal.

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:59.920
[Amit Varma]: But back then, you have this sort of atmosphere of complete ignorance and all kinds of crazy

00:55:59.920 --> 00:56:05.360
[Amit Varma]: theories, like at one point, you know, you describe this one incident in Russia, where,

00:56:05.360 --> 00:56:10.840
[Amit Varma]: quote, a few villagers abducted two doctors on duty who espoused quarantine, tied them

00:56:10.840 --> 00:56:13.680
[Amit Varma]: to cholera corpses and placed them in a pit.

00:56:13.680 --> 00:56:16.180
[Amit Varma]: Their survival would be proof against contagion.

00:56:16.180 --> 00:56:20.720
[Amit Varma]: In that particular case, they did survive and were eventually pulled out of the pit,

00:56:20.720 --> 00:56:22.280
[Amit Varma]: stop quote, which is fascinating.

00:56:22.280 --> 00:56:26.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, the other thing that strikes me is that medicine based on science at that

00:56:26.040 --> 00:56:32.000
[Amit Varma]: time is at such a primitive stage that alternative medicines are thriving, like you write at

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:36.880
[Amit Varma]: one point, quote, the native physicians, vaids and hakeems did command respect and were enlisted

00:56:36.880 --> 00:56:38.800
[Amit Varma]: by the British in relief efforts.

00:56:38.800 --> 00:56:42.240
[Amit Varma]: The cures offered could be a mixture of various medical traditions.

00:56:42.240 --> 00:56:47.320
[Amit Varma]: The vaids prescribed black pepper, ginger, cloves, and at most beloved Indian ingredient

00:56:47.320 --> 00:56:51.240
[Amit Varma]: hing or asafoetida, however you pronounce that.

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:55.920
[Amit Varma]: In Madras in South India, physicians practicing Ayurveda, Unani and Siddha, native to the

00:56:55.920 --> 00:56:59.800
[Amit Varma]: region, assisted the government and where the cure seemed to be effective, it won the

00:56:59.800 --> 00:57:06.320
[Amit Varma]: appreciation of the locals, irrespective of who the ruling class was, the British or the

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:08.840
[Amit Varma]: local royals, stop quote.

00:57:08.840 --> 00:57:13.880
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that, you know, medicine back in the day is so primitive, you know,

00:57:13.880 --> 00:57:17.880
[Amit Varma]: for various diseases, you'd have bloodletting as an option and all of that.

00:57:17.880 --> 00:57:19.800
[Amit Varma]: Hospitals would not yet be sanitized.

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:24.200
[Amit Varma]: So you could actually die because you went to a hospital that, you know, that is why

00:57:24.200 --> 00:57:28.680
[Amit Varma]: people would believe in some of these alternative systems like, you know, the explanation that

00:57:28.680 --> 00:57:32.920
[Amit Varma]: I give whenever I talk about, you know, why so many people believe in something like homeopathy,

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:35.960
[Amit Varma]: for example, is one, of course, we all know about the placebo effect.

00:57:35.960 --> 00:57:39.680
[Amit Varma]: But there's also reversion to the mean that, you know, some diseases you will just automatically

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:41.320
[Amit Varma]: get better over time.

00:57:41.320 --> 00:57:46.440
[Amit Varma]: And if you take whatever medicine you think is medicine, at the peak of that, you will

00:57:46.440 --> 00:57:51.240
[Amit Varma]: obviously ascribe causation and say, oh, no, no, no, this cured me and all of that.

00:57:51.240 --> 00:57:56.000
[Amit Varma]: So what's kind of the medical landscape like because, you know, today we think of, okay,

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:01.720
[Amit Varma]: there is science and, you know, there is proper kind of medicine and we have a great understanding

00:58:01.720 --> 00:58:02.960
[Amit Varma]: into all of these.

00:58:02.960 --> 00:58:06.720
[Amit Varma]: But at that time, everything is kind of faith based depending on whatever you think that

00:58:06.720 --> 00:58:09.680
[Amit Varma]: works because nobody really knows anything, right?

00:58:09.680 --> 00:58:10.680
[Guest]: What was that like?

00:58:10.680 --> 00:58:11.680
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:58:11.680 --> 00:58:17.720
[Guest]: I mean, you know, also this today, this notion of Western superiority in medicine, right?

00:58:17.720 --> 00:58:22.280
[Guest]: If at all it was, in fact, what I pointed on this book is that for at least these pandemics,

00:58:22.280 --> 00:58:23.880
[Guest]: it really didn't matter that much.

00:58:23.880 --> 00:58:27.000
[Guest]: Maybe cholera in the late 19th century, but for plague, they figured it out very late

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:32.380
[Guest]: after the pandemic, influenza after the pandemic, so it really didn't help during the pandemic.

00:58:32.380 --> 00:58:35.000
[Guest]: But in the early 19th century, they were all the same.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:40.040
[Guest]: I mean, there was really no advantage that Western medicine gave in, you know, surviving

00:58:40.040 --> 00:58:46.440
[Guest]: cholera vis-a-vis Ayurveda, vis-a-vis Unani, vis-a-vis Siddha, which is in South India.

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:49.560
[Guest]: So as you said, you know, completely faith based.

00:58:49.560 --> 00:58:52.200
[Guest]: Does that mean, you know, it's completely useless?

00:58:52.200 --> 00:58:56.280
[Guest]: Against cholera, it's hard to say, but against basic diseases, I'm pretty sure that some

00:58:56.280 --> 00:58:59.240
[Guest]: of these things that they would have been offering must have worked.

00:58:59.240 --> 00:59:04.200
[Guest]: Obviously every, you know, there's a credibility criteria and these doctors would have gained

00:59:04.200 --> 00:59:08.280
[Guest]: reputation over time only, of course, if things worked, right?

00:59:08.280 --> 00:59:15.080
[Guest]: But you know, this is a world where even these doctors living on side by side with massive

00:59:15.080 --> 00:59:19.080
[Guest]: superstitions and you have these witches, you have these sorcerers, you have all kinds

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:24.600
[Guest]: of people in especially rural India, but also urban India who command huge respect.

00:59:24.600 --> 00:59:30.440
[Guest]: So of course, goddesses and gods, you know, so in Indian history, Sitala is this classic

00:59:30.440 --> 00:59:33.400
[Guest]: goddess in Eastern India for smallpox.

00:59:33.400 --> 00:59:38.040
[Guest]: But very quickly for cholera, you know, across the 1700s and early 1800s, this Ola Bibi came

00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:39.560
[Guest]: into prominence.

00:59:39.560 --> 00:59:40.920
[Guest]: And it's really fascinating.

00:59:40.920 --> 00:59:47.880
[Guest]: So in 1817 and the years preceding that, Ola Bibi's kind of stock went up much more than

00:59:47.880 --> 00:59:53.880
[Guest]: Sitala, you know, and so different temples had to kind of woo, in fact, their own patrons

00:59:53.880 --> 00:59:57.080
[Guest]: saying that, no, no, our God can, you know, help you out better.

00:59:57.080 --> 01:00:02.040
[Guest]: So it's interesting how religion was, of course, very closely intertwined, you know, with healing

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:02.600
[Guest]: practices.

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:08.680
[Guest]: Also, you know, I point out in cholera, this is a jumping 100 years later, but Christian

01:00:08.680 --> 01:00:10.120
[Guest]: conversion, for example, right?

01:00:10.120 --> 01:00:15.400
[Guest]: So using epidemics as a pretext for, you know, missionary movement saying that, look, our

01:00:15.400 --> 01:00:16.680
[Guest]: science is better.

01:00:16.680 --> 01:00:21.160
[Guest]: Actually, it wasn't better for a long period, but the claim that our science is better.

01:00:21.160 --> 01:00:24.360
[Guest]: So if you join our religion, you know, you get some benefits out of it.

01:00:24.360 --> 01:00:29.000
[Guest]: So this is open game and health being a day-to-day matter, right?

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:32.840
[Guest]: It must have been such an important thing in guiding people's decisions, whether to

01:00:32.840 --> 01:00:33.960
[Guest]: convert a religion.

01:00:33.960 --> 01:00:38.280
[Guest]: If somebody is going to say that, you know, I can cure you, it is the most powerful kind

01:00:38.280 --> 01:00:42.200
[Guest]: of advice, you know, anybody can potentially take.

01:00:42.200 --> 01:00:46.680
[Guest]: Even in India today, a lot of the spiritual guru market thrives on healing powers, right?

01:00:46.680 --> 01:00:48.520
[Guest]: And so it's a very closely attached notion.

01:00:48.520 --> 01:00:52.920
[Guest]: So the medical landscape in 1870s, as you rightly pointed out, very primitive, right?

01:00:52.920 --> 01:00:55.320
[Guest]: There are no clear advantages of any system.

01:00:55.320 --> 01:00:58.760
[Guest]: And on cholera, as you said, pretty much everyone is clueless.

01:00:58.760 --> 01:01:02.040
[Guest]: In fact, some of these things that they were doing, like bloodletting, this was a British

01:01:02.040 --> 01:01:05.800
[Guest]: practice, it was completely opposite of what anyone should be doing.

01:01:05.800 --> 01:01:09.400
[Guest]: You know, the analogy I use in the book is like, you know, contracting money supply in

01:01:09.400 --> 01:01:10.280
[Guest]: a recession.

01:01:10.280 --> 01:01:11.560
[Guest]: This is pretty much what they were doing.

01:01:11.560 --> 01:01:15.640
[Guest]: That is literally, you know, what you need is actually some amount of fluids in your

01:01:15.640 --> 01:01:16.200
[Guest]: body.

01:01:16.200 --> 01:01:19.880
[Guest]: And so taking out even some of that was really a crazy idea.

01:01:20.520 --> 01:01:25.320
[Guest]: In one of the practices, they would put leeches on the anus to suck out the blood, you know,

01:01:25.320 --> 01:01:29.720
[Guest]: really crazy practices which emerged in the 1820s and 1830s.

01:01:29.720 --> 01:01:35.560
[Guest]: And all of this on the pretext that cholera was somehow coming from the air, from environment

01:01:35.560 --> 01:01:36.120
[Unknown]: and so on.

01:01:36.120 --> 01:01:40.360
[Guest]: And so it's really John Snow, who's the hero in this whole fight against cholera,

01:01:40.360 --> 01:01:45.800
[Guest]: who in, you know, 1840s and 1850s, figures out that, look, hey, this is not about air,

01:01:45.800 --> 01:01:46.920
[Guest]: this is about water.

01:01:46.920 --> 01:01:51.160
[Guest]: And that's the big discovery on cholera, that cholera is a waterborne disease.

01:01:51.160 --> 01:01:55.960
[Guest]: And yet, even though John Snow kind of proves it in the 1850s, he's not very famous in

01:01:55.960 --> 01:01:56.600
[Guest]: his lifetime.

01:01:56.600 --> 01:01:59.720
[Guest]: You know, he's now very famous today, but he was not very famous back then.

01:02:00.440 --> 01:02:04.600
[Guest]: People maintained to this airborne theory of cholera transmission for literally more

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:05.400
[Guest]: than 60 years.

01:02:05.960 --> 01:02:10.200
[Guest]: And the Indian guys, the Indian Medical Service, which are British officers, they were

01:02:10.200 --> 01:02:14.920
[Guest]: scientifically trained and so on, was so proud of their science of the airborne theory of

01:02:14.920 --> 01:02:17.480
[Guest]: cholera that they rejected John Snow's theory.

01:02:17.480 --> 01:02:22.760
[Guest]: And so for until 1900s or so, it was a complete global embarrassment because these Indian

01:02:22.760 --> 01:02:26.920
[Guest]: Medical Service people were hell-bent on showing that it was the environment.

01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:27.560
[Guest]: Why the environment?

01:02:27.560 --> 01:02:30.200
[Guest]: Because they figured out, look, cholera happens only in some parts of the year.

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:32.520
[Guest]: So it can't be just waterborne.

01:02:32.520 --> 01:02:34.600
[Guest]: Otherwise, it would be affecting you all through the year, right?

01:02:34.600 --> 01:02:36.040
[Guest]: So there must be something with the environment.

01:02:36.040 --> 01:02:37.000
[Guest]: So they had their reasons.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:41.160
[Guest]: They had their own kind of scientific reasoning based on the position they were taking.

01:02:41.160 --> 01:02:42.760
[Guest]: But on hindsight, they were completely wrong.

01:02:42.760 --> 01:02:45.800
[Guest]: Cholera is mostly a waterborne theory.

01:02:45.800 --> 01:02:49.400
[Guest]: Of course, there are new transmission mechanisms found today, but it is generally a

01:02:49.400 --> 01:02:50.280
[Guest]: waterborne disease.

01:02:50.280 --> 01:02:54.440
[Guest]: And it's only once they figure out transmission that people could start working out on

01:02:54.440 --> 01:02:55.640
[Guest]: prevention, cure, and so on.

01:02:55.640 --> 01:03:00.360
[Guest]: So that has to wait the truly great scientific revolution called bacteriology.

01:03:00.360 --> 01:03:06.280
[Guest]: And so the great bacteriologists like Robert Koch, Louis Pasteur, after everyone who gets

01:03:06.280 --> 01:03:10.200
[Guest]: up in the morning drinking milk knows about pasteurization, pasteurized milk.

01:03:10.200 --> 01:03:15.960
[Guest]: This is all the great work of certain French and German and a few British scientists in

01:03:15.960 --> 01:03:17.320
[Guest]: the late 19th century.

01:03:17.320 --> 01:03:21.640
[Guest]: And it's only with that that you can see a dramatic divergence then in medical systems.

01:03:21.640 --> 01:03:25.320
[Guest]: So that's really what takes Western medicine ahead, because they start this idea of

01:03:25.320 --> 01:03:27.000
[Guest]: experimentation-based science.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:31.880
[Guest]: They kind of understand what is the idea of the germs creating disease and so on.

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:35.960
[Guest]: And then that, of course, helps in controlling cholera eventually.

01:03:35.960 --> 01:03:38.360
[Guest]: But the overall progress is very slow.

01:03:38.360 --> 01:03:44.680
[Guest]: The case fatality rates of cholera finally fall down only in the 1910s and 1920s.

01:03:44.680 --> 01:03:50.520
[Guest]: And luckily for the Indian Medical Service, it's one of, you know, our or their people

01:03:50.520 --> 01:03:51.080
[Guest]: who does this.

01:03:51.080 --> 01:03:56.440
[Guest]: And it's a guy called Leonard Rogers who finally figures out that the way to stop a

01:03:56.440 --> 01:03:59.800
[Guest]: body from dehydrating is rehydrating it.

01:03:59.800 --> 01:04:05.480
[Guest]: And so what he pioneered was this IV method, intravenous method of injecting fluids, saline,

01:04:05.480 --> 01:04:10.120
[Guest]: high saline sort of portions into the body, worked it out in Calcutta, took five years

01:04:10.120 --> 01:04:11.960
[Guest]: of experimentation, but finally he got it.

01:04:11.960 --> 01:04:15.560
[Guest]: And that reduced case fatality rates from 50% to less than 20%.

01:04:15.560 --> 01:04:19.720
[Guest]: And today, of course, you know, people say this is the greatest invention in medical

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:24.680
[Guest]: history that is ORT, you know, oral rehydration therapy, because it's so cost effective.

01:04:24.680 --> 01:04:25.720
[Guest]: It's so cheap.

01:04:25.720 --> 01:04:29.000
[Guest]: It's just a bunch of salts in your mouth and you're ingesting it.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:31.240
[Guest]: And yet it kind of protects you against diarrhea.

01:04:31.240 --> 01:04:35.800
[Guest]: It protects you against an important class of diseases that historically claimed a lot

01:04:35.800 --> 01:04:36.360
[Guest]: of lives.

01:04:36.360 --> 01:04:40.600
[Guest]: So today, cholera, even if it happens, we know how to fight it.

01:04:40.600 --> 01:04:43.720
[Guest]: Unless the strain kind of mutates and again becomes very deadly.

01:04:43.720 --> 01:04:47.240
[Guest]: But at least the lead time on bacterial diseases today is very good.

01:04:47.240 --> 01:04:48.920
[Guest]: So we can, you know, quickly fight.

01:04:48.920 --> 01:04:54.760
[Guest]: But as you pointed out, 1817, very primitive, no real advantage offered by any medical system.

