[Amit Varma]: the break.

01:06:34.360 --> 01:06:37.480
[Amit Varma]: I have sort of a couple of follow-up points.

01:06:37.480 --> 01:06:39.080
[Amit Varma]: One is you refer to Jon Snow, right?

01:06:39.080 --> 01:06:44.280
[Amit Varma]: So and that whole narrative is very interesting where in 1849, he comes out with a book called

01:06:44.280 --> 01:06:49.960
[Amit Varma]: On the Mode of Communication of Cholera and no one pays any attention to him.

01:06:49.960 --> 01:06:52.200
[Amit Varma]: Then in 1887, you speak about M.C.

01:06:52.200 --> 01:06:56.520
[Amit Varma]: Fennell who comes out with, you know, this paper called Cholera and Water in India, stop

01:06:56.520 --> 01:06:56.760
[Amit Varma]: quote.

01:06:56.760 --> 01:07:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And what I found fascinating about that is you've reproduced a map in the book.

01:07:00.120 --> 01:07:03.720
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, people who've been following COVID would notice that there are all these

01:07:03.720 --> 01:07:07.400
[Amit Varma]: studies of how COVID can spread through droplets in a restaurant.

01:07:07.400 --> 01:07:11.640
[Amit Varma]: So you'll have maps of restaurants and where everybody is sitting and, you know, with arrows

01:07:11.640 --> 01:07:13.800
[Amit Varma]: to where the droplets are going.

01:07:13.800 --> 01:07:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And M.C.

01:07:14.520 --> 01:07:19.160
[Amit Varma]: Fennell did a similar thing where he mapped the spread of cholera in a village and he

01:07:19.160 --> 01:07:25.400
[Amit Varma]: had like two wells which he marked out and then showed the kind of spread proportional

01:07:25.400 --> 01:07:30.440
[Amit Varma]: to the two wells and therefore concluded that it's obviously a waterborne disease, which,

01:07:30.440 --> 01:07:35.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, despite what Snow had done four decades earlier, no one yet believed and,

01:07:35.240 --> 01:07:39.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, advocated things like instead of these wells, we should have mass produced

01:07:39.080 --> 01:07:40.600
[Amit Varma]: hand pumps and all that.

01:07:40.600 --> 01:07:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Just remarkable scientific work.

01:07:43.080 --> 01:07:47.160
[Amit Varma]: And yet no one took him seriously in much the same way that, for example, that, you

01:07:47.160 --> 01:07:51.960
[Amit Varma]: know, so many lives were lost because people ignored, you know, Semmelweis when he spoke

01:07:51.960 --> 01:07:54.040
[Amit Varma]: about the importance of hand washing and all of that.

01:07:54.040 --> 01:07:58.520
[Amit Varma]: Why do you think, like, it seems to me that always within any establishment in pretty

01:07:58.520 --> 01:08:03.160
[Amit Varma]: much any context, even outside the context of medicine, there is this arrogance, there

01:08:03.160 --> 01:08:07.160
[Amit Varma]: is this lack of humility, you know, there is an accepted way of doing things, of thinking

01:08:07.160 --> 01:08:08.040
[Amit Varma]: about things.

01:08:08.040 --> 01:08:09.960
[Amit Varma]: And you imagine that this is right.

01:08:09.960 --> 01:08:15.640
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, anything new that comes up, new truths, new revelations can often take

01:08:15.640 --> 01:08:20.680
[Amit Varma]: decades to spread, even in something which literally can, you know, affect lives.

01:08:20.680 --> 01:08:25.960
[Amit Varma]: So and it's not just in medicine, it's in economics, it's in governance, in so many

01:08:25.960 --> 01:08:29.800
[Amit Varma]: different fields, you find that, you know, authorities are sticking by the wrong way

01:08:29.800 --> 01:08:33.960
[Amit Varma]: of doing things for ages, while, you know, the truth is out there.

01:08:33.960 --> 01:08:37.000
[Amit Varma]: So is this something that you've, you know, kind of thought about?

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:40.920
[Guest]: Yeah, in social science, we say, you know, paradigms go away one death at a time, you

01:08:40.920 --> 01:08:45.560
[Guest]: know, it's only when the guy dies, finally, that his disciples, his, you know, chelas

01:08:45.560 --> 01:08:51.000
[Guest]: across many PhDs, you know, lineages, who kind of propagate this guy's views throughout.

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:53.560
[Guest]: But the thing with science is that this such thing should not happen.

01:08:53.560 --> 01:08:57.800
[Guest]: I can imagine economics, you're a clinician, or you're a Friedmanite, and you know, these

01:08:57.800 --> 01:09:00.280
[Guest]: kind of ideologies pass on through PhD students.

01:09:00.280 --> 01:09:03.240
[Guest]: But in science, the whole idea of science is fairly objective.

01:09:03.240 --> 01:09:05.800
[Guest]: If it's bad science, it gets figured out very quickly.

01:09:05.800 --> 01:09:08.360
[Guest]: And so John Snow had kind of figured it out very well.

01:09:08.920 --> 01:09:13.800
[Guest]: Europe started implementing that, you know, they started having better water supply systems,

01:09:13.800 --> 01:09:19.400
[Guest]: they kind of started accepting it as controversial, but some kind of evidence based approach to

01:09:19.400 --> 01:09:20.760
[Guest]: understanding cholera was on.

01:09:22.040 --> 01:09:26.920
[Guest]: In Germany, one of the heroes of the sanitation policies guy called Max von Pettenkofer.

01:09:26.920 --> 01:09:31.960
[Guest]: And Pettenkofer, interestingly, you know, did not believe in the waterborne theory.

01:09:31.960 --> 01:09:35.160
[Guest]: And almost in his death, he committed suicide, finally, in the 1890s.

01:09:35.160 --> 01:09:40.040
[Guest]: He maintained this view that, you know, it's the environment and not, he, in fact, actively

01:09:40.040 --> 01:09:41.960
[Guest]: looked down upon bacteriology and so on.

01:09:41.960 --> 01:09:46.520
[Guest]: Even Florence Nightingale had to be shown a microscope to say, look, this is the new

01:09:46.520 --> 01:09:49.240
[Guest]: science, right, and this is what is causing diseases.

01:09:49.240 --> 01:09:50.920
[Guest]: And then finally, she accepted.

01:09:50.920 --> 01:09:54.680
[Guest]: So often you have to demonstrate, you know, this revolutionary ideas which were coming

01:09:54.680 --> 01:09:55.400
[Guest]: back then.

01:09:55.400 --> 01:09:59.880
[Guest]: In the case of MC Fern, very interesting, you know, he's a lower rung sort of bureaucrat

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:04.760
[Guest]: in the Indian Medical Service, but completely ignored by the top brass, and by some accounts,

01:10:04.760 --> 01:10:09.720
[Guest]: even lost his job because he was actively propagating an idea which would have saved

01:10:09.720 --> 01:10:14.520
[Guest]: millions of Indian lives, you know, if people had started getting good water supply systems,

01:10:14.520 --> 01:10:18.280
[Guest]: that was all it was needed to prevent muscular heartbreaks.

01:10:18.280 --> 01:10:22.280
[Guest]: Interestingly, the Maharaja of Travancore, you know, wrote to him saying that, you know,

01:10:22.280 --> 01:10:24.360
[Guest]: I would like to hear more about your ideas and so on.

01:10:24.360 --> 01:10:28.120
[Guest]: So there were people, there was a particular audience who was willing to experiment.

01:10:28.120 --> 01:10:32.920
[Guest]: But the IMS, Indian Medical Service, hell-bent, in fact, they looked up to Pettenkofer.

01:10:32.920 --> 01:10:36.520
[Guest]: They said, if Pettenkofer is saying this, you know, we believe Pettenkofer's theory.

01:10:36.520 --> 01:10:41.960
[Guest]: So this is an interesting kind of thing, even in science, because both the IMS and John

01:10:41.960 --> 01:10:44.440
[Guest]: Snow are coming from a particular scientific tradition.

01:10:45.320 --> 01:10:48.200
[Guest]: But in science, we would say, you know, one thing has to be right, and one thing has to

01:10:48.200 --> 01:10:49.560
[Guest]: be wrong eventually.

01:10:49.560 --> 01:10:52.360
[Guest]: In this case, these guys held on to this position for far too long.

01:10:53.080 --> 01:10:57.720
[Guest]: And eventually, you know, it was kind of demonstrated, clear cut, that it was a waterborne

01:10:57.720 --> 01:10:58.680
[Guest]: disease.

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:01.400
[Guest]: And it's only much later that these water supply systems came.

01:11:01.400 --> 01:11:06.600
[Guest]: In fact, in Calcutta, cholera started and overall mortality started falling majorly

01:11:06.600 --> 01:11:10.360
[Guest]: after 1869, when the pipe water supply was introduced in the city.

01:11:10.360 --> 01:11:15.480
[Guest]: So even that was actually a clear cut example of success in how one can prevent cholera.

01:11:15.480 --> 01:11:16.280
[Guest]: So you're absolutely right.

01:11:16.280 --> 01:11:18.040
[Guest]: You know, these paradigms exist.

01:11:18.040 --> 01:11:23.000
[Guest]: And it's very tough sometimes for a revolutionary idea to make its way across the board.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:27.640
[Guest]: And stuff which today we would take for granted, you know, that if this is what scientists

01:11:27.640 --> 01:11:32.360
[Guest]: are saying by, you know, using a particular process of experimentation and so on, there's

01:11:32.360 --> 01:11:33.640
[Guest]: much more credibility today.

01:11:34.360 --> 01:11:40.440
[Guest]: But back in late 19th century, when the first ideas of bacteriology were coming in, it received

01:11:40.440 --> 01:11:41.480
[Guest]: a lot of pushback.

01:11:42.200 --> 01:11:46.360
[Guest]: And, you know, the people were very, very skeptical of the claims that they were making.

01:11:46.360 --> 01:11:51.240
[Guest]: It really, but it's only with the 1900s, when without a doubt, you know, the ideas of pasture,

01:11:51.240 --> 01:11:55.400
[Guest]: caulk, and many others were finally holding sway.

01:11:55.400 --> 01:12:02.280
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, another thing that kind of struck me when I was reading this book was

01:12:03.480 --> 01:12:09.400
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, we look back on those times with hindsight and the accumulated knowledge

01:12:09.400 --> 01:12:14.120
[Amit Varma]: that we have, and look at it through that prism, like I sometimes feel I cannot possibly

01:12:14.120 --> 01:12:18.600
[Amit Varma]: imagine what it would be like for me to live in the 19th century, because whatever knowledge

01:12:18.600 --> 01:12:22.280
[Amit Varma]: I have, I would have to assume it does not exist, I would have to strip it away.

01:12:22.280 --> 01:12:25.480
[Amit Varma]: And all those sort of the certainties kind of vanish.

01:12:25.480 --> 01:12:29.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, we speak about how, you know, in one sense, you know, the God of religion

01:12:29.560 --> 01:12:32.360
[Amit Varma]: is really the God of the gaps, there are so many things you can't explain.

01:12:32.360 --> 01:12:37.640
[Amit Varma]: So you bring God as an explanation, you are in prehistoric times, you don't even understand,

01:12:37.640 --> 01:12:41.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, the sun, the moon, the rain, so you have gods for each of them, and so on,

01:12:41.160 --> 01:12:41.960
[Amit Varma]: and so forth.

01:12:41.960 --> 01:12:47.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, in modern times, the only things that can't be explained is perhaps the things that

01:12:47.080 --> 01:12:50.600
[Amit Varma]: will never be explained, which is, or which will never be confronted, like what is the

01:12:50.600 --> 01:12:51.400
[Amit Varma]: meaning of life?

01:12:51.400 --> 01:12:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, one could just say that, look, rationally speaking, there is no meaning,

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:56.600
[Amit Varma]: it is random and all of that.

01:12:56.600 --> 01:12:58.440
[Amit Varma]: But that's a little hard to accept.

01:12:58.440 --> 01:13:03.000
[Amit Varma]: But a lot of these other questions have been answered, like, you know, Douglas Adams once

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:07.240
[Amit Varma]: famously said, when speaking about natural selection, that give me the awe of knowledge

01:13:07.240 --> 01:13:12.200
[Amit Varma]: over, you know, whatever, or religion kind of might invoke.

01:13:12.200 --> 01:13:16.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, I'm kind of thinking back to the 19th century, when this shit is happening all around

01:13:16.040 --> 01:13:20.120
[Amit Varma]: you, people are dying, and you have no clue why some random person is saying it's because

01:13:20.120 --> 01:13:23.720
[Amit Varma]: of water, but other people are coming up with various explanations.

01:13:23.720 --> 01:13:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And some of these are stunning explanations.

01:13:25.560 --> 01:13:29.960
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, you write in your book, quote, one Sanskrit scholar from that region

01:13:29.960 --> 01:13:34.600
[Amit Varma]: mused that there were three types of disease in the world, for sins committed in past lives,

01:13:34.600 --> 01:13:39.640
[Amit Varma]: for sins of the current life, and for accidental sins, and that an epidemic like cholera came

01:13:39.640 --> 01:13:42.600
[Amit Varma]: under the second category, which is sins of the current life.

01:13:43.160 --> 01:13:47.400
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, similarly, you talk about how there are cholera deities all over the place, including

01:13:47.400 --> 01:13:50.600
[Amit Varma]: one called Harlul Lala in Bundelkhand.

01:13:50.600 --> 01:13:55.960
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, you know, one of the British dignitaries of that time who was leading them

01:13:55.960 --> 01:14:00.440
[Amit Varma]: against the Marathas, in fact, in the third Anglo-Maratha war, Francis Rodden Hastings,

01:14:00.440 --> 01:14:06.520
[Amit Varma]: you write about how his men are blamed for killing cows on Lala's grave, which is why

01:14:06.520 --> 01:14:09.960
[Amit Varma]: he is effectively now taking revenge and he is a cholera deity.

01:14:09.960 --> 01:14:14.920
[Amit Varma]: You also speak about how in the Konkan region on the west coast, witches and sorcerers are

01:14:14.920 --> 01:14:21.480
[Amit Varma]: being blamed for cholera and as late as 1943, B. R. Ambedkar writes, quote, it was reported

01:14:21.480 --> 01:14:26.680
[Amit Varma]: from Nasik on 1st September that the Hindus of a village attacked an Achuth, which is

01:14:26.680 --> 01:14:32.120
[Amit Varma]: a term Ambedkar used, attacked an Achuth family, tied the hands and feet of an elderly woman,

01:14:32.120 --> 01:14:35.400
[Amit Varma]: placed her on a pile of wood, which was subsequently set on fire.

01:14:35.400 --> 01:14:39.480
[Amit Varma]: All this because they thought she was a cause of the cholera in the village, stop quote.

01:14:39.480 --> 01:14:42.360
[Amit Varma]: And these narratives are crazy.

01:14:42.360 --> 01:14:46.040
[Amit Varma]: Of course, they're not like propagating at WhatsApp speed like they do today.

01:14:46.040 --> 01:14:50.680
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, and today you could argue that despite the fact that we know so much more,

01:14:50.680 --> 01:14:55.160
[Amit Varma]: these narratives are still so commonplace, like around Sushant Singh Rajput's death when

01:14:55.160 --> 01:15:01.160
[Amit Varma]: he recently dies and all the mad conspiracy theories that came up then, some on news TV

01:15:01.160 --> 01:15:03.800
[Amit Varma]: and some even on Twitter and so on and so forth.

01:15:03.800 --> 01:15:08.200
[Amit Varma]: And again, you've spoken about how back then people used to resist vaccination when it

01:15:08.200 --> 01:15:12.520
[Amit Varma]: came about, when it, you know, started becoming sort of popularized in the late 19th century,

01:15:12.520 --> 01:15:14.840
[Amit Varma]: because they were like, it'll make us important.

01:15:14.840 --> 01:15:19.080
[Amit Varma]: And just today, I saw on Twitter that people are talking about these current vaccines that

01:15:19.720 --> 01:15:23.640
[Amit Varma]: I think somewhere in central India, there is this rumor that the men start behaving

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:27.800
[Amit Varma]: like women and the women start behaving like men, which if you ask me is not a very bad

01:15:27.800 --> 01:15:28.360
[Amit Varma]: thing.

01:15:28.360 --> 01:15:31.000
[Amit Varma]: So there is a sense of overall bewilderment.

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:35.240
[Amit Varma]: So and as a historian who is kind of going in there doing the complete opposite, you

01:15:35.240 --> 01:15:40.520
[Amit Varma]: know, making sense of everything, but everybody in your stories in the histories that you

01:15:40.520 --> 01:15:43.640
[Amit Varma]: tell, most people are just completely bewildered all the time.

01:15:43.640 --> 01:15:46.600
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, what is your sense of this?

01:15:46.600 --> 01:15:50.200
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, whether this kind of reveals something about the human condition and the

01:15:50.200 --> 01:15:51.880
[Amit Varma]: progress of science will not affect it?

01:15:51.880 --> 01:15:54.680
[Guest]: This is a very deep question.

01:15:54.680 --> 01:16:01.080
[Guest]: Because, I mean, this idea of panic, fear, you know, conspiracy, rumor mongering, we've

01:16:01.080 --> 01:16:06.280
[Guest]: seen so much of that this year itself, you know, in 2020, maybe not as deadly as the

01:16:06.280 --> 01:16:07.240
[Guest]: rumors back then.

01:16:07.880 --> 01:16:11.880
[Guest]: But of course, the rumors travel much faster now than back then.

01:16:11.880 --> 01:16:15.000
[Guest]: For example, you know, in March, there was this thing about Indian immunity.

01:16:15.560 --> 01:16:19.960
[Guest]: And a lot of people say, no, this will not come to India, because we have such strong

01:16:19.960 --> 01:16:20.760
[Guest]: immunity.

01:16:20.760 --> 01:16:22.760
[Guest]: You know, these people live in clean environments.

01:16:22.760 --> 01:16:24.280
[Guest]: And so that's why they get COVID.

01:16:24.280 --> 01:16:27.000
[Guest]: Whereas we kind of grow up in these bad environments.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:31.240
[Guest]: And we, it's almost like this pride that, you know, we can have our own water and food

01:16:31.240 --> 01:16:33.960
[Guest]: and the foreigners who come here fall sick.

01:16:33.960 --> 01:16:36.280
[Guest]: Now, this is not something to be proud about.

01:16:36.280 --> 01:16:39.640
[Guest]: This is, we have bad quality water and, you know, we are kind of immune to it.

01:16:39.640 --> 01:16:41.480
[Guest]: But that's only one part of immunity.

01:16:41.480 --> 01:16:44.600
[Guest]: There's nothing like full blown, you know, immunity to anything.

01:16:44.600 --> 01:16:46.360
[Guest]: That's how we kind of fool ourselves.

01:16:46.360 --> 01:16:50.840
[Guest]: You know, we fool ourselves with these nice stories, which vegetarianism, you know, this

01:16:50.840 --> 01:16:55.320
[Guest]: huge thing with Indians, or there was one, you know, WhatsApp forward this year, India

01:16:55.320 --> 01:16:57.480
[Guest]: has never been the source of pandemics.

01:16:57.480 --> 01:17:01.160
[Guest]: And the subtext being, you know, because they are mostly like the argument being because

01:17:01.160 --> 01:17:03.080
[Guest]: India has a lot of vegetarians and so on.

01:17:03.080 --> 01:17:09.080
[Guest]: But cholera was, I mean, like the world blames China today for nearly a century, India was

01:17:09.080 --> 01:17:13.000
[Guest]: seen as China is seen today, an originator of pandemics, you know.

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:18.520
[Guest]: So the sort of classic emotions of fear, that will not stop.

01:17:18.520 --> 01:17:21.000
[Guest]: But I think here's what collective memory can do.

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:26.280
[Guest]: You know, if collective memory is there, it's a built in, we know, we can see the markers

01:17:26.280 --> 01:17:27.720
[Guest]: and quickly react to that.

01:17:27.720 --> 01:17:31.560
[Guest]: So, you know, nobody is in Europe is blaming the Jews for poisoning bells.

01:17:31.560 --> 01:17:34.120
[Guest]: This was happening in the 14th century plague.

01:17:34.120 --> 01:17:37.160
[Guest]: And of course, it was happening in different ways in the early 20th century, but today

01:17:37.160 --> 01:17:38.200
[Guest]: that's not happening.

01:17:38.200 --> 01:17:42.360
[Guest]: And so that sort of, you know, collective memory is useful to understand.

01:17:42.360 --> 01:17:46.760
[Guest]: I think the thing with pandemics is that when it strikes, it happens so rarely that when

01:17:46.760 --> 01:17:51.720
[Guest]: it strikes, people have no clue how to react to it, or any new epidemic.

01:17:52.520 --> 01:17:56.840
[Guest]: And that is why, you know, building this collective memory through different generation, passing

01:17:56.840 --> 01:18:00.120
[Guest]: that information on to each generation is very important so that people realize that

01:18:00.120 --> 01:18:03.560
[Guest]: there are certain patterns, you know, pandemics will happen.

01:18:03.560 --> 01:18:08.520
[Guest]: And, you know, there's no need to kind of completely go into panic and rumor mongering

01:18:08.520 --> 01:18:09.320
[Guest]: mode.

01:18:09.320 --> 01:18:14.280
[Guest]: One needs to trust scientists and hear out at least what they're saying, and so on.

01:18:14.280 --> 01:18:18.760
[Guest]: So this, you know, in the 19th century world, given the kind of, you know, the world of

01:18:18.760 --> 01:18:23.560
[Guest]: witches and sorcerers and so on, you can just imagine the amount of crazy things.

01:18:23.560 --> 01:18:28.760
[Guest]: I mean, Ambedkar was reporting stuff in the 1940s, you know, of people burning, literally

01:18:28.760 --> 01:18:30.920
[Guest]: putting people on the stake, so to speak.

01:18:30.920 --> 01:18:35.400
[Guest]: Crazy things happening in the name of epidemics in a caste-driven society as India, you know,

01:18:36.040 --> 01:18:38.440
[Guest]: where today the word is social distancing.

01:18:38.440 --> 01:18:42.520
[Guest]: Historically in India, I mean, it's a different concept, but untouchability, right?

01:18:42.520 --> 01:18:46.840
[Guest]: And in the world of epidemics, of course, that took on a huge meaning because often

01:18:46.840 --> 01:18:51.640
[Guest]: the segregation in villages and cities meant that the lowest ranking caste, for example,

01:18:51.640 --> 01:18:56.200
[Guest]: were confined to the worst amount of food, the worst kind of water, and highly sensitive.

01:18:56.200 --> 01:19:02.200
[Guest]: So influenza, for example, you know, the death rates for plague influenza, especially influenza,

01:19:02.200 --> 01:19:07.480
[Guest]: was so much higher, you know, among certain social groups of India compared to the rest.

01:19:07.480 --> 01:19:12.440
[Guest]: So diseases acted differently, you know, on, you know, different sets of social groups

01:19:12.440 --> 01:19:13.560
[Guest]: in the population.

01:19:13.560 --> 01:19:19.240
[Guest]: And thus, there was the thing, so if you escaped one plausible hypothesis that, you know, say

01:19:19.240 --> 01:19:23.880
[Guest]: the so-called untouchables of that time had a much, much more higher death rates because

01:19:23.880 --> 01:19:25.400
[Guest]: nutrition was so poor, right?

01:19:25.400 --> 01:19:28.360
[Guest]: So they're really poor and could not withstand these diseases.

01:19:28.920 --> 01:19:33.560
[Guest]: But yet, the perception that so many people who are dying of plague influenza belong to

01:19:33.560 --> 01:19:38.440
[Guest]: these social groups leads to a new perception that it's them who are causing these diseases.

01:19:38.440 --> 01:19:41.720
[Guest]: And so that becomes like a self-reinforcing stereotype.

01:19:41.720 --> 01:19:45.560
[Guest]: And what modern science does, of course, to kind of, you know, tell that this is not cause

01:19:45.560 --> 01:19:46.040
[Guest]: and effect.

01:19:46.040 --> 01:19:47.480
[Guest]: There's a different set of reasons why.

01:19:48.280 --> 01:19:54.200
[Guest]: This is why when cholera first struck London and UK in a big way, it hit the poor parts,

01:19:54.200 --> 01:19:55.400
[Guest]: you know, of this thing.

01:19:55.400 --> 01:19:59.160
[Guest]: And the poor actually thought that it's a way of the rich to get rid of.

01:20:00.040 --> 01:20:01.800
[Guest]: So that's an interesting story.

01:20:01.800 --> 01:20:05.080
[Amit Varma]: But another of the interesting things that I found, you know, while reading your book

01:20:05.080 --> 01:20:08.360
[Amit Varma]: is that typically we think of a pandemic as an event that happened.

01:20:08.360 --> 01:20:11.800
[Amit Varma]: And then in a year or two, it's over and it's done and all of that.

01:20:11.800 --> 01:20:17.000
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, cholera pretty much for the whole of the 19th century and even beyond,

01:20:17.800 --> 01:20:19.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, plague does.

01:20:19.320 --> 01:20:22.360
[Amit Varma]: And as I shouldn't use the term plague does, cholera does.

01:20:22.920 --> 01:20:26.360
[Amit Varma]: And some people treat it as six separate pandemics.

01:20:26.360 --> 01:20:30.920
[Amit Varma]: But you actually point out that, quote, the six pandemic should be considered as being

01:20:30.920 --> 01:20:35.400
[Amit Varma]: nested within one large pandemic extending over a century.

01:20:35.400 --> 01:20:36.200
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:20:36.200 --> 01:20:41.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about sort of why you come to this way of thinking about it.

01:20:41.240 --> 01:20:45.720
[Guest]: Until like 15 years back, you know, the standard way about nobody would talk about one cholera

01:20:45.720 --> 01:20:46.200
[Guest]: pandemic.

01:20:46.200 --> 01:20:51.800
[Guest]: There was always the first cholera pandemic, the second one from like 1829 to 33, the third

01:20:51.800 --> 01:20:56.280
[Guest]: one from, you know, 1840s, fifth one, sixth one, seventh one, and so on.

01:20:56.280 --> 01:21:01.480
[Guest]: And this was partly because of the way cholera was characterized by writers of those times

01:21:01.480 --> 01:21:05.480
[Guest]: in the late 19th century and early 20th century when they started recording cholera as an

01:21:05.480 --> 01:21:07.560
[Guest]: event in history, the first writers on cholera.

01:21:08.200 --> 01:21:11.800
[Guest]: And all of them argued that it all started in India.

01:21:11.800 --> 01:21:16.680
[Guest]: And what they're trying to do is like point out each and every outbreak, say, in Mexico

01:21:16.680 --> 01:21:21.240
[Guest]: can be linked to it starting in India a few years before that.

01:21:21.240 --> 01:21:21.720
[Guest]: Right.

01:21:21.720 --> 01:21:23.080
[Guest]: And this was a chain of events.

01:21:23.080 --> 01:21:29.160
[Guest]: So this idea was that every outbreak in the West happened because of some start in India

01:21:29.160 --> 01:21:31.240
[Guest]: and then it got transmitted by some mechanism.

01:21:32.280 --> 01:21:36.680
[Guest]: The problem with this theory is that oftentimes there was no clear mechanism linking it to

01:21:36.680 --> 01:21:37.480
[Guest]: India.

01:21:37.480 --> 01:21:42.360
[Guest]: You know, Japan, for example, you know, it had outbreaks in many years in the 19th century,

01:21:42.360 --> 01:21:43.560
[Guest]: but often there's really no connection.

01:21:43.560 --> 01:21:48.440
[Guest]: So connection could come from ships, you know, from people getting off and then contaminating

01:21:48.440 --> 01:21:49.480
[Guest]: waters and so on.

01:21:49.480 --> 01:21:53.800
[Guest]: So this mystery was actually clarified only in the last 15 years, where people realize

01:21:53.800 --> 01:21:58.280
[Guest]: actually cholera vibrio can become endemic, which means it can sustain itself in certain

01:21:58.280 --> 01:21:59.480
[Guest]: water systems.

01:21:59.480 --> 01:22:01.960
[Guest]: So you don't need like a continuous transmission.

01:22:01.960 --> 01:22:07.640
[Guest]: Once it settles down in certain maritime systems, it can kind of lead to outbreaks

01:22:07.640 --> 01:22:09.880
[Guest]: nested from those systems themselves.

01:22:09.880 --> 01:22:14.600
[Guest]: So the key is, how does the 1817 strain move around the world?

01:22:14.600 --> 01:22:19.400
[Guest]: And so plausible hypothesis is that it moved around in the first 10 or 20 years, and then

01:22:19.400 --> 01:22:23.880
[Guest]: it settled down and became endemic in certain parts, and it kind of grew out from there.

01:22:23.880 --> 01:22:27.000
[Guest]: So in such a reading, then you don't get multiple pandemics.

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:32.600
[Guest]: You're really talking about one large pandemic in the sense that there were outbreaks in

01:22:32.600 --> 01:22:38.440
[Guest]: certain times of the year, and only in certain years, it could be activated by reasons concerning

01:22:38.440 --> 01:22:40.600
[Guest]: the survival prospects of cholera vibrio.

01:22:40.600 --> 01:22:45.720
[Guest]: But beyond that, you know, to point out each and every wave of the pandemic to India was

01:22:45.720 --> 01:22:46.360
[Guest]: seen to be faulty.

01:22:46.360 --> 01:22:49.720
[Guest]: So you now have a research paper in Japan, which basically shows that actually all those

01:22:49.720 --> 01:22:55.160
[Guest]: outbreaks were not linked with India, especially in the later part of the 19th century.

01:22:55.160 --> 01:22:56.120
[Guest]: It was more endemic.

01:22:56.120 --> 01:22:57.640
[Guest]: It was completely happening within.

01:22:57.640 --> 01:23:03.960
[Guest]: And so this new research actually is overturning earlier research, which showed cholera in

01:23:03.960 --> 01:23:05.560
[Guest]: terms of waves of pandemics.

01:23:05.560 --> 01:23:10.120
[Guest]: And so there's a good one biography of cholera, again, focusing mainly on the endemic

01:23:10.120 --> 01:23:15.880
[Guest]: focusing mainly on the West, which basically now makes this very strong case of not calling

01:23:15.880 --> 01:23:20.120
[Guest]: it six different pandemics, but calling it one pandemic.

01:23:20.120 --> 01:23:21.960
[Guest]: So I'm in a way following that line.

01:23:21.960 --> 01:23:26.200
[Guest]: It's really very cutting edge research of the last 10 years, which is actually showing

01:23:26.200 --> 01:23:31.080
[Guest]: new kind of it's shedding new light on cholera and how cholera can transmit and become endemic

01:23:31.080 --> 01:23:31.800
[Guest]: in certain parts.

01:23:31.800 --> 01:23:34.920
[Guest]: So that's the kind of line which I take in this book.

01:23:34.920 --> 01:23:37.640
[Guest]: That is not all of this was linked with India.

01:23:37.640 --> 01:23:41.960
[Guest]: And this new strain of cholera, which exists in the world today, started roughly in the

01:23:41.960 --> 01:23:43.000
[Guest]: 1860s.

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:47.560
[Guest]: And most people point out to, again, a mutation which happens roughly around Indonesia.

01:23:47.560 --> 01:23:51.240
[Guest]: You know, and it's now this strain which is found across the world.

01:23:51.240 --> 01:23:53.240
[Guest]: Nobody talks about cholera today.

01:23:53.240 --> 01:23:53.880
[Guest]: It's still there.

01:23:53.880 --> 01:23:57.800
[Guest]: You know, it still hurts some people because it's so easy to treat it today.

01:23:57.800 --> 01:24:02.440
[Guest]: You know, so that's why it's no longer an important disease for us to kind of be worried

01:24:02.440 --> 01:24:02.920
[Guest]: with.

01:24:02.920 --> 01:24:06.920
[Guest]: But the strain mutation, the two big ones happened in 1870, it looks like.

01:24:06.920 --> 01:24:09.000
[Guest]: And one in the 1960s.

01:24:09.640 --> 01:24:09.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:24:09.880 --> 01:24:14.280
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you speaking of Indonesia, you pointed out about how as it spread across

01:24:14.280 --> 01:24:19.240
[Amit Varma]: Asia, 17,000 people died in what was then called Batavia, now Jakarta.

01:24:19.240 --> 01:24:22.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it's spreading through East Asia, spreading through West Asia, where you

01:24:22.360 --> 01:24:24.840
[Amit Varma]: speak of 15,000 people dying in Basra.

01:24:24.840 --> 01:24:29.800
[Amit Varma]: And you also sort of talk about and this again struck a chord of, you know, in terms of how

01:24:29.800 --> 01:24:33.560
[Amit Varma]: it must have been for a common person to watch someone in his family just die, where you

01:24:33.560 --> 01:24:38.280
[Amit Varma]: write quote, in boats and caravans and in deserts and plateaus, people watched in horror,

01:24:38.280 --> 01:24:42.280
[Amit Varma]: the passing of rice water stools, and the subsequent deaths, stop code.

01:24:42.280 --> 01:24:46.520
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that once you know, mentally, you've connected the two, it must be such

01:24:46.520 --> 01:24:48.120
[Amit Varma]: a feeling of terror.

01:24:48.120 --> 01:24:51.800
[Amit Varma]: When someone close to you gets rice water stools for the first time, like, you know,

01:24:51.800 --> 01:24:55.320
[Amit Varma]: it's almost beyond imagination.

01:24:55.320 --> 01:24:59.080
[Amit Varma]: The other sort of interesting thing that you speak about was that, look, there were four

01:24:59.080 --> 01:25:04.520
[Amit Varma]: big diseases of the 19th century, as you say, cholera, plague, smallpox, typhus, and cholera

01:25:04.520 --> 01:25:07.400
[Amit Varma]: actually took much fewer lives and malaria.

01:25:07.400 --> 01:25:12.920
[Amit Varma]: So and yet it dominates a popular imagination in a much greater sense, you know, you have

01:25:12.920 --> 01:25:16.920
[Amit Varma]: love in the time of cholera, you don't have love in the time of anopheles mosquito.

01:25:16.920 --> 01:25:17.960
[Amit Varma]: So why is that?

01:25:17.960 --> 01:25:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Is it because of the way that people just it happens, and they just die and much more

01:25:22.120 --> 01:25:26.280
[Amit Varma]: sort of viscerally shocking, you know, what are the reasons behind that?

01:25:26.280 --> 01:25:29.240
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it's to do the symptoms, though I should, you know, correct you, we do have

01:25:29.240 --> 01:25:33.240
[Guest]: Nana Partekar's dialogue, Ek Machhar, you know, so we do blame the mosquito, at least

01:25:33.240 --> 01:25:35.000
[Guest]: for some reasons.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:39.800
[Guest]: But, but you're right, you know, there is, we don't see malaria kills so many people

01:25:39.800 --> 01:25:42.920
[Guest]: even today, you know, we don't call it a pandemic.

01:25:42.920 --> 01:25:46.920
[Guest]: It's because it's endemic in certain regions, but there's no real clear evidence of it transmitting

01:25:46.920 --> 01:25:50.440
[Guest]: itself across time, like how cholera, plague and influenza did.

01:25:50.440 --> 01:25:54.760
[Guest]: That's why we don't call it pandemic, it's far more deadly in terms of, you know, actual

01:25:54.760 --> 01:25:59.080
[Guest]: deaths taken, even in this age of pandemics, they're saying 70 million people died because

01:25:59.080 --> 01:26:01.800
[Guest]: of these pandemics, but malaria actually killed more people.

01:26:01.800 --> 01:26:04.680
[Guest]: So malaria was always the number one sort of killer.

01:26:04.680 --> 01:26:09.560
[Guest]: So the difference between cholera and plague, and some of these other epidemics is precisely

01:26:09.560 --> 01:26:14.280
[Guest]: the symptoms, you know, with plague, it was this bubo, which basically got these big sort

01:26:14.280 --> 01:26:15.880
[Guest]: of boils on your on your body.

01:26:16.600 --> 01:26:18.280
[Guest]: And in cholera, it was these rice voters too.

01:26:18.280 --> 01:26:22.280
[Guest]: So there's no doubt that there's some kind of horror attached with cholera and plague,

01:26:22.280 --> 01:26:23.800
[Unknown]: which did not happen with malaria.

01:26:23.800 --> 01:26:25.800
[Unknown]: I mean, the symptoms of malaria were high fever.

01:26:25.800 --> 01:26:31.800
[Guest]: You know, that is, you didn't start growing stuff in your body, or you didn't, you know,

01:26:31.800 --> 01:26:35.480
[Guest]: have to go to the toilet a thousand times, like in the case of cholera.

01:26:35.480 --> 01:26:40.440
[Guest]: So there's no doubt that this added to this, you know, this fear of cholera throughout.

01:26:40.440 --> 01:26:45.080
[Guest]: And when it started transmitting, as you said, basically, we see a guy, you know, suffer

01:26:45.080 --> 01:26:48.440
[Guest]: with this, it really became a talking point.

01:26:48.440 --> 01:26:54.680
[Guest]: And so it became a very, you know, very quickly, people started hating the whole idea of getting

01:26:54.680 --> 01:26:56.600
[Amit Varma]: cholera rather than getting, say, malaria.

01:26:56.600 --> 01:27:00.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I guess, you know, the basic symptoms of malaria, like fever, shiver also happened

01:27:00.200 --> 01:27:01.240
[Amit Varma]: for many other things.

01:27:01.240 --> 01:27:05.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, you know, you can recover from a fever, but can you recover

01:27:05.320 --> 01:27:06.440
[Amit Varma]: from loose motions?

01:27:06.440 --> 01:27:09.640
[Amit Varma]: This is not a question we would ask ourselves today.

01:27:09.640 --> 01:27:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And you know, among the many sort of historical consequences that you point out, the one that

01:27:14.520 --> 01:27:20.760
[Amit Varma]: kind of struck me was the one about the 1857 rebellion, or the First War of Independence,

01:27:20.760 --> 01:27:23.320
[Amit Varma]: or whatever one calls it, and chapatis.

01:27:23.320 --> 01:27:25.240
[Amit Varma]: What do chapatis have to do with cholera?

01:27:25.240 --> 01:27:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Just tell me about that.

01:27:27.080 --> 01:27:33.320
[Guest]: It is a debate among historians, you know, but what did the circulation of chapatis convey?

01:27:33.320 --> 01:27:38.040
[Guest]: And one line of reasoning is that it conveyed the incoming of epidemics.

01:27:38.040 --> 01:27:42.680
[Guest]: So what this, so just to tell you the system, basically, a village would send out this,

01:27:42.680 --> 01:27:47.960
[Guest]: let's call him a postman, you know, postal person, and this person would give literally

01:27:47.960 --> 01:27:51.400
[Guest]: a box of chapatis, you know, to the next village, and so on.

01:27:51.400 --> 01:27:54.040
[Guest]: And so it's like a relay network of chapatis.

01:27:54.040 --> 01:27:58.840
[Guest]: And this was, it's a historical fact that this was observed in 1857, you know, a few

01:27:59.400 --> 01:28:02.840
[Guest]: months before the actual outbreak began.

01:28:02.840 --> 01:28:07.160
[Guest]: And there's actually a research paper now, which connects the dots and says that towns

01:28:07.160 --> 01:28:13.720
[Guest]: which got this chapati circulation, basically, as a proxy for impending cholera, you know,

01:28:13.720 --> 01:28:19.240
[Guest]: heightened the kind of prejudice of people against the British and made them act more.

01:28:19.240 --> 01:28:21.640
[Guest]: So it's an interesting line of causation.

01:28:22.280 --> 01:28:27.000
[Guest]: But this idea of chapati circulation, as an interesting traditional knowledge, you can

01:28:27.000 --> 01:28:32.920
[Guest]: call it, to warn others that, you know, cholera has come, cholera is in town, right, is a

01:28:32.920 --> 01:28:35.160
[Guest]: very interesting and attractive proposition.

01:28:35.160 --> 01:28:36.840
[Guest]: But I should say that it's contentious.

01:28:36.840 --> 01:28:38.360
[Guest]: Not all historians agree.

01:28:38.360 --> 01:28:41.400
[Guest]: There are different interpretations of what chapati circulation meant.

01:28:41.400 --> 01:28:45.640
[Guest]: But I think in this book, I think this idea that it was actually connected very closely

01:28:45.640 --> 01:28:46.440
[Guest]: with cholera.

01:28:46.440 --> 01:28:51.720
[Guest]: And coming to that, you know, 1857, such an important year in Indian history, nobody really

01:28:51.720 --> 01:28:56.760
[Guest]: thinks of it as cholera year, you know, but it is a fact that cholera preceded the outbreak.

01:28:56.760 --> 01:29:02.360
[Guest]: And a lot of people died, more people died from cholera, rather than arguably the massive

01:29:02.360 --> 01:29:03.960
[Guest]: uprising in that year.

01:29:03.960 --> 01:29:09.080
[Amit Varma]: No, I know many hipsters on a gluten free diet who would argue that chapatis are a problem

01:29:09.080 --> 01:29:10.200
[Amit Varma]: in and of themselves.

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, tell me a little bit about the toll of this.

01:29:14.120 --> 01:29:17.480
[Amit Varma]: And also, I was intrigued by something that you've pointed out when you're talking about

01:29:17.480 --> 01:29:22.520
[Amit Varma]: the toll that, you know, you have estimated that 40 million Indians died due to cholera

01:29:22.520 --> 01:29:29.640
[Amit Varma]: between 1817 and 1920, which works out to, you know, 300,000 deaths every year, 5% of

01:29:29.640 --> 01:29:32.360
[Amit Varma]: all deaths in the Indian subcontinent during this period.

01:29:32.360 --> 01:29:35.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, sort of one, you've pointed out that this is your estimate.

01:29:35.640 --> 01:29:39.560
[Amit Varma]: Secondly, you know, he later when talking about influenza, which we'll also chat about,

01:29:39.560 --> 01:29:44.040
[Amit Varma]: you've pointed out about how, for the longest time, people believe that the figure of the

01:29:44.040 --> 01:29:47.960
[Amit Varma]: number of people dead was one of the early figures that were cited at that time, which

01:29:47.960 --> 01:29:50.680
[Amit Varma]: is 6 million, but actually 20 million people died.

01:29:50.680 --> 01:29:55.400
[Amit Varma]: So some of the work that has gone into this is actually your original research, looking

01:29:55.400 --> 01:29:57.720
[Amit Varma]: at the numbers and figuring this stuff out.

01:29:57.720 --> 01:30:02.440
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how did you do this, what was your methodology, and so

01:30:02.440 --> 01:30:03.480
[Amit Varma]: on and so forth.

01:30:03.480 --> 01:30:07.480
[Guest]: Yeah, this is where the training in economics and also demography, I mean, the connecting

01:30:07.480 --> 01:30:10.520
[Guest]: theme between the first book and second book is actually demography.

01:30:10.520 --> 01:30:14.600
[Guest]: Demographers basically study three things, fertility, mortality, and migration.

01:30:14.600 --> 01:30:17.080
[Guest]: And my first book is about migration, and this book is about mortality.

01:30:17.080 --> 01:30:18.760
[Guest]: So the connecting theme is demography.

01:30:19.400 --> 01:30:23.320
[Guest]: And I've been exposed to a lot of demographic research methods, how do you estimate death

01:30:23.320 --> 01:30:26.280
[Guest]: with, you know, very few data points, and so on.

01:30:26.280 --> 01:30:31.320
[Guest]: So our death statistics, in fact, this is a side note, it's precisely because of the

01:30:31.320 --> 01:30:35.640
[Guest]: cholera pandemic that we actually started recording deaths systematically in India.

01:30:35.640 --> 01:30:40.920
[Guest]: So this process starts in the early 1860s, after a series of devastating cholera outbreaks

01:30:40.920 --> 01:30:42.360
[Guest]: in the years following that.

01:30:42.360 --> 01:30:46.360
[Guest]: And the British start the system mainly to monitor the health of their army, right?

01:30:46.360 --> 01:30:48.680
[Guest]: So they're not really doing it for the native population.

01:30:48.680 --> 01:30:51.480
[Unknown]: But very quickly, they realize there's a need to do that.

01:30:51.480 --> 01:30:55.480
[Guest]: They need to sort of document systematically what's happening in the native population.

01:30:55.480 --> 01:31:01.480
[Guest]: So India's death registration system, like we have today, the origins of it are the 1860s.

01:31:01.480 --> 01:31:08.040
[Guest]: And from the 1870s, annually, province-wise, sometimes even district-wise, the British

01:31:08.040 --> 01:31:12.040
[Guest]: systematically collected deaths and the causes of deaths.

01:31:12.040 --> 01:31:13.720
[Guest]: Now, obviously, there are huge problems.

01:31:13.720 --> 01:31:17.800
[Guest]: You know, the person reporting these deaths was not a well-trained medical doctor.

01:31:17.800 --> 01:31:21.400
[Guest]: It was often the village patwari or the tax person, you know, at the village level.

01:31:21.400 --> 01:31:23.400
[Guest]: So a lot of, you know, issues around that.

01:31:23.400 --> 01:31:27.480
[Guest]: But the general trend that you will see kind of mimics what is happening.

01:31:27.480 --> 01:31:31.320
[Guest]: So in some years, if there were a lot of plague cases, you would see a spike in plague cases.

01:31:31.320 --> 01:31:36.440
[Guest]: So what I have on a spreadsheet now is a province-level database of all the deaths

01:31:36.440 --> 01:31:38.440
[Guest]: between 1870 and 1940s.

01:31:38.440 --> 01:31:39.880
[Guest]: So that's what 70 years data.

01:31:40.440 --> 01:31:43.960
[Guest]: Now, that's a great database for plague, which starts in 1890s.

01:31:43.960 --> 01:31:47.960
[Guest]: That's a great database for influenza, which is recorded under fevers, which makes it slightly

01:31:47.960 --> 01:31:48.680
[Guest]: complicated.

01:31:48.680 --> 01:31:54.840
[Guest]: But for cholera, it's tricky, because what do I do with this period, 1817 to 1860s, where

01:31:54.840 --> 01:31:56.840
[Guest]: there's literally no database, right?

01:31:56.840 --> 01:31:57.960
[Guest]: So they're just guesstimates.

01:31:58.680 --> 01:32:00.920
[Guest]: And so on what basis does one make guesstimates?

01:32:00.920 --> 01:32:03.080
[Guest]: So I then look at all the records.

01:32:03.080 --> 01:32:05.160
[Guest]: I look at, you know, the South Park cemetery records.

01:32:05.160 --> 01:32:06.280
[Guest]: I look at different records.

01:32:06.280 --> 01:32:07.320
[Guest]: And there's these projections.

01:32:07.320 --> 01:32:08.440
[Guest]: They're not perfect numbers.

01:32:09.080 --> 01:32:14.360
[Guest]: But on average, there were 300,000 people dying of cholera between the 1870s and 1910s.

01:32:14.360 --> 01:32:15.400
[Guest]: And that number is going up.

01:32:15.400 --> 01:32:21.320
[Guest]: And so what we can say for sure on the basis of that rough number, 250,000 to 300,000 deaths,

01:32:21.320 --> 01:32:24.040
[Guest]: is a certain number of millions of deaths of Indians.

01:32:24.040 --> 01:32:28.040
[Guest]: The thing with cholera, of course, was that it was partly endemic, which meant that a

01:32:28.040 --> 01:32:32.840
[Guest]: certain number of people died every year, irrespective if it was virulent.

01:32:32.840 --> 01:32:37.320
[Guest]: So in Calcutta and Eastern India, where it was endemic in those maritime systems, some

01:32:37.320 --> 01:32:38.840
[Guest]: people always died of cholera.

01:32:38.840 --> 01:32:41.880
[Guest]: How do you make a distinction between what is endemic and what is epidemic?

01:32:41.880 --> 01:32:46.040
[Guest]: So I kind of look at only those years where a clear case of epidemic, which means it's

01:32:46.040 --> 01:32:47.800
[Guest]: spread all across India, was recorded.

01:32:48.360 --> 01:32:54.920
[Guest]: And so my final numbers are 8 million deaths in India in this whole period, which is epidemic,

01:32:54.920 --> 01:32:59.000
[Guest]: but actually 31 million people, you know, which is endemic.

01:32:59.000 --> 01:33:02.680
[Guest]: And so there's so many more people who died in the average year itself.

01:33:03.320 --> 01:33:08.440
[Guest]: And so this 70 million global figure that I have in this book actually does not count

01:33:08.440 --> 01:33:12.440
[Guest]: the 31 million deaths of endemic cholera in India.

01:33:12.440 --> 01:33:16.200
[Guest]: If you add it to that 70 million, then it actually goes up to more than 100 million.

01:33:16.200 --> 01:33:19.960
[Guest]: So a lot of this death accounting, and it's a really morbid task, you know, I mean, even

01:33:19.960 --> 01:33:24.760
[Guest]: for a person trained in statistics like me, you know, just to, when you're looking at

01:33:24.760 --> 01:33:31.480
[Guest]: those numbers, I mean, just think about 300,000 deaths due to just cholera in one year, at

01:33:31.480 --> 01:33:36.280
[Guest]: a time when the population of India is one fourth of what it is today.

01:33:36.280 --> 01:33:41.400
[Guest]: And so today we are kind of under by 150,000 COVID deaths on a population, which is four

01:33:41.400 --> 01:33:42.440
[Guest]: times larger.

01:33:42.440 --> 01:33:47.160
[Guest]: So those death rates themselves are so unbelievably high back then.

01:33:47.160 --> 01:33:52.520
[Guest]: So a lot of this book, as I said, the starting point of this book was a statistical database

01:33:52.520 --> 01:33:56.440
[Guest]: to try and understand which parts of India had more mortality.

01:33:56.440 --> 01:34:02.040
[Guest]: And then in the case of cholera, you know, I have this on page 70 of the book, it's probably

01:34:02.040 --> 01:34:08.520
[Guest]: the first time somebody has given global estimates of cholera, because it's kind of tricky.

01:34:08.520 --> 01:34:10.760
[Guest]: How do you estimate cholera deaths, you know, across time.

01:34:10.760 --> 01:34:12.920
[Guest]: So people have done it for some individual countries.

01:34:12.920 --> 01:34:17.720
[Guest]: What I've just done on that table is to kind of aggregate it, again, using certain methods

01:34:17.720 --> 01:34:23.280
[Guest]: of years for which we don't have data, but it turns out that Russia had a lot of deaths.

01:34:23.280 --> 01:34:27.880
[Guest]: One famous casualty being Tchaikovsky, the famous composer, even his mother actually

01:34:27.880 --> 01:34:30.000
[Guest]: died of cholera.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:34.560
[Guest]: Then you have, you know, Spain, Hungary, France, Germany, UK, all of them about a few hundred

01:34:34.560 --> 01:34:39.920
[Guest]: thousand, but Egypt, you know, and Egypt is spectacular in terms of, I mean, the estimates

01:34:39.920 --> 01:34:44.040
[Guest]: that I have is, you know, about more than a half a million people out of a population

01:34:44.040 --> 01:34:45.040
[Guest]: of nearly 6 million.

01:34:45.040 --> 01:34:50.240
[Guest]: So that's about 10% of the population kind of getting wiped out due to just one disease,

01:34:50.240 --> 01:34:56.120
[Guest]: cholera, you know, so that's kind of a really spectacular kind of strike rate of cholera

01:34:56.120 --> 01:34:57.120
[Guest]: in Egypt.

01:34:57.120 --> 01:35:01.640
[Guest]: So that's one part of this project is to just understand who is dying and where is it dying.

01:35:01.640 --> 01:35:04.440
[Guest]: That's aided by British maintained colonial statistics.

01:35:04.440 --> 01:35:10.680
[Guest]: I should add, we actually don't know much about cholera plague and influenza in places

01:35:10.680 --> 01:35:15.120
[Guest]: where we did not record statistics, for example, the princely states in India.

01:35:15.120 --> 01:35:20.560
[Guest]: So we know much more about Madras presidency, Bombay presidency, Bengal presidency, or UP,

01:35:20.560 --> 01:35:23.800
[Guest]: or United Provinces, but we don't know much about Nizam's Hyderabad.

01:35:23.800 --> 01:35:25.120
[Guest]: We don't know much about Mysore.

01:35:25.120 --> 01:35:27.240
[Guest]: We don't know much about Rajputana.

01:35:27.240 --> 01:35:29.880
[Guest]: And that's because these statistics were never really connected.

01:35:29.880 --> 01:35:31.960
[Guest]: So I need to project for them.

01:35:31.960 --> 01:35:35.520
[Guest]: So then, you know, I use some other methods to kind of project for them based on basic

01:35:35.520 --> 01:35:37.080
[Guest]: population counts and so on.

01:35:37.080 --> 01:35:38.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:35:38.080 --> 01:35:42.040
[Amit Varma]: And lay people often think of statistics as very dry and the eyes glaze over when you

01:35:42.040 --> 01:35:46.120
[Amit Varma]: look at big numbers, but numbers are people and I guess part of the task of a skilled

01:35:46.120 --> 01:35:50.240
[Amit Varma]: historian is to sort of turn those numbers into stories.

01:35:50.240 --> 01:35:55.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've written about as cholera traveled across the world, how it was changing

01:35:55.120 --> 01:35:56.120
[Amit Varma]: history everywhere.

01:35:56.120 --> 01:36:00.640
[Amit Varma]: Like in France, you talk about how 300,000 people died and in 1832, there was actually

01:36:00.640 --> 01:36:03.360
[Amit Varma]: a rebellion out there.

01:36:03.360 --> 01:36:07.200
[Amit Varma]: In Spain, you speak about how the monarch had to come out on the streets to console

01:36:07.200 --> 01:36:10.280
[Amit Varma]: the people and tell them, don't worry, we are on top of it.

01:36:10.280 --> 01:36:16.640
[Amit Varma]: You speak about, you know, the religious revival in Marseille, which was Catholic at the time.

01:36:16.640 --> 01:36:20.280
[Amit Varma]: And interestingly, you speak about, you know, Rabindranath Tagore's grandfather, Dwarkanath

01:36:20.280 --> 01:36:22.600
[Amit Varma]: Tagore donating money to France.

01:36:22.600 --> 01:36:27.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, how much pride something like that would give our nationalists today.

01:36:27.080 --> 01:36:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about the consequences of cholera on India.

01:36:30.000 --> 01:36:35.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, not just in terms of deaths, but politics, economics, society itself.

01:36:35.400 --> 01:36:39.320
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that because it lasted such a long time and took so many lives,

01:36:39.320 --> 01:36:40.320
[Amit Varma]: 40 million people.

01:36:40.320 --> 01:36:42.600
[Guest]: Yeah, I think two very clearly discernible.

01:36:42.600 --> 01:36:44.320
[Guest]: One is of course, 1857.

01:36:44.320 --> 01:36:49.000
[Guest]: So we should start talking more about how the pandemic was a backdrop under which the

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:50.000
[Guest]: revolution took place.

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:51.000
[Guest]: One is on health.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:56.040
[Guest]: You know, there's definitely a, you know, greater demand from the people to improve

01:36:56.040 --> 01:36:57.040
[Guest]: public health.

01:36:57.040 --> 01:37:01.360
[Guest]: It's not a big demand, but that's, you know, one important aspect of how it started.

01:37:01.360 --> 01:37:02.360
[Guest]: Death registration statistics.

01:37:02.360 --> 01:37:06.720
[Guest]: The whole idea of tabulating death is a consequence of the pandemic.

01:37:06.720 --> 01:37:11.400
[Guest]: That's existing with us even today, you know, what we call as a sample registration system.

01:37:11.400 --> 01:37:15.880
[Guest]: That's a 40 year history, but the real roots of recording death in India start from the

01:37:15.880 --> 01:37:16.880
[Guest]: 1860s, the cholera pandemic.

01:37:16.880 --> 01:37:20.800
[Guest]: A lot of interesting, you know, things, of course, some important people are killed by,

01:37:20.800 --> 01:37:24.080
[Guest]: you know, even in 1857, some British generals are killed.

01:37:24.080 --> 01:37:30.120
[Guest]: There's this guy in Calcutta, a young 22 year old guy, Henry de Borio, and he's basically

01:37:30.120 --> 01:37:35.960
[Guest]: sort of, he dies at 22, but he's a staunch Anglo-Portuguese person who is criticizing

01:37:35.960 --> 01:37:40.040
[Guest]: British rule, you know, and unfortunately his death, he dies at a very young age because

01:37:40.040 --> 01:37:41.040
[Guest]: of cholera.

01:37:41.040 --> 01:37:44.920
[Guest]: Raja Ram Mohan Roy has this very interesting thing about cholera, and this is a larger

01:37:44.920 --> 01:37:45.920
[Unknown]: thing about epidemics.

01:37:45.920 --> 01:37:50.920
[Guest]: He says, obviously epidemics are horrible because they kill a lot of people, but when

01:37:50.920 --> 01:37:55.360
[Guest]: you have so many people like in India, in a labor surplus kind of country, could that

01:37:55.360 --> 01:37:59.440
[Guest]: actually improve the lives of people who are left alive, you know?

01:37:59.440 --> 01:38:02.880
[Guest]: And that's the whole reasoning between the black death and it kills so many people that

01:38:02.880 --> 01:38:07.340
[Guest]: those who survived actually worked with more capital and productivity increased.

01:38:07.340 --> 01:38:10.240
[Guest]: And Raja Ram Mohan Roy has this argument, but I couldn't find too much of reference

01:38:10.240 --> 01:38:11.240
[Guest]: with cholera.

01:38:11.240 --> 01:38:15.560
[Guest]: I found more with plague and influenza, that it had positive consequences for those who

01:38:15.560 --> 01:38:16.560
[Guest]: survived.

01:38:16.560 --> 01:38:17.560
[Guest]: For cholera, not so much.

01:38:17.560 --> 01:38:22.280
[Guest]: It kind of, you know, in Europe, the impact was very clear, they had cholera riots.

01:38:22.280 --> 01:38:24.080
[Guest]: So you had like violence attached with cholera.

01:38:24.080 --> 01:38:28.720
[Guest]: I mean, I write, you know, the cholera outbreaks in Europe coincided with, you know, Europe's

01:38:28.720 --> 01:38:34.120
[Guest]: revolutionary war of year of 1848, the Crimean War in the 1850s, the overthrow of the German

01:38:34.120 --> 01:38:40.360
[Guest]: Confederation 1866, the end of France's second empire in 1871, and also in Russian Poland

01:38:40.360 --> 01:38:41.360
[Guest]: in 1892.

01:38:41.360 --> 01:38:46.440
[Guest]: So, important events in history, which actually coincided, you know, important political events

01:38:46.440 --> 01:38:51.860
[Guest]: in both European and Indian history, we talked about 1857, which coincided.

01:38:51.860 --> 01:38:56.960
[Guest]: The other part is that cholera coincided very much with famines.

01:38:56.960 --> 01:39:02.080
[Guest]: Because what would famines do is, you know, famines also classic starvation kind of deaths,

01:39:02.080 --> 01:39:07.200
[Guest]: it would drive people outside in the search of water, because what is a famine in India,

01:39:07.200 --> 01:39:10.160
[Guest]: it was basically bad, lack of rainfall.

01:39:10.160 --> 01:39:15.360
[Guest]: And in that process, people would congregate towards certain centers where they would find

01:39:15.360 --> 01:39:16.600
[Guest]: water.

01:39:16.600 --> 01:39:21.200
[Guest]: And that is how with contaminated water, basically, cholera would, you know, just rip through

01:39:21.200 --> 01:39:22.720
[Guest]: those populations.

01:39:22.720 --> 01:39:28.600
[Guest]: So in India's great famine years, like 1899, 1900, or, you know, 1877, 1878, those are

01:39:28.600 --> 01:39:31.160
[Guest]: the years that cholera really shot through the roof.

01:39:31.160 --> 01:39:35.320
[Guest]: So cholera also in interaction with famines made it much worse.

01:39:35.320 --> 01:39:39.280
[Guest]: And so the public health officials had to really, you know, scamper around.

01:39:39.280 --> 01:39:45.880
[Guest]: The biggest implication, of course, of cholera was WHO itself, that it is because of cholera,

01:39:45.880 --> 01:39:49.040
[Guest]: that you had this first conference in 1851.

01:39:49.040 --> 01:39:53.160
[Guest]: It is the first example of a global health surveillance system, though, of course, it

01:39:53.160 --> 01:39:57.000
[Guest]: was pretty much European imperial powers plus the Ottoman Empire trying to understand how

01:39:57.000 --> 01:39:58.520
[Guest]: to prevent cholera.

01:39:58.520 --> 01:40:04.840
[Guest]: But that is really, they had a series of conferences, 1851, then another one, then 1866, series

01:40:04.840 --> 01:40:06.280
[Guest]: of conferences.

01:40:06.280 --> 01:40:09.520
[Guest]: That turns out then later, once the League of Nations is formed, it's the same set of

01:40:09.520 --> 01:40:13.440
[Guest]: conference people who make a kind of a department.

01:40:13.440 --> 01:40:19.040
[Guest]: And that is the genesis of the World Health Organization in 1948, and the WHO, which call

01:40:19.040 --> 01:40:20.600
[Guest]: it a pandemic in 2020.

01:40:20.600 --> 01:40:27.120
[Guest]: So you can see this unbroken kind of, you know, line connecting cholera and the first

01:40:27.120 --> 01:40:32.720
[Guest]: conference of 1851, and WHO announcing it, because it's all linked, you know, it's all

01:40:32.720 --> 01:40:38.320
[Guest]: part of that same thing, how do we spread a disease from traveling globally?

01:40:38.320 --> 01:40:43.520
[Amit Varma]: What was also fascinating to me was, I thought this will be like, you know, a linear recounting

01:40:43.520 --> 01:40:47.440
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that you have three chapters, cholera, plague and influenza, but they all

01:40:47.440 --> 01:40:48.600
[Amit Varma]: kind of overlap.

01:40:48.600 --> 01:40:53.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, by the time you get to say something like 1918, all these are happening, plus there

01:40:53.520 --> 01:40:58.080
[Amit Varma]: is a monsoon that has been disastrous, and everything is just haywire, like you speak

01:40:58.080 --> 01:41:02.800
[Amit Varma]: about how the previous year, there was too much rainfall, which was a problem, and the

01:41:02.800 --> 01:41:04.920
[Amit Varma]: next year, there is too little rainfall.

01:41:04.920 --> 01:41:09.160
[Amit Varma]: And you know, everything is just happening at the same time, along with imperialism,

01:41:09.160 --> 01:41:10.160
[Amit Varma]: of course.

01:41:10.160 --> 01:41:14.760
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of move on from cholera now, as in fact, you know, humanity is done because

01:41:14.760 --> 01:41:19.240
[Amit Varma]: it's pretty much, it's virtually a problem that we have solved, and talk about the plague.

01:41:19.240 --> 01:41:24.920
[Amit Varma]: Now the plague's been sort of around for much longer in the consciousness, like I love this

01:41:24.920 --> 01:41:30.640
[Amit Varma]: quote with which you started this chapter, which is from, you know, about 1615, from

01:41:30.640 --> 01:41:36.880
[Amit Varma]: Iqbal Namai Jahangiri, and I'll read it out, quote, when it was about to break out, a mouse

01:41:36.880 --> 01:41:41.120
[Amit Varma]: would rush out of its hole as if mad, and striking itself against the door and the walls

01:41:41.120 --> 01:41:42.800
[Amit Varma]: of the house would expire.

01:41:42.800 --> 01:41:46.960
[Amit Varma]: If immediately after this signal, the occupants left the house and went away to the jungle,

01:41:46.960 --> 01:41:47.960
[Amit Varma]: their lives were saved.

01:41:47.960 --> 01:41:52.200
[Amit Varma]: If otherwise, the inhabitants of the whole village would be swept away by the hand of

01:41:52.200 --> 01:41:53.200
[Amit Varma]: death.

01:41:53.200 --> 01:41:56.640
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, which is, you know, the hand of death is also a striking phrase, it just,

01:41:56.640 --> 01:42:00.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, and this was written before Adam Smith's invisible hand.

01:42:00.480 --> 01:42:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is also a kind of invisible hand, what a morbid thought.

01:42:04.000 --> 01:42:09.600
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about how sort of plague is looked at in India and how it comes to

01:42:09.600 --> 01:42:14.040
[Amit Varma]: India and in fact, plague at the end of the 1890s didn't even necessarily originate here,

01:42:14.040 --> 01:42:17.520
[Amit Varma]: like you point out, it's happening in Hong Kong, it's happening in China.

01:42:17.520 --> 01:42:22.760
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this and how it is kind of different from, you know, cholera,

01:42:22.760 --> 01:42:24.240
[Amit Varma]: which came before and all of that.

01:42:24.240 --> 01:42:29.440
[Guest]: Yeah, firstly, it was, you know, plague is history's greatest disease, if you had to

01:42:29.440 --> 01:42:33.760
[Guest]: put an honour on the like, you know, the great in terms of, you know, this sheer sort of

01:42:33.760 --> 01:42:37.560
[Guest]: glamour value attached to it in terms of what it can do, and so on.

01:42:37.560 --> 01:42:38.560
[Guest]: Why?

01:42:38.560 --> 01:42:39.920
[Guest]: Because the Black Death was about the plague, right?

01:42:39.920 --> 01:42:44.720
[Guest]: So that was one third of Europe, it was a big moment in European history.

01:42:44.720 --> 01:42:48.200
[Guest]: Events of plague attacks in Indian history, it must have happened, you know, because we're

01:42:48.200 --> 01:42:51.200
[Guest]: saying plague is also endemic among rodents and so on.

01:42:51.200 --> 01:42:56.400
[Guest]: Again, so for those who don't know, plague is, we now know that plague is about a bacteria,

01:42:56.400 --> 01:43:01.080
[Guest]: Yersinia pestis, as it's called, discovered in the late 19th century.

01:43:01.080 --> 01:43:06.120
[Guest]: But until 1890s, nobody knew what really causes plague, you know.

01:43:06.120 --> 01:43:10.960
[Guest]: And as you pointed out, all people knew was that rodents and especially rats or mice started

01:43:10.960 --> 01:43:11.960
[Guest]: dying in large numbers.

01:43:11.960 --> 01:43:16.240
[Guest]: And if you saw that happening, just get out, that was the sort of standard operating procedure

01:43:16.240 --> 01:43:17.960
[Guest]: regarding plague.

01:43:17.960 --> 01:43:22.880
[Guest]: I do note in the book, and you know, I want to claim this as my little small contribution,

01:43:22.880 --> 01:43:28.560
[Guest]: that the Arthashastra has certain references, you know, which seem remarkable about rats

01:43:28.560 --> 01:43:29.560
[Guest]: and rodents.

01:43:29.560 --> 01:43:31.420
[Guest]: And they also talk about rat attacks and so on.

01:43:31.420 --> 01:43:33.840
[Guest]: And all of these things came into play in the 20th century.

01:43:33.840 --> 01:43:37.920
[Guest]: And I make this argument that maybe, I speculate, that maybe what the Arthashastra is referring

01:43:37.920 --> 01:43:39.280
[Guest]: to was the plague outbreak.

01:43:39.280 --> 01:43:42.480
[Guest]: This is something medical historians have not yet revealed.

01:43:42.480 --> 01:43:47.040
[Guest]: But plague has sort of always been there in the Indian subcontinent.

01:43:47.040 --> 01:43:51.960
[Guest]: But it never became so big as, we don't have evidence of it becoming so big as it did in

01:43:51.960 --> 01:43:55.000
[Guest]: the late 19th and early 20th century.

01:43:55.000 --> 01:43:59.440
[Guest]: And the fundamental way it kind of works, we now know, is from, it comes from rodents

01:43:59.440 --> 01:44:03.800
[Guest]: to humans via the bite of a rat flea.

01:44:03.800 --> 01:44:07.760
[Guest]: But this transmission mechanism and just unraveling that mechanism itself is, you know, one can

01:44:07.760 --> 01:44:11.760
[Guest]: write books on that, it is so fascinating, that whole debate.

01:44:11.760 --> 01:44:17.040
[Guest]: But in the 19th century, it's not that, you know, in fact, my understanding of plague

01:44:17.040 --> 01:44:20.360
[Guest]: was that it comes to India out of nowhere in 1896.

01:44:20.360 --> 01:44:23.920
[Guest]: But even in India in the 19th century, you know, it hits Ahmedabad in 1814, I think,

01:44:23.920 --> 01:44:28.120
[Guest]: you know, early part of the 19th century, it hits Ahmedabad and there are gruesome accounts

01:44:28.120 --> 01:44:29.360
[Guest]: of plague.

01:44:29.360 --> 01:44:33.200
[Guest]: And the thing with plague, even more than cholera, so in cholera, the bad things, you

01:44:33.200 --> 01:44:37.920
[Guest]: keep going, you know, you keep going to the toilet, in plague, you can see it, you know,

01:44:37.920 --> 01:44:41.920
[Guest]: there are these large black lumps, which develop in your body.

01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:45.560
[Guest]: So this is almost a bit like leprosy in the sense that this is a disease which kind of

01:44:45.560 --> 01:44:47.760
[Guest]: leaves its mark on its victims.

01:44:47.760 --> 01:44:50.640
[Guest]: And of course, there are different types of plague, there's also mnemonic plague, which

01:44:50.640 --> 01:44:53.960
[Guest]: is, you know, which does not leave such marks necessarily.

01:44:53.960 --> 01:44:57.880
[Guest]: But the principle, the classic, you know, plague leaves these marks and they stand out

01:44:57.880 --> 01:45:01.600
[Guest]: in, and that's why it's also recorded by travelers.

01:45:01.600 --> 01:45:05.520
[Guest]: And we have more evidence of plague in history than many other diseases.

01:45:05.520 --> 01:45:09.040
[Guest]: So it really breaks out in a big way in China.

01:45:09.040 --> 01:45:11.640
[Guest]: The way historians have classified is three pandemics.

01:45:11.640 --> 01:45:14.720
[Guest]: So the first one is called the Justinian plague.

01:45:14.720 --> 01:45:18.720
[Guest]: And new research is suggesting that it was not as big as it was previously thought, kind

01:45:18.720 --> 01:45:23.400
[Guest]: of affected the Mediterranean world, you know, so this place around, you know, Egypt, Turkey

01:45:23.400 --> 01:45:29.480
[Guest]: today, and this is we're talking about, you know, the sixth century CE, the time of Emperor

01:45:29.480 --> 01:45:31.840
[Guest]: Justinian of the Byzantine Empire.

01:45:31.840 --> 01:45:34.440
[Guest]: So that's one, the first plague pandemic as it's called.

01:45:34.440 --> 01:45:39.560
[Guest]: The second plague pandemic is Europe in between 1348 and 1353.

01:45:39.560 --> 01:45:43.920
[Guest]: But there are repeated plague outbreaks throughout Europe, you know, until the 1700s.

01:45:43.920 --> 01:45:48.200
[Guest]: So London, for example, most famously was ravaged first by the plague and then by fire,

01:45:48.200 --> 01:45:51.400
[Guest]: and this is in 1660s or so.

01:45:51.400 --> 01:45:55.640
[Guest]: But plague kind of stops, you know, it hits, I think the last time it hits Europe in a

01:45:55.640 --> 01:46:00.720
[Guest]: big way is Marseilles, if I'm not mistaken, 1720s, but after that, it doesn't hit Europe.

01:46:00.720 --> 01:46:04.400
[Guest]: After that, it's pretty much China, you know, and so that's where the accounts of plague

01:46:04.400 --> 01:46:05.400
[Guest]: come.

01:46:05.400 --> 01:46:09.520
[Guest]: It's pretty much Egypt, interestingly, and also India.

01:46:09.520 --> 01:46:15.000
[Guest]: And so when it breaks out in a big way in China in the 1850s and 1860s and 1870s, it

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:18.100
[Guest]: really captures the imagination of a lot of doctors.

01:46:18.100 --> 01:46:23.080
[Guest]: But it becomes a global issue when it reaches Hong Kong in 1894.

01:46:23.080 --> 01:46:27.600
[Guest]: And that's when we kind of start saying, you know, the third plague pandemic really begins

01:46:27.600 --> 01:46:31.240
[Guest]: because from Hong Kong, then it goes around the world because Hong Kong was a major trade

01:46:31.240 --> 01:46:32.240
[Guest]: center.

01:46:32.240 --> 01:46:36.600
[Guest]: It also, you know, exported a lot of food grains and food grains was a classic sort

01:46:36.600 --> 01:46:39.400
[Guest]: of storage point where rodents would go.

01:46:39.400 --> 01:46:43.040
[Guest]: And that is how, you know, that's the association between food grains, rodents, and the spread

01:46:43.040 --> 01:46:45.720
[Guest]: of plague, which is a classic transmission mechanism.

01:46:45.720 --> 01:46:49.920
[Guest]: And so from China, the most accepted theory is that it came to Bombay from Hong Kong and

01:46:49.920 --> 01:46:51.400
[Guest]: from Bombay, it spread everywhere.

01:46:51.400 --> 01:46:54.000
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean that there was no plague before that.

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:55.520
[Guest]: There was plague in Garhwal.

01:46:55.520 --> 01:46:56.520
[Guest]: It was called actually Mahamari.

01:46:56.520 --> 01:46:59.520
[Guest]: Mahamari is the word today we use for pandemic.

01:46:59.520 --> 01:47:03.960
[Guest]: The word epidemic, by the way, in, you know, in Indian language, it's either Mari or Mari.

01:47:03.960 --> 01:47:04.960
[Guest]: Okay.

01:47:04.960 --> 01:47:07.760
[Guest]: Used in different contexts for at least more than a thousand years, I think.

01:47:07.760 --> 01:47:11.040
[Guest]: More of Mari in North India and more of Mari in South India.

01:47:11.040 --> 01:47:15.440
[Guest]: But Mahamari, which is really pandemic, you know, in today's parlance, was used to describe

01:47:15.440 --> 01:47:18.320
[Guest]: plague in the Garhwal region in North India.

01:47:18.320 --> 01:47:20.360
[Guest]: And this is, you know, like 1850s and so on.

01:47:20.360 --> 01:47:25.800
[Guest]: This is in British reports, but 1896, it comes to Bombay and that's when, you know, all hell

01:47:25.800 --> 01:47:26.800
[Guest]: breaks loose.

01:47:26.800 --> 01:47:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:47:27.800 --> 01:47:31.440
[Amit Varma]: And it's fascinating how the numbers are like you, you've written about how, when it hit

01:47:31.440 --> 01:47:36.420
[Amit Varma]: Canton in 1894, there was an 80% case mortality rate, 80%.

01:47:36.420 --> 01:47:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And interestingly, people in upper stories were surviving because obviously, you know,

01:47:40.680 --> 01:47:45.560
[Amit Varma]: a little further away from rats and those pesky little rat fleas that they carry.

01:47:45.560 --> 01:47:50.920
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Canton lost 40,000 people in a day and, you know, you've quoted this wonderful

01:47:50.920 --> 01:47:51.920
[Amit Varma]: poem.

01:47:51.920 --> 01:47:53.080
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful because I enjoyed reading it.

01:47:53.080 --> 01:47:57.120
[Amit Varma]: It's not a wonderful, wonderful poem per se, but it's very enjoyable called The Plague

01:47:57.120 --> 01:47:58.520
[Amit Varma]: of Bombay by B.F.

01:47:58.520 --> 01:48:01.400
[Amit Varma]: Patel about Mandvi in 1896.

01:48:01.400 --> 01:48:05.280
[Amit Varma]: So I will just read it out for the amusement of my listeners.

01:48:05.280 --> 01:48:10.280
[Amit Varma]: Quote, I stand in Mandvi all around with cries of woe the streets resound.

01:48:10.280 --> 01:48:14.060
[Amit Varma]: This quarter crowded at the best first falls a victim to the best.

01:48:14.060 --> 01:48:19.520
[Amit Varma]: The Jains and Bhatia sat to tell first in alarming numbers fell in every home a death

01:48:19.520 --> 01:48:22.320
[Amit Varma]: or two meets a beveled gazer's view.

01:48:22.320 --> 01:48:27.120
[Amit Varma]: These sects seemed as picked out to bear alone the burden of despair.

01:48:27.120 --> 01:48:31.880
[Amit Varma]: The other races as yet free could not the lurking danger see, half callous to their

01:48:31.880 --> 01:48:33.100
[Amit Varma]: neighbor's woes.

01:48:33.100 --> 01:48:37.520
[Amit Varma]: The plague disturbed not their repose, but soon all undeceived they stand.

01:48:37.520 --> 01:48:41.760
[Amit Varma]: The ravager with scythe in hand scowls every corner of the land.

01:48:41.760 --> 01:48:47.440
[Amit Varma]: Top quote and, you know, apologies to all the Jains and Bhatia who must have, you know,

01:48:47.440 --> 01:48:49.600
[Amit Varma]: reacted with alarm when I read these words out.

01:48:49.600 --> 01:48:50.600
[Amit Varma]: These are not my words.

01:48:50.600 --> 01:48:52.640
[Amit Varma]: This is from The Plague of Bombay by B.F.

01:48:52.640 --> 01:48:53.640
[Amit Varma]: Patel.

01:48:53.640 --> 01:48:57.800
[Amit Varma]: And there's even, you know, a touch of nigh molar about this in the sense that, you know,

01:48:57.800 --> 01:49:01.520
[Amit Varma]: the other races as yet free could not the lurking danger see.

01:49:01.520 --> 01:49:03.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, you've pointed out it early on.

01:49:03.200 --> 01:49:08.920
[Amit Varma]: The numbers are not crazily alarming, like in 1896, you know, 3000 people are recorded

01:49:08.920 --> 01:49:14.680
[Amit Varma]: as dying, then 50,000 the next year, 100,000 the next year, pretty bad, but not yet, kind

01:49:14.680 --> 01:49:16.720
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, hysteria or pandemic levels.

01:49:16.720 --> 01:49:18.880
[Amit Varma]: And most of these are in Bombay presidency.

01:49:18.880 --> 01:49:24.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about, you know, what's going on with the plague in the popular consciousness

01:49:24.360 --> 01:49:26.680
[Amit Varma]: at this point in time?

01:49:26.680 --> 01:49:31.000
[Guest]: Yeah, the first, you know, that's why I have a whole section called crisis in Western India,

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:32.840
[Guest]: 1896 to 98.

01:49:32.840 --> 01:49:36.560
[Guest]: The government of India, British India goes bonkers, you know, and they're doing this

01:49:36.560 --> 01:49:40.800
[Guest]: because they don't want plague to reach Europe, you know, so that's the fear they've been

01:49:40.800 --> 01:49:44.320
[Guest]: battling cholera all these years, they've got a grip on cholera, cholera is no longer

01:49:44.320 --> 01:49:46.040
[Guest]: important in Europe.

01:49:46.040 --> 01:49:51.080
[Guest]: But plague invokes this memory of the Black Death, you know, so, and again, it's the collective

01:49:51.080 --> 01:49:52.080
[Guest]: memory.

01:49:52.080 --> 01:49:55.120
[Guest]: That's what I'm talking about in this book, it's that collective memory, which is driving

01:49:55.120 --> 01:49:59.600
[Guest]: them to say, at no cost shall plague enter Europe.

01:49:59.600 --> 01:50:03.440
[Guest]: And their principal point of interest is Bombay, and of course, Hong Kong.

01:50:03.440 --> 01:50:08.520
[Guest]: And so they, you know, this epidemic act, which we are living under today is the creation

01:50:08.520 --> 01:50:14.400
[Guest]: in February 1898, where this Weissrheim-Elgin basically rolls out, they basically say we

01:50:14.400 --> 01:50:18.440
[Guest]: have to control this, and they impose these most draconian measures, which most public

01:50:18.440 --> 01:50:20.960
[Guest]: health experts would say is, you know, not right.

01:50:20.960 --> 01:50:25.440
[Guest]: Not because, I mean, for the simple reason to combat any epidemic pandemic, you need

01:50:25.440 --> 01:50:26.920
[Guest]: to win the trust of people.

01:50:26.920 --> 01:50:29.600
[Guest]: If you don't win the trust of people, nothing can work.

01:50:29.600 --> 01:50:32.920
[Guest]: And so that's exactly what happened, they went around with search operations.

01:50:32.920 --> 01:50:37.640
[Guest]: And on hindsight, completely wrong science, they thought it was just poverty and filth,

01:50:37.640 --> 01:50:38.640
[Guest]: which led to plague.

01:50:38.640 --> 01:50:43.520
[Guest]: If that was true, you know, Calcutta, people said Calcutta got cholera because of its filth.

01:50:43.520 --> 01:50:45.680
[Guest]: But Calcutta rarely suffered from plague.

01:50:45.680 --> 01:50:49.720
[Guest]: It was really about the rats and fleas and the particular nature of rats and fleas.

01:50:49.720 --> 01:50:52.920
[Guest]: And this got known only after 1905, in a big way.

01:50:52.920 --> 01:50:57.280
[Guest]: So for the first seven years of this pandemic, they were going on throwing disinfectants.

01:50:57.280 --> 01:50:58.280
[Guest]: What will disinfectants do?

01:50:58.280 --> 01:51:02.920
[Guest]: They're not, I mean, this is the idea again, of some sort of airborne transmission, just

01:51:02.920 --> 01:51:05.040
[Guest]: in somewhere there in this medical service.

01:51:05.040 --> 01:51:06.040
[Guest]: So they went around.

01:51:06.040 --> 01:51:09.440
[Guest]: So the cover of the book, for example, shows a flushing, you know, engine used to kind

01:51:09.440 --> 01:51:12.960
[Guest]: of use, it looks a little like a fire and, you know, fire situation.

01:51:12.960 --> 01:51:18.120
[Guest]: When you think of how actually plague gets transmitted through rodents and fleas, it's

01:51:18.120 --> 01:51:20.880
[Guest]: all completely wrong prevention measures.

01:51:20.880 --> 01:51:25.720
[Guest]: And what this meant was massive clampdown on individual liberty, and huge pushback,

01:51:25.720 --> 01:51:27.720
[Guest]: you know, and pushback came in interesting ways.

01:51:27.720 --> 01:51:31.400
[Guest]: People were, people were scared and hurt, caste taboos, for example, like, how can you

01:51:31.400 --> 01:51:32.400
[Guest]: touch me?

01:51:32.400 --> 01:51:35.520
[Guest]: You know, so how can you inspect my wife at the railway station?

01:51:35.520 --> 01:51:38.360
[Guest]: So there were opposition coming from all sorts of, you know, ways.

01:51:38.360 --> 01:51:43.960
[Guest]: How can you let, how can you put me in a hospital next to a person of another caste, for example.

01:51:43.960 --> 01:51:45.240
[Guest]: They had this strict segregation law.

01:51:45.240 --> 01:51:48.880
[Guest]: So if you got plagued, you had to go to the hospital, there was no, and you would be separated

01:51:48.880 --> 01:51:49.880
[Guest]: from your family.

01:51:49.880 --> 01:51:56.400
[Guest]: And this is important because this is the first time the British state really intervenes

01:51:56.400 --> 01:51:59.360
[Guest]: in Indian lives in a major, major way.

01:51:59.360 --> 01:52:00.920
[Guest]: And the pushback is tremendous.

01:52:00.920 --> 01:52:05.360
[Guest]: You know, this is, I would say, like 1857, though we didn't have an uprising, you know,

01:52:05.360 --> 01:52:07.280
[Guest]: we got certain reactions.

01:52:07.280 --> 01:52:11.680
[Guest]: In Pune, there was an assassination, Walter Ryan was assassinated by the Sapika brothers

01:52:11.680 --> 01:52:16.280
[Guest]: because they thought that, you know, this guy's breaching all limits into our society.

01:52:16.280 --> 01:52:20.920
[Guest]: And it's the birth of Tilak as this massive star, you know, Tilak goes to jail, Ganpati

01:52:20.920 --> 01:52:23.120
[Guest]: is banned, you know, Ganpati festival is banned.

01:52:23.120 --> 01:52:27.120
[Guest]: Interestingly, Ganpati, you know, has his rodent on the side, so that's a side story

01:52:27.120 --> 01:52:28.120
[Guest]: of the plague.

01:52:28.120 --> 01:52:31.960
[Guest]: But, you know, when he's released from jail, Tilak is a star.

01:52:31.960 --> 01:52:35.360
[Guest]: So it's literally the plague, you know, which launches him onto the national stage in a

01:52:35.360 --> 01:52:36.360
[Guest]: big way.

01:52:36.360 --> 01:52:41.240
[Guest]: It makes Gokhale a big star later on, Gokhale becomes, you know, the head of Pune municipality.

01:52:41.240 --> 01:52:46.600
[Guest]: So it's also birthplace, you know, plague is a backdrop, especially in Western India,

01:52:46.600 --> 01:52:52.360
[Guest]: because the British government goofs up so spectacularly that the pushback is tremendous.

01:52:52.360 --> 01:52:57.320
[Guest]: And, but the paradox is, a lot of what even I had heard of the plague, you know, before

01:52:57.320 --> 01:53:01.400
[Guest]: starting on this book, was of this period, 1896 to 98.

01:53:01.400 --> 01:53:05.200
[Guest]: And I thought this was when plague really hit, and this was the intensity.

01:53:05.200 --> 01:53:09.200
[Guest]: It turns out that afterwards, actually, the British kind of said, you know, we need to

01:53:09.200 --> 01:53:12.040
[Guest]: change track, we need to be having a different approach.

01:53:12.040 --> 01:53:16.280
[Guest]: But plague really starts hitting India after 1900.

01:53:16.280 --> 01:53:18.920
[Guest]: And that's when the numbers start going through the roof.

01:53:18.920 --> 01:53:24.200
[Guest]: And you know, we're talking of like, in one year, a million deaths just because of plague.

01:53:24.200 --> 01:53:28.760
[Guest]: And it's not Bombay city, it's really places like Dharwad, Belgaum, Satara, you know, a

01:53:28.760 --> 01:53:32.000
[Guest]: lot of these places in Bombay presidency, which get affected.

01:53:32.000 --> 01:53:36.040
[Guest]: And a lot of it was because of, basically, 20 years later, they realized the best way

01:53:36.040 --> 01:53:40.240
[Guest]: to prevent plague was rat proofing, you know, if you could keep the rats out, you wouldn't

01:53:40.240 --> 01:53:41.240
[Guest]: get plague.

01:53:41.240 --> 01:53:45.920
[Guest]: And that is why throughout the pandemic, soldiers in the Indian Army, you know, very few of

01:53:45.920 --> 01:53:46.920
[Guest]: them died due to the plague.

01:53:46.920 --> 01:53:47.920
[Guest]: Why?

01:53:47.920 --> 01:53:48.920
[Guest]: Because of the cantonments.

01:53:48.920 --> 01:53:53.320
[Guest]: Cantonments were nice pukka structures, you couldn't get plague in the cantonments.

01:53:53.320 --> 01:53:57.820
[Guest]: But you could get plague in basically, you know, what we call as kutcha structures.

01:53:57.820 --> 01:54:00.160
[Guest]: And that is where it had its greatest intensity.

01:54:00.160 --> 01:54:04.240
[Guest]: But for plague, you wanted the correct kind of rat and the correct kind of rat flea.

01:54:04.240 --> 01:54:08.960
[Guest]: So the distribution within India was not because in a certain places are more dirty than others.

01:54:08.960 --> 01:54:11.960
[Guest]: It just so happened that some places had a particular kind of rat flea.

01:54:11.960 --> 01:54:16.500
[Guest]: So in South India, rat flea was not this ex-cheapest variety, it was a different variety.

01:54:16.500 --> 01:54:19.760
[Guest]: So it was not an efficient transmitter of plague from rodents to humans.

01:54:19.760 --> 01:54:22.560
[Guest]: So that is why South India kind of escaped plague pretty much.

01:54:22.560 --> 01:54:27.080
[Guest]: But in Punjab, UP and, you know, Bombay presidency, they had the perfect kind of rat and perfect

01:54:27.080 --> 01:54:29.920
[Guest]: kind of rat flea, perfect for plague transmission.

01:54:29.920 --> 01:54:31.640
[Guest]: And that's why it kind of got ravaged.

01:54:31.640 --> 01:54:35.040
[Guest]: And that's why arguments on sanitation again fell flat, because people are pointing out,

01:54:35.040 --> 01:54:39.720
[Guest]: you know, for 100 years, you've been telling us that Calcutta has cholera because Calcutta

01:54:39.720 --> 01:54:40.720
[Guest]: is dirty.

01:54:40.720 --> 01:54:42.920
[Guest]: And yet Calcutta kind of escaped plague.

01:54:42.920 --> 01:54:43.920
[Guest]: So here was a paradox.

01:54:43.920 --> 01:54:48.560
[Guest]: And it's only, you know, such kind of questioning, which led scientists to really find out the

01:54:48.560 --> 01:54:50.480
[Guest]: roots of plague.

01:54:50.480 --> 01:54:51.920
[Amit Varma]: Optimal rat plus optimal rat flea.

01:54:51.920 --> 01:54:55.960
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to come back to rats later, because there is much about rats in the book as well.

01:54:55.960 --> 01:55:00.400
[Amit Varma]: But first, this question that strikes me and it's almost resonant in a way that when I

01:55:00.400 --> 01:55:05.560
[Amit Varma]: think of current times, you know, one of the first things that struck us in March, at least

01:55:05.560 --> 01:55:09.600
[Amit Varma]: in India, is that this is a very alarming situation that is developing.

01:55:09.600 --> 01:55:12.840
[Amit Varma]: And even if we don't have collective memory, at least we can see what's happening in Italy

01:55:12.840 --> 01:55:18.000
[Amit Varma]: and Spain and everything and can take it as seriously as it requires.

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:20.760
[Amit Varma]: But you know, there is limited state capacity.

01:55:20.760 --> 01:55:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, there is no option for a state in a country like ours, but to resort to blunt

01:55:25.520 --> 01:55:31.560
[Amit Varma]: tools, which in our case in India was of course, a blunt tool of the lockdown and with its

01:55:31.560 --> 01:55:33.560
[Amit Varma]: various costs and benefits.

01:55:33.560 --> 01:55:37.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when I was sort of reading about what the British government did at the time

01:55:37.720 --> 01:55:42.840
[Amit Varma]: of the plague, it seems that what you have is a bunch of blunt tools, which also arise

01:55:42.840 --> 01:55:47.440
[Amit Varma]: from a time of epistemic uncertainty in the sense that you don't know what the hell is

01:55:47.440 --> 01:55:48.440
[Amit Varma]: going on, really.

01:55:48.440 --> 01:55:50.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, today, we have a much better idea.

01:55:50.880 --> 01:55:51.880
[Amit Varma]: From the start.

01:55:51.880 --> 01:55:55.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, despite all the uncertainty about masks, and you know, whether it is surface

01:55:55.840 --> 01:56:00.400
[Amit Varma]: borne or whatever, at least we had a much better idea than those guys back then did.

01:56:00.400 --> 01:56:04.360
[Amit Varma]: And I will just like I'll quote from your book about some of the blunt tools that came

01:56:04.360 --> 01:56:09.320
[Amit Varma]: into force at one point, you write, quote, as part of the plague prevention measures,

01:56:09.320 --> 01:56:13.920
[Amit Varma]: thousands of buildings were cleared out citing unsanitary living conditions, property was

01:56:13.920 --> 01:56:18.200
[Amit Varma]: destroyed and burnt, and drains were regularly cleaned, tiles were removed from the roofs

01:56:18.200 --> 01:56:23.320
[Amit Varma]: of houses and dwellings with reported infections were marked with signs outside them and treated

01:56:23.320 --> 01:56:24.560
[Amit Varma]: as if they were on fire.

01:56:24.560 --> 01:56:29.200
[Amit Varma]: They were flushed with water from fire engines and flushing pumps mixed with disinfectant

01:56:29.200 --> 01:56:32.440
[Amit Varma]: such as Cresol or phenyl based potassium permanganate.

01:56:32.440 --> 01:56:35.900
[Amit Varma]: Houses were also lime washed and sulphur was burnt inside.

01:56:35.900 --> 01:56:39.020
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, you talk about how the poor are panicking because they're often being

01:56:39.020 --> 01:56:43.240
[Amit Varma]: left homeless because the dwellings have been targeted, they rise up against the government.

01:56:43.240 --> 01:56:48.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the slogans of that time is Mar Dalo Goreko, which I don't need

01:56:48.360 --> 01:56:49.520
[Amit Varma]: to translate.

01:56:49.520 --> 01:56:54.120
[Amit Varma]: And in Pune, you know, speak about Walter and quote, Walter and went in for the harshest

01:56:54.120 --> 01:56:58.400
[Amit Varma]: containment measures anywhere in the country, with intensive house searches conducted by

01:56:58.400 --> 01:57:02.760
[Amit Varma]: European troops to identify sick people and transfer them to the hospital.

01:57:02.760 --> 01:57:07.920
[Amit Varma]: In the event, accusations of forced examination and misconduct, especially with women, flew

01:57:07.920 --> 01:57:08.920
[Amit Varma]: thick and fast.

01:57:08.920 --> 01:57:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Rand was shot on 22nd June 1897 by brothers from an outrage family with the surname Chhapakar,

01:57:15.040 --> 01:57:16.040
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

01:57:16.040 --> 01:57:21.040
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out, this has repercussions, Tilak becomes a superstar, Gokhale, you know,

01:57:21.040 --> 01:57:26.040
[Amit Varma]: becomes involved there in 1907, which is when, as you point out, a million people die.

01:57:26.040 --> 01:57:31.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, the Congress is sort of split between the moderates led by Gokhale and the extremists

01:57:31.440 --> 01:57:33.360
[Amit Varma]: led by Tilak.

01:57:33.360 --> 01:57:37.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of fascinating, like, again, I'm quoting, you'd go during the peak of the

01:57:37.200 --> 01:57:42.600
[Amit Varma]: plague pandemic in India, more than inoculation or sanitation, it would be quarantine and

01:57:42.600 --> 01:57:45.760
[Amit Varma]: evacuation that would become the norm.

01:57:45.760 --> 01:57:52.680
[Amit Varma]: So in general, when you think of the state's response to events like this, and also then

01:57:52.680 --> 01:57:58.120
[Amit Varma]: the pushback against the people to the state, you know, how sort of are there patterns that

01:57:58.120 --> 01:58:02.240
[Amit Varma]: emerge in terms of, you know, overreach and so on and so forth?

01:58:02.240 --> 01:58:03.240
[Amit Varma]: What are your observations?

01:58:03.240 --> 01:58:09.080
[Guest]: One was, you know, clearly a big issue, while trying to enforce some sort of a lockdown

01:58:09.080 --> 01:58:12.160
[Guest]: then is, of course, what do we do with migrant workers, you know, that's a big issue, of

01:58:12.160 --> 01:58:16.080
[Guest]: course, which happened this year, where I think, you know, we clearly got it wrong,

01:58:16.080 --> 01:58:17.080
[Guest]: in my view.

01:58:17.080 --> 01:58:21.400
[Guest]: And, you know, we had a migration crisis earlier this year.

01:58:21.400 --> 01:58:25.080
[Guest]: Interestingly, the British had a very different view, you know, they took this view that look,

01:58:25.080 --> 01:58:27.320
[Guest]: whatever we do, these guys are going to go back.

01:58:27.320 --> 01:58:29.520
[Guest]: If we have a harsh lockdown, these guys will walk back.

01:58:29.520 --> 01:58:31.680
[Guest]: If we shut down the railways, they will walk back.

01:58:31.680 --> 01:58:35.600
[Guest]: So interestingly, for all their other faults, the British actually allowed these people

01:58:35.600 --> 01:58:37.160
[Guest]: to go home, you know.

01:58:37.160 --> 01:58:39.760
[Guest]: Now, did that lead to a spread of the pandemic?

01:58:39.760 --> 01:58:44.120
[Guest]: There's no evidence of that, because there's no spike in deaths, you know, immediately

01:58:44.120 --> 01:58:45.120
[Guest]: after that.

01:58:45.120 --> 01:58:49.480
[Guest]: But what it enabled was that to Bombay, half of Bombay, 400,000 people actually left Bombay,

01:58:49.480 --> 01:58:53.200
[Guest]: you know, and they came back just like this year, people are coming back now to the cities.

01:58:53.200 --> 01:58:56.680
[Guest]: But that's a classic response in a pandemic that is returned.

01:58:56.680 --> 01:59:01.640
[Guest]: So migrant workers will want to go back, you know, the same voices that we heard this year,

01:59:01.640 --> 01:59:05.200
[Guest]: were heard back then, that is marna hai toh gaon mein marenge, the psychology that, you

01:59:05.200 --> 01:59:09.000
[Guest]: know, if you want to die, we'd rather go back home and die.

01:59:09.000 --> 01:59:14.440
[Guest]: So that's one classic response, clearly, which we saw back then, and what we saw today.

01:59:14.440 --> 01:59:18.960
[Guest]: The other, which is really interesting is that the best strategy was actually evacuation.

01:59:18.960 --> 01:59:20.480
[Guest]: And this was traditional knowledge.

01:59:20.480 --> 01:59:25.440
[Guest]: This was passed down from generation to generation, you know, started off with that quote.

01:59:25.440 --> 01:59:29.760
[Guest]: That is, if you see these rodents coming out, spinning and dying, the best thing to do is

01:59:29.760 --> 01:59:30.760
[Guest]: move out.

01:59:30.760 --> 01:59:34.520
[Guest]: And, you know, this traditional knowledge also had many aspects to it.

01:59:34.520 --> 01:59:39.080
[Guest]: So entire villages would vacate and stay out during the night, there was some implied thing

01:59:39.080 --> 01:59:41.680
[Guest]: that there's something to do with nighttime.

01:59:41.680 --> 01:59:45.280
[Guest]: And later on, science actually showed that it's, you know, a lot of this is transmitted

01:59:45.280 --> 01:59:49.400
[Guest]: at night, that is, is rat fleas actually really work best at night.

01:59:49.400 --> 01:59:52.120
[Guest]: So aspects of traditional knowledge were embedded.

01:59:52.120 --> 01:59:57.080
[Guest]: The British kind of, you know, did not keep to it, and later on started respecting.

01:59:57.080 --> 02:00:00.920
[Guest]: So by the, even, you know, by 1905, 1910, the British showed us the best strategy actually

02:00:00.920 --> 02:00:06.160
[Guest]: is to let villagers camp out of villages, and let the season pass off of plague, and

02:00:06.160 --> 02:00:07.160
[Guest]: then come back.

02:00:07.160 --> 02:00:11.360
[Guest]: That became the most cost effective strategy, right, in the absence of any powerful vaccine

02:00:11.360 --> 02:00:17.200
[Guest]: or inoculation, in the absence of any breakthrough in, you know, in like a antibiotic, which

02:00:17.200 --> 02:00:19.320
[Guest]: was not existent back then.

02:00:19.320 --> 02:00:23.040
[Guest]: The only thing that people could do was what people are doing for centuries, that was evacuation.

02:00:23.040 --> 02:00:27.640
[Guest]: And I estimate easily 30 million people must have evacuated at some point or the other

02:00:27.640 --> 02:00:29.800
[Guest]: in this terrible sort of decade.

02:00:29.800 --> 02:00:32.840
[Guest]: And I've now come across, you know, first person accounts of people who lived on the

02:00:32.840 --> 02:00:36.720
[Guest]: edges of the villages, not just villages, entire towns, you know, observers, there's

02:00:36.720 --> 02:00:40.960
[Guest]: a reference in this book, Bijapur, which is not a small place, you know, it's got tens

02:00:40.960 --> 02:00:44.400
[Guest]: of thousands of people, the entire town would camp outside.

02:00:44.400 --> 02:00:48.920
[Guest]: So it would be a town completely locked with everyone living outside, purely in order to

02:00:48.920 --> 02:00:50.640
[Guest]: escape this thing.

02:00:50.640 --> 02:00:54.760
[Guest]: The way to beat plague was, of course, was to build good buildings, good quality buildings.

02:00:54.760 --> 02:00:56.000
[Guest]: But there was no demand for that.

02:00:56.000 --> 02:00:57.000
[Guest]: And there was no supply for that.

02:00:57.000 --> 02:00:59.400
[Guest]: So that never really, you know, came apart.

02:00:59.400 --> 02:01:03.680
[Guest]: The learning from that is, you know, massive state overreach in the first phase, the British

02:01:03.680 --> 02:01:08.240
[Guest]: learned from that, eventually, the plague manual basically started off pretty much by

02:01:08.240 --> 02:01:13.240
[Guest]: saying respect people, and you know, like, you know, that if you have to take into people

02:01:13.240 --> 02:01:17.280
[Guest]: in confidence, and that has kind of persisted, all public health manuals will tell you that,

02:01:17.280 --> 02:01:19.680
[Guest]: you know, you have to win the trust of people.

02:01:19.680 --> 02:01:24.160
[Guest]: The second thing that the sort of plague did was, of course, reorganize urban governance.

02:01:24.160 --> 02:01:28.840
[Guest]: Now, this had its pros and cons, there were some long needed things like sort of revamping

02:01:28.840 --> 02:01:32.440
[Guest]: the sewerage systems, because that's where a lot of the rats were breeding.

02:01:32.440 --> 02:01:34.040
[Guest]: So all of that were good things.

02:01:34.040 --> 02:01:37.040
[Guest]: But in this process, of course, mass scale displacement, as you pointed out, a lot of

02:01:37.040 --> 02:01:39.440
[Guest]: the poor people, you know, had to come out on the streets.

02:01:39.440 --> 02:01:43.120
[Guest]: And so in those terms, a huge negative repercussions.

02:01:43.120 --> 02:01:46.640
[Guest]: One of the consequences, of course, of plague is today, you know, in every city, there's

02:01:46.640 --> 02:01:48.160
[Guest]: a development authority board.

02:01:48.160 --> 02:01:53.440
[Guest]: Okay, so you have like this MMRDA in Bombay, or DDA, Delhi Development Authority, the roots

02:01:53.440 --> 02:02:00.240
[Guest]: of that line, the plague, you know, it's the first the Bombay Improvement Trust is formed

02:02:00.240 --> 02:02:04.640
[Guest]: as a response to the plague, the Hyderabad Improvement Trust is formed as a response

02:02:04.640 --> 02:02:05.680
[Guest]: to plague.

02:02:05.680 --> 02:02:09.920
[Guest]: And so though our cities, I think, you know, not really, you know, the best examples of

02:02:09.920 --> 02:02:15.840
[Guest]: cities in the world, but whatever basic semblance of urban governance came into account, was

02:02:15.840 --> 02:02:18.160
[Guest]: precisely because the plague prompted, you know, things.

02:02:18.160 --> 02:02:22.960
[Guest]: Shivaji Park, most famously in Bombay, you know, was created as a response to having

02:02:22.960 --> 02:02:27.600
[Guest]: roomy, airy flats, these are theories as to how plague transmit.

02:02:27.600 --> 02:02:32.840
[Guest]: And so a lot of these sub-organization, more broadly, started in a big way in India, thanks

02:02:32.840 --> 02:02:33.840
[Guest]: to the plague.

02:02:33.840 --> 02:02:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's fascinating.

02:02:35.840 --> 02:02:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you referred to the guideline of how the state should treat the people.

02:02:38.880 --> 02:02:43.440
[Amit Varma]: I'll read out this line that struck me from the Punjab Plague Manual in 1909.

02:02:43.440 --> 02:02:47.480
[Amit Varma]: And it says, quote, the cardinal principle of all plague administration must be that

02:02:47.480 --> 02:02:52.400
[Amit Varma]: no pressure or compulsion in any shape or form is to be brought to bear on the people.

02:02:52.400 --> 02:02:55.920
[Amit Varma]: Encouragement, persuasion and the provision of facilities for carrying out the measures

02:02:55.920 --> 02:03:00.560
[Amit Varma]: advocated are the only legitimate means of influencing and guiding public opinion in

02:03:00.560 --> 02:03:01.560
[Amit Varma]: the direction desired.

02:03:01.560 --> 02:03:07.720
[Amit Varma]: Stop, quote, and, you know, another resonant part was about sort of the quarantine circumstances

02:03:07.720 --> 02:03:12.640
[Amit Varma]: like recently, again, just today on Twitter, I came across this sort of disturbing piece

02:03:12.640 --> 02:03:16.840
[Amit Varma]: about Harsh Mandar about he got COVID and got himself admitted to a hospital and things

02:03:16.840 --> 02:03:21.680
[Amit Varma]: were so bad that, you know, he lost his memory for 10 days effectively and kind of lucky

02:03:21.680 --> 02:03:22.680
[Amit Varma]: to get out of there.

02:03:22.680 --> 02:03:26.320
[Amit Varma]: And as he pointed out, despite all the privilege and social capital and all that, so think

02:03:26.320 --> 02:03:28.000
[Amit Varma]: of what's happening to others.

02:03:28.000 --> 02:03:32.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, again, you can read an echo of it in the book, you've quoted from, you

02:03:32.360 --> 02:03:35.880
[Amit Varma]: know, the Shanta Gokhale translation of Lakshmibai Tilak's Mithi Chitre.

02:03:35.880 --> 02:03:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll read that bit out.

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:41.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, this is from more than a century ago, but it need not be.

02:03:41.200 --> 02:03:46.200
[Amit Varma]: Quote, the cottages were ventilated by openings about a span long running along the top and

02:03:46.200 --> 02:03:47.200
[Amit Varma]: bottom of the walls.

02:03:47.200 --> 02:03:48.240
[Amit Varma]: The walls were made of tin.

02:03:48.240 --> 02:03:51.200
[Amit Varma]: They got so cold at night that we felt we would freeze over.

02:03:51.200 --> 02:03:54.980
[Amit Varma]: We were surrounded by the sick, they screamed and beat on the tin walls.

02:03:54.980 --> 02:03:58.920
[Amit Varma]: At times a patient would climb onto a wall and jump with a loud thud into the neighbouring

02:03:58.920 --> 02:03:59.920
[Amit Varma]: room.

02:03:59.920 --> 02:04:01.680
[Amit Varma]: The floors of the cottage had not been levelled.

02:04:01.680 --> 02:04:04.320
[Amit Varma]: When you walked, pebbles bit into the soles of your feet.

02:04:04.320 --> 02:04:07.040
[Amit Varma]: There was no food in our stomachs and no sleep in our eyes.

02:04:07.040 --> 02:04:09.760
[Amit Varma]: Tara's, her daughter, Tara's screams were heart rending.

02:04:09.760 --> 02:04:12.680
[Amit Varma]: I thought if Yama had a kingdom anywhere, it had to be here.

02:04:12.680 --> 02:04:13.740
[Amit Varma]: The place was terrifying.

02:04:13.740 --> 02:04:14.740
[Amit Varma]: The night was terrifying.

02:04:14.740 --> 02:04:18.520
[Amit Varma]: The surroundings were terrifying and the state of my heart was terrifying.

02:04:18.520 --> 02:04:19.520
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

02:04:19.520 --> 02:04:22.600
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, again, I thought I should read this out for the benefit of the listeners

02:04:22.600 --> 02:04:27.520
[Amit Varma]: and I'm just going to go right out and sort of buy, you know, Smriti Chitre.

02:04:27.520 --> 02:04:31.560
[Amit Varma]: And to go back to what we said earlier about people forming crazy narratives over all these,

02:04:31.560 --> 02:04:35.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, you've mentioned a bunch of rumours that came about, such as, you know, the British

02:04:35.120 --> 02:04:39.480
[Amit Varma]: are collecting Indian bodies to extract momai, a fluid to save themselves.

02:04:39.480 --> 02:04:40.480
[Amit Varma]: This was one rumour.

02:04:40.480 --> 02:04:46.200
[Amit Varma]: Another rumour was about how, you know, for vaccination, the needle was a yard long.

02:04:46.200 --> 02:04:48.280
[Amit Varma]: You died immediately after the operation.

02:04:48.280 --> 02:04:51.040
[Amit Varma]: You survived the operation just six months and then collapsed.

02:04:51.040 --> 02:04:53.800
[Amit Varma]: Men lost their virility and women became sterile.

02:04:53.800 --> 02:04:57.680
[Amit Varma]: The deputy commissioner himself underwent the operation and expired half an hour afterwards

02:04:57.680 --> 02:04:59.800
[Amit Varma]: in great agony.

02:04:59.800 --> 02:05:00.800
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

02:05:00.800 --> 02:05:01.800
[Amit Varma]: Unrelated question.

02:05:01.800 --> 02:05:06.960
[Amit Varma]: Why does this shit spread like I had Pratik Sinha of Alt News on my show, you know, more

02:05:06.960 --> 02:05:08.720
[Amit Varma]: than a year ago.

02:05:08.720 --> 02:05:12.660
[Amit Varma]: And you know, we were discussing those crazy rumours on WhatsApp where people are talking

02:05:12.660 --> 02:05:16.400
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, children being kidnapped by strangers.

02:05:16.400 --> 02:05:20.740
[Amit Varma]: And those rumours were constantly being modified with, you know, whichever area they were meant

02:05:20.740 --> 02:05:22.560
[Amit Varma]: to reach out to that area being put in.

02:05:22.560 --> 02:05:26.240
[Amit Varma]: And as a consequence, people were believing that rubbish and they were actually lynching

02:05:26.240 --> 02:05:29.800
[Amit Varma]: strangers who happened to pass through their village.

02:05:29.800 --> 02:05:35.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, I understand that, you know, we are a species which explains a very complex world

02:05:35.400 --> 02:05:37.240
[Amit Varma]: through simple stories.

02:05:37.240 --> 02:05:38.720
[Amit Varma]: But why these kind of stories?

02:05:38.720 --> 02:05:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Why this sort of morbid fascination that exists?

02:05:42.040 --> 02:05:46.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know that this is not related either to the book or to economics or history or

02:05:46.400 --> 02:05:47.400
[Amit Varma]: whatever.

02:05:47.400 --> 02:05:48.400
[Amit Varma]: But what are your thoughts on this?

02:05:48.400 --> 02:05:50.200
[Guest]: I think there's something about death itself, right?

02:05:50.200 --> 02:05:54.320
[Guest]: I mean, death being the most natural, but also something which everyone is obsessed

02:05:54.320 --> 02:05:59.880
[Guest]: about that really sparks off all sorts of conspiracy theories.

02:05:59.880 --> 02:06:03.440
[Unknown]: I would say not just epidemics, you know, even the suicide like we saw earlier this

02:06:03.440 --> 02:06:08.480
[Guest]: year or there's something about death, which makes it very easily pliable to gossip.

02:06:08.480 --> 02:06:10.360
[Guest]: I think that's that's really the root.

02:06:10.360 --> 02:06:16.520
[Guest]: Now you combine that with a general atmosphere of fear and panic like in a pandemic.

02:06:16.520 --> 02:06:22.440
[Guest]: And what you get is quite a lethal sort of mix of fake information, which either this

02:06:22.440 --> 02:06:25.800
[Guest]: year or especially, you know, during the plague transmitted like wildfire.

02:06:25.800 --> 02:06:30.120
[Guest]: I think also what matters is the credibility of the state, you know, and because British

02:06:30.120 --> 02:06:36.080
[Guest]: India came down so harshly that they kind of did not gain the trust of the people for

02:06:36.080 --> 02:06:37.160
[Guest]: a very long time.

02:06:37.160 --> 02:06:41.600
[Guest]: And so even on vaccination, you know, later on, there's a quote in this book, it says

02:06:41.600 --> 02:06:48.200
[Guest]: the same vaccine where people were almost causing a riot because the vaccine was introduced.

02:06:48.200 --> 02:06:52.360
[Guest]: Later on, there was literally a riot for the vaccine, that is, people saw the benefits

02:06:52.360 --> 02:06:54.960
[Guest]: of the vaccine and then wanted that vaccine.

02:06:54.960 --> 02:06:59.000
[Guest]: So the whole mindset shifted in the span of about 25 years.

02:06:59.000 --> 02:07:03.720
[Guest]: But getting this idea of inoculation and vaccination took so much time.

02:07:03.720 --> 02:07:08.160
[Guest]: And often these doctors and so on had to literally inject themselves, like what Joe Biden just

02:07:08.160 --> 02:07:12.840
[Guest]: did, you know, sort of take that first shot and say that, you know, this is this is fine.

02:07:12.840 --> 02:07:17.720
[Guest]: So I mean, I'm not an expert on psychology, but I would imagine that under, you know,

02:07:17.720 --> 02:07:23.400
[Guest]: heightened situations of stress, it's definitely something to be said about the exponential

02:07:23.400 --> 02:07:27.000
[Guest]: rise in, you know, rumors and spread.

02:07:27.000 --> 02:07:30.340
[Guest]: And so that's why you need a credible state and a government which will give you good

02:07:30.340 --> 02:07:32.200
[Guest]: information from time to time.

02:07:32.200 --> 02:07:35.320
[Amit Varma]: The interesting thing about these kind of stories is that they don't just happen during

02:07:35.320 --> 02:07:40.320
[Amit Varma]: heightened stress or, you know, we are just surrounded by so much crazy conspiracy theory

02:07:40.320 --> 02:07:43.480
[Amit Varma]: all around that it's a little bizarre.

02:07:43.480 --> 02:07:48.400
[Amit Varma]: But there is also in the middle of all this superstition and blind faith, there is also

02:07:48.400 --> 02:07:50.000
[Amit Varma]: some great science happening.

02:07:50.000 --> 02:07:56.200
[Amit Varma]: I was especially struck by the science around rats and cats, which simultaneously evolved

02:07:56.200 --> 02:08:00.240
[Amit Varma]: during this period, like you've spoken about how there was this municipal commissioner

02:08:00.240 --> 02:08:05.840
[Amit Varma]: of Bombay PCS know, who charted in your words, quote, charted the migration path of rats

02:08:05.840 --> 02:08:09.800
[Amit Varma]: within the city from the east to the west and then to the north, and emphasized that

02:08:09.800 --> 02:08:14.760
[Amit Varma]: rat migration and mortality impeded local efforts to contain the plague among humans

02:08:14.760 --> 02:08:16.280
[Amit Varma]: in newer regions.

02:08:16.280 --> 02:08:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

02:08:17.360 --> 02:08:21.640
[Amit Varma]: So my question is, how is he charting the migration of rats?

02:08:21.640 --> 02:08:24.760
[Guest]: Yeah, they're literally taking samples, you know, they're taking samples.

02:08:24.760 --> 02:08:29.880
[Guest]: I mean, this is a really amazing story, this 25 year period where people are really studying

02:08:29.880 --> 02:08:35.320
[Guest]: rats at, you know, multiple levels and also cats, you know, as I pointed out at one place.

02:08:35.320 --> 02:08:39.480
[Guest]: And what Snow is doing is, you know, they're taking samples of rats found dead.

02:08:39.480 --> 02:08:41.200
[Guest]: And they're kind of literally tracking.

02:08:41.200 --> 02:08:45.000
[Guest]: So they have these monitors of rats to see how many dead rats are we getting from different

02:08:45.000 --> 02:08:46.640
[Guest]: locations.

02:08:46.640 --> 02:08:51.840
[Guest]: And so they draw these charts and rat, I mean, putting the number of rats found dead, or

02:08:51.840 --> 02:08:57.100
[Guest]: even caught alive, you know, this becomes a statistic for almost 25 years, a hotly looked

02:08:57.100 --> 02:09:01.440
[Guest]: up statistic during the plague years, believe it or not, is, you know, how many rats died

02:09:01.440 --> 02:09:02.440
[Guest]: in your locality.

02:09:02.440 --> 02:09:06.440
[Guest]: And this whole phenomenon of rat catchers, you know, becomes a big deal.

02:09:06.440 --> 02:09:10.000
[Guest]: So yeah, in this particular case, you know, before the migration of humans, it actually

02:09:10.000 --> 02:09:13.920
[Guest]: starts by looking at the migration of rats, and how they are, they're going.

02:09:13.920 --> 02:09:18.160
[Guest]: And again, the science is not clear, it's, even today, we don't know exactly how rodents,

02:09:18.160 --> 02:09:22.600
[Guest]: because, you know, they can go very long distances, even just by foot.

02:09:22.600 --> 02:09:25.920
[Guest]: The rat fleas can't go, you know, so they're two vectors, right?

02:09:25.920 --> 02:09:29.840
[Guest]: So there's a rat and there's a rat flea, the rat flea has to be embedded in the rat.

02:09:29.840 --> 02:09:34.960
[Guest]: But the rat flea can't go very far, unless it's nested in, say, shirts or cotton, which

02:09:34.960 --> 02:09:39.160
[Guest]: is a classic, you know, transmitter, or the rats themselves.

02:09:39.160 --> 02:09:43.960
[Guest]: But the rats themselves can sit in the storage, and they can go by train wagons and reach,

02:09:43.960 --> 02:09:48.600
[Guest]: you know, Punjab, for example, and then, you know, infect other other rats and so on.

02:09:48.600 --> 02:09:53.760
[Guest]: But one thing we should talk about is also that more rats died than humans.

02:09:53.760 --> 02:09:57.400
[Guest]: You know, this is the thing about plague, that people, you know, blame the rats, yes,

02:09:57.400 --> 02:09:58.400
[Guest]: we blame them.

02:09:58.400 --> 02:10:02.560
[Guest]: But actually, it's the rats at the receiving end, you know, and it's only when rats die,

02:10:02.560 --> 02:10:05.920
[Guest]: that actually what happens is the flea gets hungry and then bites humans.

02:10:05.920 --> 02:10:08.440
[Guest]: That's the science behind plague transmission.

02:10:08.440 --> 02:10:15.400
[Guest]: So the unfortunate saga of, in fact, rat migration is a sign of rat death, they're kind of helping

02:10:15.400 --> 02:10:19.240
[Guest]: us by pointing out that, look, stay away, there's something wrong happening.

02:10:19.240 --> 02:10:22.400
[Guest]: If rats are there, this is again, just a joke, but you know, if rats are there, it means

02:10:22.400 --> 02:10:25.800
[Guest]: that there's no plague, if rats are surviving for a long period, that means there's no plague

02:10:25.800 --> 02:10:29.760
[Guest]: and you know, you're relatively safe, but it's amazing the kind of stuff people did

02:10:29.760 --> 02:10:30.760
[Guest]: with rats.

02:10:30.760 --> 02:10:35.840
[Guest]: Eventually, the science came to be that once it was confirmed that rats were the source,

02:10:35.840 --> 02:10:39.400
[Guest]: rat fleas were the source, rat catching became an occupation.

02:10:39.400 --> 02:10:42.920
[Guest]: And even today, the Bombay municipality, I think it gives you 18 rupees for a rat or

02:10:42.920 --> 02:10:43.920
[Guest]: something like that.

02:10:43.920 --> 02:10:44.920
[Guest]: That's the going rate today.

02:10:44.920 --> 02:10:50.440
[Guest]: But this whole occupation of rat catchers took on big time and you know, they were given

02:10:50.440 --> 02:10:55.400
[Guest]: these incentives to catch rats, they were objections, for example, a gen said, you know,

02:10:55.400 --> 02:10:58.800
[Guest]: this is against our religion, so you should not touch animals and so on.

02:10:58.800 --> 02:11:03.040
[Guest]: So they would project upset, but the mechanism is very simple, they would keep these instruments,

02:11:03.040 --> 02:11:07.800
[Guest]: these objects to catch rats, and they would lay these sort of poison sort of bread in

02:11:07.800 --> 02:11:09.320
[Guest]: these cages.

02:11:09.320 --> 02:11:10.880
[Guest]: And then the next day, they would have to report.

02:11:10.880 --> 02:11:14.920
[Guest]: Now, once the rats come to the laboratory, imagine these scientists at you know, these

02:11:14.920 --> 02:11:19.480
[Guest]: plague research laboratory, they're basically studying if these rats have plague or not,

02:11:19.480 --> 02:11:22.320
[Guest]: because by then they discovered the germs that you know, lead to plague.

02:11:22.320 --> 02:11:25.960
[Guest]: So all literally, I think there's something thousands of rats landing up at this laboratory

02:11:25.960 --> 02:11:26.960
[Unknown]: every day.

02:11:26.960 --> 02:11:30.320
[Guest]: Just imagine this economy, you know, of firstly paying people to catch rats, then somebody

02:11:30.320 --> 02:11:34.280
[Guest]: analyzing the rats, then they built like a rat scorecard, they have a chart, you know,

02:11:34.280 --> 02:11:36.680
[Guest]: how many rats are dying and so on.

02:11:36.680 --> 02:11:40.520
[Guest]: And then you know, then they say that the and because plague was cyclical, you know,

02:11:40.520 --> 02:11:41.600
[Guest]: why was it cyclical?

02:11:41.600 --> 02:11:46.340
[Guest]: Because the rat flea could survive only in certain seasons of the year and it transmitted.

02:11:46.340 --> 02:11:51.720
[Guest]: So in different parts of India, the cycle varied, but you could say that it became seasonal,

02:11:51.720 --> 02:11:54.960
[Guest]: which meant that people could observe just like how we know the monsoon is coming and

02:11:54.960 --> 02:11:55.960
[Guest]: going.

02:11:55.960 --> 02:11:59.560
[Guest]: You could see over time when the plague is coming and then going, you know, which was

02:11:59.560 --> 02:12:01.720
[Guest]: not known in 1897, 1898.

02:12:01.720 --> 02:12:07.880
[Guest]: But by 1905, 1906, it became so seasonal, that this rat scorecard is very important

02:12:07.880 --> 02:12:10.920
[Guest]: because the rat scorecard, you know, as it started tapering out, you knew that plague

02:12:10.920 --> 02:12:12.520
[Guest]: is ebbing out.

02:12:12.520 --> 02:12:15.800
[Guest]: So just like we look at this COVID chart numbers, and you know, now it's on the downward track

02:12:15.800 --> 02:12:20.000
[Guest]: in India, the track, the number that they were seeing even more than human beings was

02:12:20.000 --> 02:12:21.000
[Guest]: actually rats.

02:12:21.000 --> 02:12:24.400
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's completely crazy, because you've written a lot about this.

02:12:24.400 --> 02:12:26.040
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I won't quote all of it.

02:12:26.040 --> 02:12:31.240
[Amit Varma]: But one of the things I was struck by is how it was estimated, quote, that there were as

02:12:31.240 --> 02:12:34.920
[Amit Varma]: many rats as humans in England and Wales, that is about 40 million.

02:12:34.920 --> 02:12:40.560
[Amit Varma]: And using a similar ratio, 1 million rats were estimated to live in the city of Bombay,

02:12:40.560 --> 02:12:42.200
[Amit Varma]: stop quote, which is just nuts.

02:12:42.200 --> 02:12:46.040
[Amit Varma]: And what happens after this is, and by the way, what he was saying earlier about an incentive

02:12:46.040 --> 02:12:50.880
[Amit Varma]: to catch rats, it strikes me was also an incentive to breed rats.

02:12:50.880 --> 02:12:54.160
[Amit Varma]: But you know, was there ever a scam like that, where people were breeding rats?

02:12:54.160 --> 02:12:55.160
[Guest]: There was.

02:12:55.160 --> 02:12:57.920
[Guest]: There's a scam in Vietnam, for sure.

02:12:57.920 --> 02:12:59.400
[Guest]: So we don't have evidence in India.

02:12:59.400 --> 02:13:03.560
[Guest]: But I'm quite sure that you know, this economy, this is a classic perverse incentive kind

02:13:03.560 --> 02:13:04.760
[Guest]: of problem.

02:13:04.760 --> 02:13:05.760
[Guest]: But it did lead.

02:13:05.760 --> 02:13:10.400
[Guest]: So there's a historian who's documented this in Vietnam, it's called the Hanoi rat catchers.

02:13:10.400 --> 02:13:13.680
[Guest]: And you know, there's a whole economy which started on breeding rats so that you can,

02:13:13.680 --> 02:13:14.680
[Guest]: you know, catch them.

02:13:14.680 --> 02:13:15.680
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

02:13:15.680 --> 02:13:16.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:13:16.680 --> 02:13:17.680
[Amit Varma]: The seen and the unseen.

02:13:17.680 --> 02:13:21.440
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, and also the directions in which it goes like one of the ways to get rid of rats

02:13:21.440 --> 02:13:22.820
[Amit Varma]: is to have cats.

02:13:22.820 --> 02:13:26.200
[Amit Varma]: So there is a dude called Andrew Buchanan, you write about who actually carries out a

02:13:26.200 --> 02:13:27.760
[Amit Varma]: cat census.

02:13:27.760 --> 02:13:32.540
[Amit Varma]: And then you write quote, in 1910, he staged demonstrations in a room with glass doors

02:13:32.540 --> 02:13:36.160
[Amit Varma]: of how cats killed rats to create visual awareness.

02:13:36.160 --> 02:13:41.520
[Amit Varma]: His enthusiasm was supported by luminaries such as Robert Koch and Eskita Sato.

02:13:41.520 --> 02:13:46.040
[Amit Varma]: However, he found few takers for his proposals in India, and stringent opposition from a

02:13:46.040 --> 02:13:51.000
[Amit Varma]: few scientists abroad who argued that cats themselves could harbor the plague.

02:13:51.000 --> 02:13:54.840
[Amit Varma]: Some even argued that non venomous snakes were a better option since they did not attract

02:13:54.840 --> 02:13:59.020
[Amit Varma]: rat fleas, stop quote, and I can imagine a home keeping, you know, non venomous snakes

02:13:59.020 --> 02:14:01.040
[Amit Varma]: instead of cats for the rats.

02:14:01.040 --> 02:14:05.800
[Amit Varma]: And then I found I love this para as well, quote, in the middle of this fascinating

02:14:05.800 --> 02:14:10.240
[Amit Varma]: mammalian and reptilian debate, cats were introduced in plague prevention policies in

02:14:10.240 --> 02:14:15.320
[Amit Varma]: British ruled Hong Kong, and in German ruled Togoland and Japan, a small business of cat

02:14:15.320 --> 02:14:17.800
[Amit Varma]: rearing and trade also developed on the side.

02:14:17.800 --> 02:14:24.200
[Amit Varma]: In 1909, Japan imported 4000 cats from the USA, and still noted a shortfall of 10,000

02:14:24.200 --> 02:14:25.200
[Amit Varma]: felines.

02:14:25.200 --> 02:14:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Cat breeds were compared on their efficiency in killing rats.

02:14:28.400 --> 02:14:33.680
[Amit Varma]: In Japan, Kita Sato praised the rats sent to him by Buchanan as exquisite rat catchers

02:14:33.680 --> 02:14:39.840
[Amit Varma]: and of a better race than the ones found there, stop quote, which is all of it is sort of

02:14:39.840 --> 02:14:40.840
[Amit Varma]: completely nuts.

02:14:40.840 --> 02:14:47.120
[Amit Varma]: And now, you know, before we move on to influenza, you speak about how the main legacy of the

02:14:47.120 --> 02:14:54.160
[Amit Varma]: plague as such can be traced alongside, you know, four kind of different arcs, law, politics,

02:14:54.160 --> 02:14:56.000
[Amit Varma]: labor and urban governance.

02:14:56.000 --> 02:15:01.520
[Amit Varma]: So you know, can you elaborate on these for me, because it seems to a certain extent,

02:15:01.520 --> 02:15:06.560
[Amit Varma]: the consequences of all of these, you know, good or bad are with us today.

02:15:06.560 --> 02:15:07.560
[Guest]: Yeah, definitely.

02:15:07.560 --> 02:15:12.600
[Guest]: I think if you ask me between cholera, plague and influenza, which has the greatest impact,

02:15:12.600 --> 02:15:16.960
[Guest]: which still lives with us today, it's plague for so the legal aspect is the law, which

02:15:16.960 --> 02:15:20.360
[Guest]: is called you know, this epidemics, Diseases Act of 1897.

02:15:20.360 --> 02:15:23.120
[Guest]: I mean, COVID prevention today is under that act, right?

02:15:23.120 --> 02:15:29.080
[Guest]: So that's the that's the real big legal kind of I mean, the legacy in terms of law comes

02:15:29.080 --> 02:15:30.080
[Guest]: from that.

02:15:30.080 --> 02:15:33.360
[Guest]: And interestingly, as I write about inheritance law, and so on, because so many people died

02:15:33.360 --> 02:15:36.880
[Guest]: so quickly, that people had to start writing bills and so on.

02:15:36.880 --> 02:15:39.880
[Guest]: And it gave a little fillip to that industry as well.

02:15:39.880 --> 02:15:45.000
[Guest]: So that's the law part that is the architecture of countering pandemics in India, the legal

02:15:45.000 --> 02:15:50.760
[Guest]: architecture was born out of this third global plague pandemic called plague pandemic of

02:15:50.760 --> 02:15:51.760
[Guest]: India.

02:15:51.760 --> 02:15:53.000
[Guest]: So we start from 1896.

02:15:53.000 --> 02:15:56.280
[Guest]: The other part is, you know, about political movements.

02:15:56.280 --> 02:15:58.400
[Guest]: So one part is Tilak Gokhale, right?

02:15:58.400 --> 02:16:00.960
[Guest]: So that's a huge part of Western Indian politics.

02:16:00.960 --> 02:16:05.440
[Guest]: But then it's also about the cooperative movement, you know, the history of the cooperative movement.

02:16:05.440 --> 02:16:06.960
[Guest]: So we talk about Amul today, and so on.

02:16:06.960 --> 02:16:10.040
[Guest]: So there's some successful cooperatives, a lot of them have failed.

02:16:10.040 --> 02:16:15.120
[Guest]: But interestingly, a lot of that organizational bandwidth, to run a successful cooperative,

02:16:15.120 --> 02:16:18.380
[Guest]: you need to be able to get a lot of people for your cause.

02:16:18.380 --> 02:16:20.800
[Guest]: So you need organizational skills, leadership skills.

02:16:20.800 --> 02:16:25.600
[Guest]: And that came about often, in people handling these plague evacuation camps.

02:16:25.600 --> 02:16:30.080
[Guest]: So imagine if you have to evacuate an entire village or an entire town again, and again,

02:16:30.080 --> 02:16:34.640
[Guest]: certain kind of cater of people who kind of emerged in this system, who basically, you

02:16:34.640 --> 02:16:38.920
[Guest]: know, were then the leaders of the first cooperatives of India, which were emerging in 1905, and

02:16:38.920 --> 02:16:39.920
[Guest]: so on.

02:16:39.920 --> 02:16:44.700
[Guest]: So the Servants of India Society of Gokhale is a classic example of that, which were into

02:16:44.700 --> 02:16:48.520
[Guest]: plague relief, and then became a big social work kind of society.

02:16:48.520 --> 02:16:52.920
[Guest]: And then, you know, we mentioned the year of the plague, which was really 1907, one

02:16:52.920 --> 02:16:59.360
[Guest]: million deaths, the worst year in Indian history from plague was the year of the Congress split.

02:16:59.360 --> 02:17:03.780
[Guest]: And so that was, it's not the defining reason, you know, I'm not arguing that these epidemics

02:17:03.780 --> 02:17:08.280
[Guest]: were the main reason, but an important factor, you know, the fact that how was the government

02:17:08.280 --> 02:17:14.000
[Guest]: responding to this was a big deciding point between different factions of the International

02:17:14.000 --> 02:17:15.000
[Guest]: Congress.

02:17:15.000 --> 02:17:16.000
[Guest]: Right.

02:17:16.000 --> 02:17:19.000
[Guest]: And then in Ahmedabad where I'm based, you know, Vallabhbhai Patel, Vallabhbhai Patel,

02:17:19.000 --> 02:17:25.000
[Guest]: you know, the Sardar Patel's starting point in politics was really being this head of

02:17:25.000 --> 02:17:28.120
[Guest]: the sanitation department of the Ahmedabad municipality.

02:17:28.120 --> 02:17:32.000
[Guest]: And his first big job was in 1917, plague outbreak in Ahmedabad, Ahmedabad survived

02:17:32.000 --> 02:17:37.440
[Guest]: plague until then, not no major outbreak, 1917, bad year for Ahmedabad, a lot of people

02:17:37.440 --> 02:17:41.840
[Guest]: left Ahmedabad and Patel kind of went on the ground, tried to understand the situation.

02:17:41.840 --> 02:17:45.680
[Guest]: So Patel's political career also, you know, kind of starts off with this, there's an economic

02:17:45.680 --> 02:17:50.200
[Guest]: impact, you know, can't ignore the fact that economic activity is constrained, like, you

02:17:50.200 --> 02:17:51.840
[Guest]: know, this year is a recession year.

02:17:51.840 --> 02:17:57.760
[Guest]: Now think of a pandemic striking India from year to year, it's a kind of lesser known

02:17:57.760 --> 02:18:02.960
[Guest]: part of economic history of India, that pandemics curtail India's growth story, you know, in

02:18:02.960 --> 02:18:06.200
[Guest]: the 1980s, 90s, 1910s in a huge way.

02:18:06.200 --> 02:18:10.840
[Guest]: And so I give examples, there are clear examples of GDP falling in some years by 5% and so

02:18:10.840 --> 02:18:11.840
[Guest]: on.

02:18:11.840 --> 02:18:16.880
[Guest]: And so that kind of aggravates some of these other impacts, and business houses everywhere

02:18:16.880 --> 02:18:21.480
[Guest]: are complaining, you know, they're saying we can't do business in epidemic times like

02:18:21.480 --> 02:18:22.480
[Guest]: these.

02:18:22.480 --> 02:18:26.280
[Guest]: Workers get some bargaining power, you know, this is the classic thing of epidemics, when

02:18:26.280 --> 02:18:30.720
[Guest]: enough people die, the guys surviving can get good wages.

02:18:30.720 --> 02:18:35.060
[Guest]: And so there's a labor shortage in many sectors, which drives up wages.

02:18:35.060 --> 02:18:36.060
[Guest]: So that's one thing.

02:18:36.060 --> 02:18:40.000
[Guest]: And then urban governance, which I've already alluded to, which is these improvement trusts.

02:18:40.000 --> 02:18:45.960
[Guest]: So the roots of urban planning, urban, let's say urban development, really, you know, take

02:18:45.960 --> 02:18:46.960
[Guest]: us back to the plague.

02:18:46.960 --> 02:18:50.560
[Guest]: And so the Bombay Improvement Trust is really the first one.

02:18:50.560 --> 02:18:56.320
[Guest]: That started in 1898, Mysore in 1903, Calcutta in 1911, Hyderabad, it happens literally a

02:18:56.320 --> 02:18:59.640
[Guest]: few months after Hyderabad is knocked out.

02:18:59.640 --> 02:19:04.440
[Guest]: And you know, literally, you cannot talk about the urban history of India.

02:19:04.440 --> 02:19:09.280
[Guest]: Because so many cities of India, plague was a huge part of their history for at least

02:19:09.280 --> 02:19:10.280
[Guest]: 20 years.

02:19:10.280 --> 02:19:15.320
[Guest]: You know, in Hyderabad, you know, between 1911 and 1920s or so was continuously ravaged

02:19:15.320 --> 02:19:16.320
[Guest]: by plague.

02:19:16.320 --> 02:19:18.440
[Guest]: You know, Hyderabad's population collapsed completely.

02:19:18.440 --> 02:19:23.040
[Guest]: We talk of the Moosi floods, you know, in Hyderabad, which for Hyderabadis, people know

02:19:23.040 --> 02:19:27.480
[Guest]: about the Moosi floods, but actually the plague killed many more people than the Moosi floods.

02:19:27.480 --> 02:19:30.240
[Guest]: But nobody remembers the plague as we do the Moosi floods.

02:19:30.240 --> 02:19:35.760
[Guest]: And that's again, coming back to this point, that floods, earthquakes, big calamities,

02:19:35.760 --> 02:19:40.840
[Guest]: are better remembered than epidemics, because epidemics are not destroying, you know, capital

02:19:40.840 --> 02:19:41.840
[Guest]: stock and so on.

02:19:41.840 --> 02:19:45.160
[Guest]: So this is how I see the legacy of the plague on politics.

02:19:45.160 --> 02:19:49.040
[Guest]: So you know, it's interesting, if you see the full arc of Indian freedom movement, the

02:19:49.040 --> 02:19:56.720
[Guest]: way I'm looking at it now is cholera and 1857 uprising, plague and the rise of the Congress,

02:19:56.720 --> 02:19:58.440
[Guest]: and influenza and the rise of Gandhi.

02:19:58.440 --> 02:20:04.280
[Guest]: And so three major sort of markers in our freedom movement can be pinned against the

02:20:04.280 --> 02:20:07.840
[Guest]: backdrop of, you know, a major pandemic.

02:20:07.840 --> 02:20:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And Mahatma Gandhi also kind of plays a side role even in plague hitting South Africa,

02:20:12.000 --> 02:20:15.600
[Amit Varma]: because as you point out, when he's in South Africa, you know, that sort of slogan of his

02:20:15.600 --> 02:20:19.400
[Amit Varma]: cleanliness is next only to godliness, perhaps has something to do with that.

02:20:19.400 --> 02:20:24.720
[Amit Varma]: And you also talk about how because South Africans, white South Africans would blame

02:20:24.720 --> 02:20:30.160
[Amit Varma]: outsiders for this, in a sense, it was also a contributing factor to apartheid.

02:20:30.160 --> 02:20:31.160
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:20:31.160 --> 02:20:34.600
[Guest]: I mean, that's definitely the case, you know, we've talked so far about plague in India.

02:20:34.600 --> 02:20:37.920
[Guest]: But plague, when we said the pandemic, it really reached many parts of the world.

02:20:37.920 --> 02:20:38.920
[Guest]: It didn't kill many people.

02:20:38.920 --> 02:20:44.360
[Guest]: You know, the estimates I've put until 1920, 13 million deaths, 12 million in India.

02:20:44.360 --> 02:20:47.560
[Guest]: But there were 1 million deaths outside India, a lot of it in China.

02:20:47.560 --> 02:20:49.400
[Guest]: But South Africa got hit.

02:20:49.400 --> 02:20:53.120
[Guest]: Brazil got a little bit of plague, not too many deaths, but a huge scare.

02:20:53.120 --> 02:20:55.960
[Guest]: Some parts of Europe, Indonesia got a lot of plague.

02:20:55.960 --> 02:20:59.600
[Guest]: And in South Africa, there's no doubt that, you know, it contributed, it's not the main

02:20:59.600 --> 02:21:04.960
[Guest]: factor, but it contributed towards these very strict segregation policies that started.

02:21:04.960 --> 02:21:08.640
[Guest]: Because like with cholera, plague was associated with filth and dirt.

02:21:08.640 --> 02:21:11.040
[Guest]: So how do we keep plague away from us?

02:21:11.040 --> 02:21:14.000
[Guest]: Don't let these people who carry plague come near us.

02:21:14.000 --> 02:21:19.160
[Guest]: And so segregation policies were, you know, very strongly put into place in South Africa.

02:21:19.160 --> 02:21:22.800
[Guest]: So you know, so as a historian has noted on plague, Myron Eschenberg, who's written a

02:21:22.800 --> 02:21:26.400
[Guest]: book on plague, he says it contributed to the rise of nationalism in India, the great

02:21:26.400 --> 02:21:31.040
[Guest]: fire in Honolulu, which is, you know, in Hawaii, the persistence of anti-Asian prejudice in

02:21:31.040 --> 02:21:32.120
[Guest]: the U.S.

02:21:32.120 --> 02:21:37.880
[Guest]: So one of the, though it didn't hit the U.S., their immigration laws became extremely racist

02:21:37.880 --> 02:21:42.440
[Guest]: after 1905, precisely because they associated with immigration the disease.

02:21:42.440 --> 02:21:47.920
[Guest]: And so that's how this anti-China, anti-Indian sentiments rose, the rise of apartheid in

02:21:47.920 --> 02:21:50.920
[Guest]: South Africa, and the growth of public health service in Brazil.

02:21:50.920 --> 02:21:54.760
[Guest]: Interestingly, Brazil, one of the leading scientists in the world, you know, was appointed

02:21:54.760 --> 02:21:57.320
[Guest]: at a very young age to be their public health expert.

02:21:57.320 --> 02:21:58.320
[Guest]: And he did a great job.

02:21:58.320 --> 02:22:02.920
[Guest]: He created, people say he's a, you know, the pioneer of public health in Brazil.

02:22:02.920 --> 02:22:07.520
[Guest]: And I'm pointing this out because Brazil today is on, you know, one spectrum with the government

02:22:07.520 --> 02:22:11.320
[Guest]: of Brazil is on this, literally an anti-science spectrum.

02:22:11.320 --> 02:22:14.880
[Guest]: If you plot the governments of the world today, Brazil is on one end where the president of

02:22:14.880 --> 02:22:19.600
[Guest]: Brazil continuously says, you know, that this is not even a virus, it can't do any harm,

02:22:19.600 --> 02:22:23.440
[Guest]: and taking blatantly sort of anti-scientific positions.

02:22:23.440 --> 02:22:28.480
[Guest]: And more than 100 years back, it was the Brazilian government who got in the best scientist possible

02:22:28.480 --> 02:22:29.480
[Guest]: to handle the outbreak.

02:22:29.480 --> 02:22:34.200
[Guest]: It just shows you, you know, how things have changed for Brazil over that 100 year period.

02:22:34.200 --> 02:22:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's great.

02:22:36.480 --> 02:22:43.040
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to talking about influenza now, where, you know, the way it strikes seems

02:22:43.040 --> 02:22:48.240
[Amit Varma]: to be like much more dramatic, like you have a quote at the start of your chapter from

02:22:48.240 --> 02:22:53.520
[Amit Varma]: the famous preliminary report on the influenza pandemic of 1918 in India, which is a report

02:22:53.520 --> 02:22:57.800
[Amit Varma]: from which that 6 million figure comes, as you point out later, and this quote goes,

02:22:57.800 --> 02:23:01.880
[Amit Varma]: quote, the hospitals were choked so that it was impossible to remove the dead quickly

02:23:01.880 --> 02:23:03.960
[Amit Varma]: enough to make room for the dying.

02:23:03.960 --> 02:23:07.600
[Amit Varma]: The streets and lanes of the cities were littered with dead and dying people.

02:23:07.600 --> 02:23:10.880
[Amit Varma]: The postal and telegraph services were completely disorganized.

02:23:10.880 --> 02:23:15.000
[Amit Varma]: The train service continued, but at all the principal stations, dead and dying people

02:23:15.000 --> 02:23:16.760
[Amit Varma]: were being removed from the trains.

02:23:16.760 --> 02:23:20.920
[Amit Varma]: The burning hearts and burial grounds were literally swamped with corpses, while an even

02:23:20.920 --> 02:23:22.880
[Amit Varma]: greater number of waited removal.

02:23:22.880 --> 02:23:28.480
[Amit Varma]: The depleted medical service itself, sorely stricken by the epidemic, was incapable of

02:23:28.480 --> 02:23:32.640
[Amit Varma]: dealing with more than just a minute fraction of the sickness requiring attention.

02:23:32.640 --> 02:23:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Nearly every household was lamenting a death and everywhere terror and confusion, rain,

02:23:37.640 --> 02:23:38.880
[Amit Varma]: stop code and a stark picture.

02:23:38.880 --> 02:23:43.360
[Amit Varma]: And also for if any of my writing students are listening to this an excellent use of

02:23:43.360 --> 02:23:49.160
[Amit Varma]: semicolons like they work much better than full stops here in terms of the accumulation

02:23:49.160 --> 02:23:52.440
[Amit Varma]: of effects and the impact that they have on you.

02:23:52.440 --> 02:23:57.760
[Amit Varma]: And while these are sort of general and abstract, you know, the writer Suryakant Tripathi, also

02:23:57.760 --> 02:24:02.920
[Amit Varma]: known as Nirala, wrote about how, quote, my family disappeared in the blink of an eye.

02:24:02.920 --> 02:24:06.600
[Amit Varma]: In whichever direction I turned, I saw darkness, stop quotes.

02:24:06.600 --> 02:24:11.200
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about influenza, you know, how people react to it.

02:24:11.200 --> 02:24:15.360
[Amit Varma]: What are the theories at the time that hey, what is causing this, which as you point out

02:24:15.360 --> 02:24:19.720
[Amit Varma]: till eight decades, we didn't know for sure what was causing it.

02:24:19.720 --> 02:24:20.840
[Amit Varma]: So what was that like?

02:24:20.840 --> 02:24:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Because by now, this is no longer like cholera, which is spreading slowly in a country where

02:24:25.000 --> 02:24:27.200
[Amit Varma]: the railways aren't there and all of that.

02:24:27.200 --> 02:24:29.760
[Amit Varma]: This is just weeping through populations.

02:24:29.760 --> 02:24:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this.

02:24:31.000 --> 02:24:32.000
[Guest]: Yes.

02:24:32.000 --> 02:24:35.120
[Guest]: Firstly, because, you know, this idea of flu, most people think of it as a cold, right?

02:24:35.120 --> 02:24:40.120
[Guest]: And the common cold is also part of this what they call is run up, you know, rhino viruses

02:24:40.120 --> 02:24:41.520
[Guest]: as they're called.

02:24:41.520 --> 02:24:43.800
[Guest]: But the flu comes from influenza.

02:24:43.800 --> 02:24:46.320
[Guest]: They had people heard of influenza in 1918.

02:24:46.320 --> 02:24:50.720
[Guest]: Yes, because there was something called as a 1890 influenza pandemic.

02:24:50.720 --> 02:24:52.400
[Guest]: So the 1918 was not the first one.

02:24:52.400 --> 02:24:55.760
[Guest]: In fact, historians kind of note down many pandemics, but they were not as leaded as

02:24:55.760 --> 02:24:56.760
[Guest]: the 1918 one.

02:24:56.760 --> 02:25:02.000
[Guest]: And in Indian medical circles, they were aware of what had happened in 1890.

02:25:02.000 --> 02:25:03.880
[Guest]: And it was called Nahi Sardhi Bukhaar, you know.

02:25:03.880 --> 02:25:08.120
[Guest]: So when it had first come, it was Nahi Sardhi Bukhaar.

02:25:08.120 --> 02:25:11.680
[Guest]: So the difference between influenza and the other two diseases, cholera and plague, is

02:25:11.680 --> 02:25:13.280
[Guest]: that it's not as glamorous.

02:25:13.280 --> 02:25:15.880
[Guest]: And that's because you don't have to go to the toilet or, you know, you don't have to

02:25:15.880 --> 02:25:16.880
[Guest]: eat nothing.

02:25:16.880 --> 02:25:18.560
[Guest]: Boils don't come on your body.

02:25:18.560 --> 02:25:22.440
[Guest]: You just get a fever and some chills and so on.

02:25:22.440 --> 02:25:27.160
[Guest]: The reigning medical knowledge at that time was bacteriology.

02:25:27.160 --> 02:25:33.120
[Guest]: In fact, virology was not even, you know, nobody knew about what are viruses and so

02:25:33.120 --> 02:25:34.120
[Guest]: on.

02:25:34.120 --> 02:25:38.400
[Guest]: And so people thought that influenza is called by something called Pfeiffer's bacillus, Pfeiffer

02:25:38.400 --> 02:25:41.960
[Guest]: being the name of a scientist and bacillus being bacteria.

02:25:41.960 --> 02:25:46.160
[Guest]: And this was 1893, I think, is when he kind of noted this.

02:25:46.160 --> 02:25:51.120
[Guest]: And so 1918, the medical establishment thought that this is just another strain of Pfeiffer's

02:25:51.120 --> 02:25:52.120
[Guest]: bacillus.

02:25:52.120 --> 02:25:56.520
[Guest]: And so all the vaccination efforts, which did take place, but they were completely futile,

02:25:56.520 --> 02:26:02.520
[Guest]: was on the basis of thinking that the flu is nothing but bacteria.

02:26:02.520 --> 02:26:06.640
[Guest]: So it's as, so it was, they got that quite wrong, you know, in the sense, it's like saying

02:26:06.640 --> 02:26:09.440
[Guest]: coronavirus today is not actually a virus.

02:26:09.440 --> 02:26:13.160
[Guest]: 50 years later, somebody says that it's actually not a virus, it was something else.

02:26:13.160 --> 02:26:16.200
[Guest]: So that's what people are working with the premise that it was bacteria, but it was not,

02:26:16.200 --> 02:26:17.200
[Guest]: it was a virus.

02:26:17.200 --> 02:26:19.780
[Guest]: So that was one big unknown, right?

02:26:19.780 --> 02:26:22.800
[Guest]: And that's why nobody really knew how to deal with this.

02:26:22.800 --> 02:26:28.600
[Guest]: 1918 influenza, the virulence was kind of unprecedented.

02:26:28.600 --> 02:26:32.000
[Guest]: Most people would say it has never happened since then also.

02:26:32.000 --> 02:26:39.080
[Guest]: It spread so quickly around the world, it, you know, it reached villages in remote Alaska,

02:26:39.080 --> 02:26:42.880
[Guest]: you know, it reached like, you know, islands in Pacific Ocean.

02:26:42.880 --> 02:26:48.800
[Guest]: Just some human contact was enough, but you required human contact, you know, and that

02:26:48.800 --> 02:26:54.800
[Guest]: is why the scientist Fred Hoyle, who's a famous astrophysicist, he, in fact, pointed out that

02:26:54.800 --> 02:26:59.520
[Guest]: how can it be so viral, you know, so he argued much later, many decades later, that this

02:26:59.520 --> 02:27:04.240
[Guest]: had to do with some sort of a meteoric dispersion, that some meteor was coming from outer space

02:27:04.240 --> 02:27:07.960
[Guest]: and think of it dispersing the virus or the, you know, and that by then they knew it as

02:27:07.960 --> 02:27:10.640
[Guest]: a virus across the world, right?

02:27:10.640 --> 02:27:15.600
[Guest]: But we have evidence of influenza not touching certain islands of the world, and it's precisely

02:27:15.600 --> 02:27:17.520
[Guest]: where no ships landed there, right?

02:27:17.520 --> 02:27:21.880
[Guest]: So it's precisely in those islands, which said, we are not going to take any ships coming

02:27:21.880 --> 02:27:26.920
[Guest]: in, which got that early warning notice, which completely escaped influenza.

02:27:26.920 --> 02:27:31.160
[Guest]: So there were literally a few parts of the world, which, you know, were without influenza

02:27:31.160 --> 02:27:32.160
[Guest]: at all.

02:27:32.160 --> 02:27:34.600
[Guest]: It was not only virulent, it was lethal, right?

02:27:34.600 --> 02:27:37.320
[Guest]: And so case fatality rates varied around the world.

02:27:37.320 --> 02:27:41.480
[Guest]: In India, it was unusually high, but typically in the range of, you know, three to 5%, which

02:27:41.480 --> 02:27:47.520
[Guest]: is very high combined with that virulence, and it devastated, you know, half a million

02:27:47.520 --> 02:27:52.400
[Guest]: deaths in the US back then, literally hundreds of thousands of deaths in Europe.

02:27:52.400 --> 02:27:54.160
[Guest]: The context is also important.

02:27:54.160 --> 02:27:57.160
[Guest]: It came during World War I, right?

02:27:57.160 --> 02:28:00.400
[Guest]: And it eventually killed many more people than the war itself.

02:28:00.400 --> 02:28:05.480
[Guest]: So the war ends in November 1918, but the bulk of the influenza deaths happened between

02:28:05.480 --> 02:28:10.360
[Guest]: September 1918, let's say August 1918, and December 19.

02:28:10.360 --> 02:28:13.940
[Guest]: So this is really a pandemic, which lasts for three months, though most people today

02:28:13.940 --> 02:28:17.080
[Guest]: classify that from 1918 to 1920.

02:28:17.080 --> 02:28:19.520
[Guest]: And that's why this book's title also takes 1920 as the end.

02:28:19.520 --> 02:28:25.080
[Guest]: But most of the deaths happened in a two or three month window, that is September, October,

02:28:25.080 --> 02:28:26.080
[Guest]: November of 1918.

02:28:26.080 --> 02:28:27.080
[Guest]: Where did it start?

02:28:27.080 --> 02:28:30.640
[Guest]: It's a, it's still a mystery.

02:28:30.640 --> 02:28:34.000
[Guest]: Most people would call it, you know, we'll say America and Kansas.

02:28:34.000 --> 02:28:36.640
[Guest]: That's what the reigning theory suggests.

02:28:36.640 --> 02:28:40.720
[Guest]: But it's famously called as the Spanish flu, nothing to do with Spain.

02:28:40.720 --> 02:28:45.160
[Guest]: It's just the fact that, you know, Spain happened to be neutral in World War I.

02:28:45.160 --> 02:28:50.160
[Guest]: And so it had, its press was reporting about the disease, and so more people heard about

02:28:50.160 --> 02:28:51.560
[Guest]: the flu in Spain.

02:28:51.560 --> 02:28:56.120
[Guest]: And that's how it earned the world, I mean, it's a complete misnomer, Spanish, it should

02:28:56.120 --> 02:28:59.880
[Guest]: actually be called the American flu, if you want to call it, you know, a particular name.

02:28:59.880 --> 02:29:02.520
[Guest]: It's more accurate to call it an American flu.

02:29:02.520 --> 02:29:04.320
[Guest]: But we now know it as the Spanish flu.

02:29:04.320 --> 02:29:06.920
[Guest]: And of course, one should not, I call it the influenza of 1918.

02:29:06.920 --> 02:29:11.320
[Guest]: I don't think we should be giving, you know, geographic descriptors to diseases.

02:29:11.320 --> 02:29:15.440
[Guest]: It comes to India, and it's in two waves, okay, it comes in two waves, and the first

02:29:15.440 --> 02:29:18.320
[Guest]: wave is mild, the second wave is devastating.

02:29:18.320 --> 02:29:22.560
[Guest]: And interestingly, it kills off people in the working age group.

02:29:22.560 --> 02:29:27.920
[Guest]: So unlike COVID, which is, you know, high mortality among the old people, or even plague,

02:29:27.920 --> 02:29:33.120
[Guest]: which also killed a lot of infants, apart from working age people, influenza had this

02:29:33.120 --> 02:29:38.800
[Guest]: unique W shaped signature, it killed off a lot of very young people, then its mortality

02:29:38.800 --> 02:29:44.960
[Guest]: impact was lesser in the 10 to 20 age group, 20 to 40 age group, it really sparked up,

02:29:44.960 --> 02:29:45.960
[Guest]: then it kind of went down.

02:29:45.960 --> 02:29:49.760
[Guest]: So if you see this mortality across age groups, it was W shaped.

02:29:49.760 --> 02:29:53.880
[Guest]: And that's the signature of the virus, because that W shape was observed around the world.

02:29:53.880 --> 02:29:57.920
[Guest]: And so a lot of theory as to why the scientific theory as to why it happened.

02:29:57.920 --> 02:30:00.080
[Guest]: And what do you do, it really attacked your lungs.

02:30:00.080 --> 02:30:03.520
[Guest]: So influenza was also directly linked with pneumonia, right?

02:30:03.520 --> 02:30:07.320
[Guest]: So in a sense, it attacked, and then, you know, the kind of pneumonia took over and

02:30:07.320 --> 02:30:08.320
[Guest]: kind of destroyed your body.

02:30:08.320 --> 02:30:13.960
[Guest]: And so literally, people's lungs would fill up with fluids, it would, one way to think

02:30:13.960 --> 02:30:17.880
[Guest]: about influenza death is your lungs completely giving way.

02:30:17.880 --> 02:30:21.600
[Guest]: And so many of these deaths, eventually, people have turned blue and so on, like cholera,

02:30:21.600 --> 02:30:23.160
[Guest]: but for a different reason.

02:30:23.160 --> 02:30:25.880
[Guest]: So that's the ghastly nature of influenza.

02:30:25.880 --> 02:30:29.960
[Guest]: At the end of the day, it's a flu and even flus are not supposed to be so lethal.

02:30:29.960 --> 02:30:35.600
[Guest]: But this particular strain was, and, you know, we can talk about why it was so devastating

02:30:35.600 --> 02:30:37.240
[Guest]: in India and so on.

02:30:37.240 --> 02:30:43.280
[Guest]: But the mortality estimates, at that time, globally, were placed at about 20 million.

02:30:43.280 --> 02:30:47.680
[Guest]: That number has been revised upwards, and only upwards since then.

02:30:47.680 --> 02:30:51.760
[Guest]: And the most, I would say the best estimates put it at about 40 million worldwide.

02:30:51.760 --> 02:30:55.680
[Guest]: We still don't know the exact numbers for China in terms of mortality.

02:30:55.680 --> 02:30:58.020
[Guest]: So that's a big blind spot.

02:30:58.020 --> 02:31:01.800
[Guest]: But there's some papers which say 50 million plus, you know, and so on.

02:31:01.800 --> 02:31:05.240
[Guest]: I think there's only one paper recently, which is putting down the number but 40 million

02:31:05.240 --> 02:31:10.040
[Guest]: is the go-to number now, global deaths due to influenza pandemic.

02:31:10.040 --> 02:31:15.760
[Guest]: And I argue in this book, I've taken up the estimate for India, in a way back to 20 million.

02:31:15.760 --> 02:31:19.560
[Guest]: You know, Kingsley Davis was a demographer, he kind of backed up the envelope calculation,

02:31:19.560 --> 02:31:22.360
[Guest]: he said 20 million in 1951.

02:31:22.360 --> 02:31:24.280
[Guest]: Then that number was brought down.

02:31:24.280 --> 02:31:29.720
[Guest]: So in 1918, when this report came out, called the preliminary report, the number, you know,

02:31:29.720 --> 02:31:34.940
[Guest]: Norman White, the health commissioner of that time gave was 65 to 6 million.

02:31:34.940 --> 02:31:37.440
[Guest]: This was only British India, so not princely states.

02:31:37.440 --> 02:31:41.560
[Guest]: So if you added, say, 1 million to that, you get maybe 7 million.

02:31:41.560 --> 02:31:46.560
[Guest]: It's really the census of India, you know, when they enumerated the census in 1921, that

02:31:46.560 --> 02:31:49.720
[Guest]: really the enormity of loss stood out.

02:31:49.720 --> 02:31:53.960
[Guest]: Because the census officials said, look, it was not 5 to 6 million, because that is not

02:31:53.960 --> 02:31:54.960
[Guest]: the number we're getting.

02:31:54.960 --> 02:31:59.040
[Guest]: Because when they went to the villages, they found villages just decimated.

02:31:59.040 --> 02:32:04.000
[Guest]: So it's interesting that it's about two or three years after the event, that actually

02:32:04.000 --> 02:32:06.560
[Guest]: the enormity of loss came in.

02:32:06.560 --> 02:32:09.920
[Guest]: Because remember, how do you even get this information on loss?

02:32:09.920 --> 02:32:13.800
[Guest]: You know, you have to have a newspaper system, you need to have news agencies.

02:32:13.800 --> 02:32:15.920
[Guest]: The point is, even those guys died.

02:32:15.920 --> 02:32:16.920
[Guest]: Even reporters died.

02:32:16.920 --> 02:32:19.400
[Guest]: So it was not really covered as an event.

02:32:19.400 --> 02:32:24.000
[Guest]: It got covered only when the census officials went and said, how many guys are there in

02:32:24.000 --> 02:32:25.000
[Guest]: the village?

02:32:25.000 --> 02:32:29.000
[Guest]: And you compare it with the previous census, and then you find a staggering gap.

02:32:29.000 --> 02:32:30.360
[Guest]: And so how do you explain this gap?

02:32:30.360 --> 02:32:33.440
[Guest]: Is it because of influenza or plague or other reasons?

02:32:33.440 --> 02:32:36.480
[Guest]: So there are certain methods to discern this, but there's no doubt that the influenza had

02:32:36.480 --> 02:32:37.920
[Guest]: a huge impact.

02:32:37.920 --> 02:32:43.560
[Guest]: And so the numbers, the estimates range between, I would say, 14 million.

02:32:43.560 --> 02:32:46.080
[Guest]: Siddharth Chandra has an estimate of 14 to 15 million.

02:32:46.080 --> 02:32:51.280
[Guest]: And I basically put it upwards more, because I found that actually mortality was much higher

02:32:51.280 --> 02:32:54.700
[Guest]: in Hyderabad state and Rajasthan.

02:32:54.700 --> 02:32:56.600
[Guest]: And that has never been accounted for till now.

02:32:56.600 --> 02:33:00.400
[Guest]: So this is my research claiming high mortality for these states.

02:33:00.400 --> 02:33:02.320
[Guest]: And so now the number is about 20 million for India.

02:33:02.320 --> 02:33:05.780
[Guest]: So these are my estimates for the mortality.

02:33:05.780 --> 02:33:10.360
[Amit Varma]: And what is absolutely nuts about all of this is, you know, we are thinking of 2020 as this

02:33:10.360 --> 02:33:11.360
[Amit Varma]: horrendous year.

02:33:11.360 --> 02:33:15.960
[Amit Varma]: It's almost a meme that somebody dies and, you know, people will tweet, oh no, 2020,

02:33:15.960 --> 02:33:17.240
[Amit Varma]: when will it get over?

02:33:17.240 --> 02:33:22.320
[Amit Varma]: But you know, 1917 and 1918 were almost like a perfect storm of horrendous events.

02:33:22.320 --> 02:33:27.680
[Amit Varma]: Like, as you pointed out in the book, a quote, India went from being abnormally wet in 1917,

02:33:27.680 --> 02:33:32.480
[Amit Varma]: suitable conditions from malaria and plague, to being abnormally dry in 1980, in a classic

02:33:32.480 --> 02:33:33.960
[Amit Varma]: condition for famine.

02:33:33.960 --> 02:33:38.120
[Amit Varma]: So you've got malaria, you've got plague, you've got famine, you've got influenza hitting

02:33:38.120 --> 02:33:43.520
[Amit Varma]: and killing 20 million people, plus you have all the political discontent, the Rollit Act,

02:33:43.520 --> 02:33:47.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, Jallianwala Bagh, it's all kind of going to hell.

02:33:47.000 --> 02:33:51.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, and in a sense, it's therefore, you know, not that surprising that, you know,

02:33:51.520 --> 02:33:56.360
[Amit Varma]: with all those glamorous events happening, the influenza has kind of been sort of overlooked.

02:33:56.360 --> 02:33:57.360
[Amit Varma]: And I'll come back to that.

02:33:57.360 --> 02:34:01.400
[Amit Varma]: I was also struck by one thing here, like one, of course, the common theme in all these

02:34:01.400 --> 02:34:05.920
[Amit Varma]: pandemics, including the current one, is the essential state failure, like you quote the

02:34:05.920 --> 02:34:10.720
[Amit Varma]: historian Mridula Raman Nair saying, quote, confusion and inconsistency seem to have marked

02:34:10.720 --> 02:34:14.080
[Amit Varma]: the response of the authorities throughout the presidency.

02:34:14.080 --> 02:34:20.120
[Amit Varma]: But what was heartening then, and is similar now, in a sense, is the response of civil

02:34:20.120 --> 02:34:21.120
[Amit Varma]: society.

02:34:21.120 --> 02:34:24.880
[Amit Varma]: Like, you write about how, quote, there were appeals in newspapers to send people from

02:34:24.880 --> 02:34:29.040
[Amit Varma]: voluntary service organizations in Bombay City to affected rural areas.

02:34:29.040 --> 02:34:33.320
[Amit Varma]: These organizations would emerge as a saving grace of the pandemic across India.

02:34:33.320 --> 02:34:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And then later, you write, quote, in Bombay City, the organizations aiding in this effort

02:34:37.360 --> 02:34:41.660
[Amit Varma]: were an eclectic mix of the Hindu Medical Association, the Social Service League led

02:34:41.660 --> 02:34:47.160
[Amit Varma]: by NM Joshi and its Influenza Relief Committee, community based hospitals for the Jains, Lohanas,

02:34:47.160 --> 02:34:53.160
[Amit Varma]: Marwaris, Boras and Parsis, St. George's Nursing Association, Young Men's Mohammedan Association,

02:34:53.160 --> 02:34:59.680
[Amit Varma]: Bombay Humanitarian League, Telugu Free Library, Japanese and Shanghai Peace Goods Association,

02:34:59.680 --> 02:35:00.680
[Amit Varma]: and dozens of others.

02:35:00.680 --> 02:35:06.040
[Amit Varma]: They distributed food, medicines, and often ran traveling dispensaries, stop quote.

02:35:06.040 --> 02:35:11.880
[Amit Varma]: Almost like, you know, a secular uprising of the people helping each other in times

02:35:11.880 --> 02:35:15.760
[Amit Varma]: of need when the state has failed, somewhat similar to what even happened here during

02:35:15.760 --> 02:35:20.940
[Amit Varma]: the migrant crisis or during the lockdown in general, where it was civil service groups

02:35:20.940 --> 02:35:25.340
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi and in Mumbai who fed so many thousands of people and help them out and help them

02:35:25.340 --> 02:35:26.500
[Amit Varma]: get home.

02:35:26.500 --> 02:35:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And all of that, what's your take on sort of this aspect of what was going on?

02:35:32.320 --> 02:35:36.380
[Amit Varma]: And you know, is it something that we only noticed during a pandemic that only comes

02:35:36.380 --> 02:35:42.120
[Amit Varma]: up in these times of emergency and otherwise we chill out and most of us we are like, hey,

02:35:42.120 --> 02:35:44.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, the government is there to do all this is not my work.

02:35:44.920 --> 02:35:49.360
[Amit Varma]: But suddenly when there's a major sort of tragedy like this, and you realize the state

02:35:49.360 --> 02:35:52.720
[Amit Varma]: can't handle it, then you go out and get the job done yourself.

02:35:52.720 --> 02:35:55.360
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, you know, it's a big question.

02:35:55.360 --> 02:36:00.120
[Guest]: I think state failure is obviously an obvious prompt for civil society to wake up.

02:36:00.120 --> 02:36:04.600
[Guest]: But I think there are many aspects of state failure, where civil society does not respond

02:36:04.600 --> 02:36:05.600
[Guest]: to.

02:36:05.600 --> 02:36:11.480
[Guest]: But pandemics, as you rightly pointed out, precisely because it affects all of us collectively,

02:36:11.480 --> 02:36:13.160
[Guest]: and we're all in it together.

02:36:13.160 --> 02:36:15.840
[Guest]: That is what kind of gets it, you know, much more prominence.

02:36:15.840 --> 02:36:21.520
[Guest]: And so, like you said, like, you know, like this year, 1918 was unprecedented in the amount

02:36:21.520 --> 02:36:22.520
[Guest]: of outpouring.

02:36:22.520 --> 02:36:28.080
[Guest]: I mean, literally everyone was in it to help others, because you could see I mean, if you

02:36:28.080 --> 02:36:32.120
[Guest]: want to think of like, you know, some of these zombie movies of people walking around dead

02:36:32.120 --> 02:36:34.880
[Guest]: people walking or people falling off dead, something like that.

02:36:34.880 --> 02:36:39.280
[Guest]: I mean, when you say 20 million people dying in a few months, this is literally like that,

02:36:39.280 --> 02:36:43.000
[Guest]: you know, first quotes of the book of this chapter says people literally getting off

02:36:43.000 --> 02:36:45.400
[Guest]: railway stations and their dead bodies around.

02:36:45.400 --> 02:36:48.520
[Guest]: And people dying on the streets, you know, it's that horrific.

02:36:48.520 --> 02:36:50.040
[Guest]: And so there are two possible responses.

02:36:50.040 --> 02:36:54.320
[Guest]: People go back into their houses and say, I'm not going to come out, or actually basically

02:36:54.320 --> 02:36:56.280
[Guest]: try and help others in certain ways.

02:36:56.280 --> 02:36:59.560
[Guest]: So the Mysore government, for example, you know, they started these dispensaries, they

02:36:59.560 --> 02:37:04.720
[Guest]: would have this unique medical system, the doctors would go to houses, take a note of

02:37:04.720 --> 02:37:05.720
[Guest]: what are you eating?

02:37:05.720 --> 02:37:06.840
[Guest]: What is your diet?

02:37:06.840 --> 02:37:11.280
[Guest]: And they had some basic prescription, because what they realized was, with some amount of

02:37:11.280 --> 02:37:14.520
[Guest]: nutrition, you could sail through it.

02:37:14.520 --> 02:37:18.280
[Guest]: As long as you're well nourished, you could get through the flu.

02:37:18.280 --> 02:37:22.360
[Guest]: But if you are not that well nourished, the mortality rates were just, you know, an absolute

02:37:22.360 --> 02:37:23.360
[Guest]: killer.

02:37:23.360 --> 02:37:26.200
[Guest]: So that's the kind of realization that people, you know, found out.

02:37:26.200 --> 02:37:31.200
[Guest]: And what it meant was that you could then, as an individual cut down mortality, not based

02:37:31.200 --> 02:37:37.160
[Guest]: on science, but just based on a reasoning, that when you saw, you know, a person get

02:37:37.160 --> 02:37:41.400
[Guest]: the influenza, it caused some pain, but the person didn't die, right.

02:37:41.400 --> 02:37:45.120
[Guest]: But when the person was not that well nourished, the person was dying.

02:37:45.120 --> 02:37:49.360
[Guest]: And that sort of idea that we need to get basic food and water out there, you know,

02:37:49.360 --> 02:37:50.360
[Guest]: a massive response.

02:37:50.360 --> 02:37:54.440
[Guest]: And so the public health commissioner, a guy called Norman White, as I say, he would later

02:37:54.440 --> 02:37:59.800
[Guest]: sarcastically quip that the outpouring of support in large numbers from the educated

02:37:59.800 --> 02:38:05.520
[Guest]: towards the poor, in times of distress was unprecedented, perhaps in the history of India.

02:38:05.520 --> 02:38:09.680
[Guest]: I mean, you know, he uses his words to say that this was an interesting episode, where

02:38:09.680 --> 02:38:12.920
[Guest]: the rich actually cared for the poor, right.

02:38:12.920 --> 02:38:16.000
[Guest]: And you know, it was truly a remarkable effort.

02:38:16.000 --> 02:38:17.000
[Guest]: Was it successful?

02:38:17.000 --> 02:38:21.400
[Guest]: All we can say that it must have prevented, you know, millions of more deaths.

02:38:21.400 --> 02:38:23.400
[Guest]: So it must have helped stop it.

02:38:23.400 --> 02:38:26.400
[Guest]: It was really herd immunity, which kind of stopped it eventually, right, in the sense

02:38:26.400 --> 02:38:28.840
[Guest]: it just ripped through the population.

02:38:28.840 --> 02:38:31.440
[Guest]: And it's still a bit of a mystery as to how it goes out.

02:38:31.440 --> 02:38:35.720
[Guest]: Maybe it mutates to lesser forms, or was it, you know, complete herd immunity.

02:38:35.720 --> 02:38:38.080
[Guest]: But whatever it is, the loss was just immense.

02:38:38.080 --> 02:38:44.040
[Guest]: And as Alfred Crosby, the historian says, the single largest demographic shock ever

02:38:44.040 --> 02:38:48.200
[Guest]: received to the human species, you know, so when we say 40 million people dying in a few

02:38:48.200 --> 02:38:53.560
[Guest]: months globally, and in that India being 20 million, this was a shock of like no other.

02:38:53.560 --> 02:38:58.160
[Guest]: You know, there's an oral history, Dr. Yogesh Kulkarni, who I cite in the book, who was

02:38:58.160 --> 02:39:03.800
[Guest]: on COVID duty this year, he asked in his village in, you know, Vidarbha region, rural Vidarbha,

02:39:03.800 --> 02:39:05.640
[Guest]: saying, you know, are there instances of this in the past?

02:39:05.640 --> 02:39:08.720
[Guest]: And interestingly, the memory lingered on, you know, of influenza.

02:39:08.720 --> 02:39:13.040
[Guest]: And this particular tribal leader from the Adivasi leader from the Gond tribe, stepped

02:39:13.040 --> 02:39:18.080
[Guest]: up and said, you know, my father in our family, they tell us the story of a time when so many

02:39:18.080 --> 02:39:24.000
[Guest]: people died, that a person had to be given alcohol to drive the bullock cart to dispose

02:39:24.000 --> 02:39:25.000
[Guest]: of all the bodies.

02:39:25.000 --> 02:39:30.800
[Guest]: You know, and just the sight of bodies stacking up is one of the defining images of influenza

02:39:30.800 --> 02:39:31.800
[Guest]: at this time.

02:39:31.800 --> 02:39:36.320
[Guest]: You know, Nirala talks about the Ganga being stacked with corpses, oral histories pointing

02:39:36.320 --> 02:39:41.120
[Guest]: out to bodies being thrown off the cliff, really staggering number of deaths, you know,

02:39:41.120 --> 02:39:43.200
[Guest]: which which took place out here.

02:39:43.200 --> 02:39:47.120
[Guest]: And one of these, the sub stories of this is that it kind of came on the back of a drought,

02:39:47.120 --> 02:39:50.840
[Guest]: you know, and so that was an important part of the story, that the drought had led to

02:39:50.840 --> 02:39:55.000
[Guest]: a lot of under nutrition, which can influence action.

02:39:55.000 --> 02:39:59.680
[Amit Varma]: And there's also sort of the an unintended consequences or an unseen effect, as it were,

02:39:59.680 --> 02:40:03.920
[Amit Varma]: at one point, you write and this is from bodies piling up, and at one point, you write, quote,

02:40:03.920 --> 02:40:07.560
[Amit Varma]: in the hilly areas of Kumao, corpses were thrown into the jungle.

02:40:07.560 --> 02:40:11.640
[Amit Varma]: And according to the writer, Jim Corbett, led to leopards developing a taste for human

02:40:11.640 --> 02:40:15.800
[Amit Varma]: flesh, and thus being labeled man eaters, stop code.

02:40:15.800 --> 02:40:20.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, to think that we blame leopards and pass judgment on them, and, you know,

02:40:20.440 --> 02:40:24.600
[Amit Varma]: it's not their fault what are they to do a similar unintended consequences that you know,

02:40:24.600 --> 02:40:30.480
[Amit Varma]: you point out how Godrej move like Godrej was founded in 1897 to make security equipment.

02:40:30.480 --> 02:40:36.640
[Amit Varma]: And in 1918, they moved to manufacturing washing soap bars, which is a classic example of incentives.

02:40:36.640 --> 02:40:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of now, you know, before we move on to a final section, and we'll keep it brief,

02:40:41.400 --> 02:40:43.520
[Amit Varma]: because I know I've held you long enough.

02:40:43.520 --> 02:40:49.560
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to sort of the aftermath and the consequences of, you know, the influenza

02:40:49.560 --> 02:40:53.960
[Amit Varma]: pandemic over here, because as you point out, it's not just a debt toll.

02:40:53.960 --> 02:40:59.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, at one point, you say it is possible that in 1918, 40 to 60% of the Indian population

02:40:59.640 --> 02:41:00.640
[Amit Varma]: contracted the flu.

02:41:00.640 --> 02:41:03.440
[Amit Varma]: This has consequences even on those who survive.

02:41:03.440 --> 02:41:08.480
[Amit Varma]: You estimate that the GDP that year, you know, went down by 10%.

02:41:08.480 --> 02:41:10.040
[Amit Varma]: And all kinds of things are happening.

02:41:10.040 --> 02:41:13.320
[Amit Varma]: Because more women than men are dying, the birth rates also go down.

02:41:13.320 --> 02:41:18.840
[Amit Varma]: And all kinds of shit is playing out over the long term, there's a supply side shock.

02:41:18.840 --> 02:41:23.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, when it comes to labor supply, there's a demographic impact, all of these things

02:41:23.240 --> 02:41:24.240
[Amit Varma]: are happening.

02:41:24.240 --> 02:41:30.440
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about what these kind of impacts of that particular pandemic were.

02:41:30.440 --> 02:41:33.280
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, the economic loss was massive.

02:41:33.280 --> 02:41:37.000
[Guest]: Yeah, partly because the drought, but also because simply, this is the classic supply

02:41:37.000 --> 02:41:40.520
[Guest]: side shock, as economists would call it, that simply there are no people and hence there's

02:41:40.520 --> 02:41:41.520
[Guest]: no production.

02:41:41.520 --> 02:41:45.480
[Guest]: You know, and so we say the GDP fell by about 10%.

02:41:45.480 --> 02:41:50.360
[Guest]: It's in fact instructive, right, that in India's recorded macroeconomic history from 1901 to

02:41:50.360 --> 02:41:56.560
[Guest]: now, the two years in which India saw a negative 10% kind of fall were both pandemic years.

02:41:56.560 --> 02:42:00.040
[Guest]: And that's why I feel, you know, economic students, who often know a lot about what

02:42:00.040 --> 02:42:04.200
[Guest]: the Great Depression did to the US economy, should be taught in India about what pandemics

02:42:04.200 --> 02:42:08.720
[Guest]: can do to your economy, because they've had such a big importance in Indian history.

02:42:08.720 --> 02:42:11.680
[Guest]: So you know, agricultural yields fell that particular year.

02:42:11.680 --> 02:42:15.480
[Guest]: The big impact was on labor, you know, and what a big argument I make in this book is

02:42:15.480 --> 02:42:20.960
[Guest]: that influenza gave birth to India's labor movement in a big way, right.

02:42:20.960 --> 02:42:26.960
[Guest]: And I use this, I show this using, you know, the spike in articles on, like, if you look

02:42:26.960 --> 02:42:31.680
[Guest]: at the Times of India database, the number of times the word unions or labor is kind

02:42:31.680 --> 02:42:35.760
[Guest]: of mentioned, spikes up dramatically after influenza.

02:42:35.760 --> 02:42:39.440
[Guest]: And there are tons of documents from the Royal Labor Commission, a variety of sources, which

02:42:39.440 --> 02:42:44.320
[Guest]: tell you it's that particular three months, which changed the game for labor, simply because

02:42:44.320 --> 02:42:47.960
[Guest]: if you don't have 20 million people, what are, you know, people who are going to employ

02:42:47.960 --> 02:42:49.400
[Guest]: these people, they get tremendous.

02:42:49.400 --> 02:42:53.240
[Guest]: So the guys who were left behind, get tremendous bargaining power.

02:42:53.240 --> 02:42:54.400
[Guest]: And so wage rates start going up.

02:42:54.400 --> 02:42:58.320
[Guest]: So some amount of labor, the conditions of labor tend to improve.

02:42:58.320 --> 02:43:00.660
[Guest]: But more important for the freedom movement.

02:43:00.660 --> 02:43:05.640
[Guest]: These guys now see, of course, I mean, influenza is a rallying point, you see so many people

02:43:05.640 --> 02:43:06.640
[Guest]: dying.

02:43:06.640 --> 02:43:11.320
[Guest]: It's very clear that the British are not the so called benevolent rulers, there is massive

02:43:11.320 --> 02:43:15.040
[Guest]: calamity, which has happened, and there's a lot of opposition to the British that's

02:43:15.040 --> 02:43:16.040
[Guest]: coming out of this.

02:43:16.040 --> 02:43:20.120
[Guest]: And then, of course, you know, stuff like Jallianwala Malabar tragedy, and so on.

02:43:20.120 --> 02:43:23.000
[Guest]: So that's, you know, a huge part of the story.

02:43:23.000 --> 02:43:27.960
[Guest]: The idea that public health, I mean, it was, you know, the leading official in health Norman

02:43:27.960 --> 02:43:33.200
[Guest]: White at that time, they were called the sanitary commissioners of India, you know, it's after

02:43:33.200 --> 02:43:36.440
[Guest]: influenza that they call it the public health commissioners of India.

02:43:36.440 --> 02:43:41.840
[Guest]: So the word public health itself comes into our consciousness, really, thanks to influenza,

02:43:41.840 --> 02:43:45.400
[Guest]: you know, there's some improvement, not much improvement, but there's some improvement

02:43:45.400 --> 02:43:49.480
[Guest]: in the uptake of medical colleges, because people realize that when wherever there was

02:43:49.480 --> 02:43:53.060
[Guest]: some amount of medical facilities offered, people could survive the flu.

02:43:53.060 --> 02:43:57.000
[Guest]: And so one obvious, you know, counterpoint was that if you increase medical facilities,

02:43:57.000 --> 02:43:58.000
[Guest]: then it would be good.

02:43:58.000 --> 02:44:03.040
[Guest]: It did not get so much international opinion, or, you know, criticism, like the Bengals

02:44:03.040 --> 02:44:07.200
[Guest]: for example, much later, but the Americans, you know, I mentioned there's a, even in the

02:44:07.200 --> 02:44:11.360
[Guest]: American politics, people are pointing out to what's happening in India, saying how can

02:44:11.360 --> 02:44:14.640
[Guest]: so many people be allowed to die at that point.

02:44:14.640 --> 02:44:19.880
[Guest]: So emphasis on public health slowly sort of improves, the labor movement starts off in

02:44:19.880 --> 02:44:20.880
[Guest]: a big way.

02:44:20.880 --> 02:44:26.320
[Guest]: Again, like the cooperative movement and plague, the cooperative movement also starts rising.

02:44:26.320 --> 02:44:31.240
[Guest]: But the biggest impact is that the death rate of India finally starts falling.

02:44:31.240 --> 02:44:36.840
[Guest]: And that's why influenza bookends India's, you can say millennia worth of, you know,

02:44:36.840 --> 02:44:37.840
[Guest]: mass mortality.

02:44:37.840 --> 02:44:41.600
[Guest]: And 1920 is when the death rate starts falling.

02:44:41.600 --> 02:44:43.280
[Guest]: And that's two reasons.

02:44:43.280 --> 02:44:47.880
[Guest]: One is both, all three, cholera, plague, and influenza start ebbing, you know, because

02:44:47.880 --> 02:44:52.080
[Guest]: there's better understanding of cholera and plague, and influenza is kind of a one-off.

02:44:52.080 --> 02:44:57.400
[Guest]: But influenza kills off so many people who would have otherwise died of cholera and plague

02:44:57.400 --> 02:44:59.000
[Guest]: in the next years, right?

02:44:59.000 --> 02:45:02.520
[Guest]: So in a strange way, it kind of knocks out so many people, but the people who are left

02:45:02.520 --> 02:45:06.480
[Guest]: there then, kind of surviving or living for longer time periods.

02:45:06.480 --> 02:45:10.440
[Guest]: So India's demographic transition begins at the end of influenza.

02:45:10.440 --> 02:45:11.440
[Guest]: Why?

02:45:11.440 --> 02:45:16.160
[Guest]: Because once death rates start falling, over time, birth rates start falling, and that's

02:45:16.160 --> 02:45:18.760
[Guest]: when India's population growth really starts to grow.

02:45:18.760 --> 02:45:23.840
[Guest]: So you know, how we became a billion people, I mean, throughout history, we had high death

02:45:23.840 --> 02:45:25.640
[Guest]: rates and high birth rates.

02:45:25.640 --> 02:45:30.120
[Guest]: And our population fluctuated between most estimates between 100 and 200 million people.

02:45:30.120 --> 02:45:34.640
[Guest]: It's only after influenza that actually death rates started falling substantially.

02:45:34.640 --> 02:45:38.440
[Guest]: And the Indian population started growing steadily, you know, from 300 to 400 to 500.

02:45:38.440 --> 02:45:41.680
[Guest]: And today, we are 1.2 billion people.

02:45:41.680 --> 02:45:49.280
[Guest]: So India's falling death rates, really, that journey starts off from the end of influenza.

02:45:49.280 --> 02:45:52.800
[Guest]: And so that's why it marks the end of an epoch of mass mortality.

02:45:52.800 --> 02:45:57.120
[Amit Varma]: I like the way you point out that if they hadn't died of influenza, they would have

02:45:57.120 --> 02:46:01.600
[Amit Varma]: died of cholera or the plague, you know, if one guy doesn't get you, the other guy will.

02:46:01.600 --> 02:46:02.600
[Amit Varma]: So where are you going to run?

02:46:02.600 --> 02:46:07.920
[Amit Varma]: So we are indeed, you know, those of us who are still here in 2020, so incredibly fortunate

02:46:07.920 --> 02:46:12.560
[Amit Varma]: that we just have, you know, two enemies to contend with two dangers to ourselves.

02:46:12.560 --> 02:46:13.560
[Amit Varma]: One is COVID-19.

02:46:13.560 --> 02:46:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And the other is the flailing state.

02:46:16.120 --> 02:46:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, my next question is sort of, you know, you have a chapter at the end where you look

02:46:21.000 --> 02:46:25.360
[Amit Varma]: at COVID through the rearview mirror, you look at the lessons of the past for COVID.

02:46:25.360 --> 02:46:29.160
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that you point out is about the incentives of politicians, about

02:46:29.160 --> 02:46:34.880
[Amit Varma]: how what we see nowadays is that politicians actually have an incentive to downplay pandemic

02:46:34.880 --> 02:46:35.880
[Amit Varma]: deaths.

02:46:35.880 --> 02:46:40.240
[Amit Varma]: And they can do this by underreporting them or they can, you know, file something under

02:46:40.240 --> 02:46:42.840
[Amit Varma]: pneumonia, or they could simply not test.

02:46:42.840 --> 02:46:46.280
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, Donald Trump famously said that one way of getting the COVID numbers

02:46:46.280 --> 02:46:51.480
[Amit Varma]: down is, you know, test a little bit less than the logic there is, of course, impeccable,

02:46:51.480 --> 02:46:53.560
[Amit Varma]: except that he was making it explicit.

02:46:53.560 --> 02:46:56.280
[Amit Varma]: And these incentives work on all politicians.

02:46:56.280 --> 02:47:01.100
[Amit Varma]: So one, you know, there is this because I think one of the truths that modern politicians

02:47:01.100 --> 02:47:04.760
[Amit Varma]: have figured out that to a large extent, governance doesn't matter, narratives do.

02:47:04.760 --> 02:47:08.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, obviously, if you go to the extreme, then governance will also matter if people

02:47:08.400 --> 02:47:09.760
[Amit Varma]: are dying in the streets.

02:47:09.760 --> 02:47:15.320
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, it is really the narratives that matter and your incentive is towards,

02:47:15.320 --> 02:47:18.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, looking after the narrative and not actually doing anything about the problem.

02:47:18.760 --> 02:47:21.800
[Amit Varma]: Quite often, it will come from denying the problem.

02:47:21.800 --> 02:47:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And another aspect of this is in, you know, the tail end risk, for example, you point

02:47:27.840 --> 02:47:32.320
[Amit Varma]: out that, you know, all of these things are foreseeable, you know, Bill Gates famously

02:47:32.320 --> 02:47:35.520
[Amit Varma]: said, you know, five years ago that the next pandemic is going to be vicious.

02:47:35.520 --> 02:47:40.520
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that a politician's incentive will always be to downplay the tail risk,

02:47:40.520 --> 02:47:45.120
[Amit Varma]: because your bandwidth is limited, there are only so many things you can do and talk about.

02:47:45.120 --> 02:47:49.680
[Amit Varma]: So if something is an extremely low probability event with extremely high costs, despite the

02:47:49.680 --> 02:47:53.400
[Amit Varma]: high cost, the probability is so low that you're best off ignoring it.

02:47:53.400 --> 02:47:57.880
[Amit Varma]: And when people do talk about, you know, tail risk, such as, you know, every time there

02:47:57.880 --> 02:48:02.240
[Amit Varma]: is the warning of a pandemic, which doesn't quite become a pandemic, like bird flu or

02:48:02.240 --> 02:48:07.240
[Amit Varma]: swine flu or whatever, then, you know, it seems like what was a fuss all about and wasn't

02:48:07.240 --> 02:48:08.600
[Amit Varma]: that a false alarm.

02:48:08.600 --> 02:48:14.520
[Amit Varma]: So how does one then think about the incentives of politicians, like I completely get your

02:48:14.520 --> 02:48:20.120
[Amit Varma]: point that collective memory is important, that is, in fact, what helped, you know, Southeast

02:48:20.120 --> 02:48:24.920
[Amit Varma]: Asia deal with this current pandemic, because they've been through those previous scares,

02:48:24.920 --> 02:48:28.440
[Amit Varma]: and they kind of got their act together, you know, Kerala dealt with Nipah, which is why

02:48:28.440 --> 02:48:30.640
[Amit Varma]: they were a little more efficient here.

02:48:30.640 --> 02:48:34.880
[Amit Varma]: But having said all of that, it's also true that, you know, the incentives of politicians

02:48:34.880 --> 02:48:38.000
[Amit Varma]: are in a different direction, and so on.

02:48:38.000 --> 02:48:39.000
[Amit Varma]: So what are your thoughts on this?

02:48:39.000 --> 02:48:45.720
[Guest]: I think, you know, politicians have to claim, you know, that they're doing a good job.

02:48:45.720 --> 02:48:50.480
[Guest]: That's the basic objective of every politician, whether it's Trump or, you know, any any politician

02:48:50.480 --> 02:48:54.560
[Guest]: going to try and sell this idea that we're doing a great job.

02:48:54.560 --> 02:48:58.880
[Guest]: Now, can we objectively say that somebody is doing a great job?

02:48:58.880 --> 02:49:01.000
[Guest]: What I say in the book is actually no.

02:49:01.000 --> 02:49:05.240
[Guest]: What we can objectively say if somebody is not doing a great job, you know, it's asymmetric

02:49:05.240 --> 02:49:09.760
[Guest]: in the sense that if, you know, Pakistan has very few deaths and, you know, the economy

02:49:09.760 --> 02:49:13.920
[Guest]: is not tanked as much as in India, you know, does that mean Pakistan has managed it much

02:49:13.920 --> 02:49:14.920
[Guest]: better?

02:49:14.920 --> 02:49:15.920
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:49:15.920 --> 02:49:16.920
[Guest]: Right.

02:49:16.920 --> 02:49:20.480
[Guest]: But I can definitely say that US has managed it badly, because they've got, you know, deaths

02:49:20.480 --> 02:49:23.480
[Guest]: per capita is fairly high on the global spectrum and so on.

02:49:23.480 --> 02:49:28.760
[Guest]: So the way I'm looking at this is, you know, don't celebrate people like New Zealand is

02:49:28.760 --> 02:49:32.600
[Guest]: the classic poster child right now of good pandemic management.

02:49:32.600 --> 02:49:33.600
[Guest]: I would say don't do that.

02:49:33.600 --> 02:49:36.080
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think New Zealand has done a great or bad job.

02:49:36.080 --> 02:49:39.120
[Guest]: All we can say is that some countries have messed up big time.

02:49:39.120 --> 02:49:41.720
[Guest]: And US is probably the classic case of that.

02:49:41.720 --> 02:49:43.640
[Guest]: India is, I mean, not really.

02:49:43.640 --> 02:49:46.740
[Guest]: If you look at any objective measure, it's not that bad.

02:49:46.740 --> 02:49:48.680
[Guest]: But in our neighborhood, we are the worst.

02:49:48.680 --> 02:49:51.060
[Guest]: That we can say for sure.

02:49:51.060 --> 02:49:54.520
[Guest]: So the politics of pandemics is, you know, first is how much to intervene?

02:49:54.520 --> 02:49:56.240
[Guest]: You know, that's the big question.

02:49:56.240 --> 02:49:57.600
[Guest]: How much should be locked on?

02:49:57.600 --> 02:50:01.520
[Guest]: And the decision we took, for example, was on this probability that, you know, suppose

02:50:01.520 --> 02:50:05.800
[Guest]: it goes out of hand, then the loss will be too much for us.

02:50:05.800 --> 02:50:08.760
[Guest]: Now in hindsight, of course, maybe some would say it was too harsh.

02:50:08.760 --> 02:50:12.440
[Guest]: It was definitely not well thought out because we got a migration crisis unnecessary out

02:50:12.440 --> 02:50:15.240
[Guest]: of it.

02:50:15.240 --> 02:50:19.680
[Guest]: But I think this is this tension between economics and epidemiology, which is also there in this

02:50:19.680 --> 02:50:22.680
[Guest]: age of pandemics, kind of replayed very classically this year.

02:50:22.680 --> 02:50:26.880
[Guest]: Interestingly, there's already a research study which shows countries which are closer

02:50:26.880 --> 02:50:31.160
[Guest]: to elections, you know, did not intervene that much.

02:50:31.160 --> 02:50:34.280
[Guest]: So U.S. had an election this year, and they did not do much.

02:50:34.280 --> 02:50:35.280
[Guest]: Why?

02:50:35.280 --> 02:50:39.240
[Guest]: Because the economic losses are so massive, right, that it will basically hurt your electoral

02:50:39.240 --> 02:50:40.240
[Guest]: prospects.

02:50:40.240 --> 02:50:46.000
[Guest]: So that's one theory, that is, countries which were closer to election actually did not intervene

02:50:46.000 --> 02:50:47.000
[Guest]: that much.

02:50:47.000 --> 02:50:48.800
[Guest]: So that's one way to look at it.

02:50:48.800 --> 02:50:54.120
[Guest]: On a more grand scale, of course, you know, between the last age and this age of pandemics,

02:50:54.120 --> 02:50:58.160
[Guest]: that time there were imperial powers and Britain did not really invest as much in public health

02:50:58.160 --> 02:51:02.480
[Guest]: to control cholera in India vis-a-vis with what they were doing in Britain.

02:51:02.480 --> 02:51:03.680
[Guest]: So obviously democracies help.

02:51:03.680 --> 02:51:08.760
[Guest]: So that's a working hypothesis, that democracies are going to be better off at understanding

02:51:08.760 --> 02:51:13.240
[Guest]: pandemics because the information base will hopefully be more timely and so on.

02:51:13.240 --> 02:51:16.520
[Guest]: In any case, the death reporting hopefully is much better.

02:51:16.520 --> 02:51:21.080
[Guest]: Like today, if you ask me how many people died of, you know, COVID in China, I don't

02:51:21.080 --> 02:51:22.080
[Unknown]: know what is the number.

02:51:22.080 --> 02:51:26.000
[Guest]: You know, there's a stated number, but nobody really knows what is the actual number in

02:51:26.000 --> 02:51:27.000
[Guest]: Iran.

02:51:27.000 --> 02:51:32.240
[Guest]: But you can be quite sure of the numbers in the US, in many of the other countries.

02:51:32.240 --> 02:51:37.320
[Guest]: And so that's one thing that, you know, democracy really gives well.

02:51:37.320 --> 02:51:43.080
[Guest]: The other thing about pandemics, as I said, is about this, the regional variation of deaths.

02:51:43.080 --> 02:51:45.840
[Guest]: And we saw that very starkly in India, you know, every now and then.

02:51:45.840 --> 02:51:47.760
[Guest]: So Kerala was this model.

02:51:47.760 --> 02:51:53.460
[Guest]: Then even today, Kerala is leading on the most indicators of COVID deaths and so on.

02:51:53.460 --> 02:51:58.240
[Guest]: But it's changed, you know, from what Kerala was six months back to now, things have slightly

02:51:58.240 --> 02:52:00.280
[Guest]: changed in the pecking order.

02:52:00.280 --> 02:52:03.840
[Guest]: And what pandemic history tells you is that this will happen, you know, at some point,

02:52:03.840 --> 02:52:07.640
[Guest]: some regions will have more deaths, some other regions will have more.

02:52:07.640 --> 02:52:10.920
[Guest]: There'll be some reasons which science will tell us, you know, five years down the line

02:52:10.920 --> 02:52:16.440
[Guest]: as to why COVID mortality was much higher in some parts of the world than others.

02:52:16.440 --> 02:52:21.480
[Guest]: And so what the kind of inference I'm taking as a starting off is, is that good pandemic

02:52:21.480 --> 02:52:25.080
[Guest]: management, you know, the state has an important role to play.

02:52:25.080 --> 02:52:29.600
[Guest]: But there are a variety of other factors, right, including the disease, you know, etiology

02:52:29.600 --> 02:52:30.600
[Guest]: and so on.

02:52:30.600 --> 02:52:34.760
[Guest]: Just like why, you know, plague hit Bombay and Punjab, but not so much Eastern and Southern

02:52:34.760 --> 02:52:35.760
[Guest]: India.

02:52:35.760 --> 02:52:39.740
[Guest]: It didn't really have much to do, it had more to do with the nature of the rats and fleas.

02:52:39.740 --> 02:52:43.920
[Guest]: And so there is this role of the disease itself, the unique characteristics of the disease

02:52:43.920 --> 02:52:46.420
[Guest]: itself, and the impact it's having.

02:52:46.420 --> 02:52:51.720
[Guest]: And politicians, of course, will always try and, as I say, compare losses with somebody

02:52:51.720 --> 02:52:53.080
[Guest]: doing worse than them, right.

02:52:53.080 --> 02:52:55.960
[Guest]: And so that's why in India, we're comparing ourselves with US.

02:52:55.960 --> 02:52:59.240
[Guest]: If we compare ourselves with other countries in South Asia, we are the worst off.

02:52:59.240 --> 02:53:04.740
[Guest]: So this sort of, who are you comparing against is, you know, every politician sort of choice

02:53:04.740 --> 02:53:05.740
[Guest]: to make.

02:53:05.740 --> 02:53:10.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and you know, one of the heartening things at least is how far the science has

02:53:10.880 --> 02:53:15.160
[Amit Varma]: progressed and not in an incremental way, but almost exponentially in the sense that,

02:53:15.160 --> 02:53:19.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, when influenza hit in 1918, you know, people promised that there'll be a vaccine

02:53:19.800 --> 02:53:23.880
[Amit Varma]: soon and they only started work on a vaccine in the 1940s.

02:53:23.880 --> 02:53:27.240
[Amit Varma]: And regardless, while they found vaccines for other kinds of the flu, there's never

02:53:27.240 --> 02:53:29.480
[Amit Varma]: been a vaccine for the coronavirus before this.

02:53:29.480 --> 02:53:33.000
[Amit Varma]: I remember, you know, epidemiologists saying this year that there may never be a vaccine

02:53:33.000 --> 02:53:36.240
[Amit Varma]: for COVID-19 because while, you know, there have been other flu vaccines, nothing for

02:53:36.240 --> 02:53:41.080
[Amit Varma]: a coronavirus, look how long the HIV vaccine has been in the making, yet here we are.

02:53:41.080 --> 02:53:45.400
[Amit Varma]: And this is like, so incredibly remarkable.

02:53:45.400 --> 02:53:49.320
[Amit Varma]: Now that your book is out, and now that we've kind of discussed some of the lessons in terms

02:53:49.320 --> 02:53:54.000
[Amit Varma]: of governance and the way people react and the importance of collective memory and all

02:53:54.000 --> 02:53:55.000
[Amit Varma]: that.

02:53:55.000 --> 02:53:59.080
[Amit Varma]: But the other factor in this is, of course, the science, which is advancing massively.

02:53:59.080 --> 02:54:03.160
[Amit Varma]: But you know, nevertheless, it could be said that, you know, viruses and bacteria have

02:54:03.160 --> 02:54:08.880
[Amit Varma]: always kind of had the upper hand against us, if not colonized us entirely, in a much

02:54:08.880 --> 02:54:12.240
[Amit Varma]: deeper way than the British could manage.

02:54:12.240 --> 02:54:16.720
[Amit Varma]: So when you kind of look at the future, you know, when the next pandemic comes, will we

02:54:16.720 --> 02:54:18.600
[Amit Varma]: have learned the lessons of this one?

02:54:18.600 --> 02:54:22.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, is there a sort of given everybody's incentives and the imperatives?

02:54:22.560 --> 02:54:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Is there a classic road it'll go down on?

02:54:25.200 --> 02:54:29.240
[Amit Varma]: Like at one point, you talk about the stages of a pandemic and the, you know, the way you

02:54:29.240 --> 02:54:35.400
[Amit Varma]: have classified it is between denial, confusion, acceptance, and erasure, which, you know,

02:54:35.400 --> 02:54:39.120
[Amit Varma]: I found quite enlightening in light of all that you write in the book and in light of

02:54:39.120 --> 02:54:41.920
[Amit Varma]: all that sort of happened in this year.

02:54:41.920 --> 02:54:47.240
[Amit Varma]: So do you think that we'll at some point, you know, learn from the past and nail the

02:54:47.240 --> 02:54:50.000
[Amit Varma]: correct response to something like this?

02:54:50.000 --> 02:54:51.000
[Guest]: I think it's possible.

02:54:51.000 --> 02:54:56.320
[Guest]: As I say, you know, pandemics cannot be eradicated, but pandemics can be curtailed.

02:54:56.320 --> 02:54:57.320
[Guest]: And that is all that you can do.

02:54:57.320 --> 02:55:00.960
[Guest]: I mean, there will be epidemic outbreaks in the future, but it's about how you respond

02:55:00.960 --> 02:55:02.200
[Guest]: to it.

02:55:02.200 --> 02:55:06.600
[Guest]: And I think first, obviously, trust science and trust what the scientists are saying.

02:55:06.600 --> 02:55:11.480
[Guest]: But I think what this pandemic has shown that this classic recommendation of a lockdown,

02:55:11.480 --> 02:55:16.480
[Guest]: while obviously very useful, you know, in a country like India has massive social costs

02:55:16.480 --> 02:55:21.960
[Guest]: because the impact of a lockdown varies across different occupational groups.

02:55:21.960 --> 02:55:26.080
[Guest]: Those who can't work from home, simply put, are simply, you know, getting poorer by the

02:55:26.080 --> 02:55:27.200
[Guest]: day.

02:55:27.200 --> 02:55:30.320
[Guest]: And so hopefully some of these learnings, so having a good social security net for people

02:55:30.320 --> 02:55:34.720
[Guest]: who are going to lose out, you know, in this place, like, for example, the migration crisis

02:55:34.720 --> 02:55:38.400
[Guest]: was completely anticipable, at least for those who studied migration.

02:55:38.400 --> 02:55:41.400
[Guest]: Hopefully when the next pandemic comes, we don't have a migration crisis.

02:55:41.400 --> 02:55:44.520
[Guest]: I think that's the learning, you know, that can happen.

02:55:44.520 --> 02:55:48.320
[Guest]: And that's what past pandemics tell you, that is, you know, you have to anticipate migration.

02:55:48.320 --> 02:55:52.760
[Guest]: So you either ensure that there's enough social security given so that people are not thinking

02:55:52.760 --> 02:55:56.760
[Guest]: of going back, or you allow them to go back first up and then do the lockdown, you know,

02:55:56.760 --> 02:56:01.080
[Guest]: it's one of these two, but you can't do neither of them, as we saw earlier this year.

02:56:01.080 --> 02:56:05.440
[Guest]: So there are lessons to take from this pandemic into the next, there are lessons to take from

02:56:05.440 --> 02:56:06.800
[Guest]: past pandemics.

02:56:06.800 --> 02:56:12.040
[Guest]: And as I said, the lesser we erase, the more likely or the less likely we are going to

02:56:12.040 --> 02:56:13.960
[Guest]: deny when the next comes.

02:56:13.960 --> 02:56:18.440
[Guest]: So these four stages of, you know, denial, confusion, acceptance and erasure.

02:56:18.440 --> 02:56:23.120
[Guest]: And if we don't erase the memory, you know, then we are less likely to deny and we are

02:56:23.120 --> 02:56:28.320
[Guest]: more likely to move on to that acceptance phase in a way of smart science, that is,

02:56:28.320 --> 02:56:33.120
[Guest]: you look at the best technologies available to combat a pandemic, and then move on.

02:56:33.120 --> 02:56:38.720
[Guest]: So clearly, I mean, I'm convinced that there's a role to kind of memorialize certain events,

02:56:38.720 --> 02:56:44.440
[Guest]: especially in the medical community, which is the front runner to kind of contain a pandemic.

02:56:44.440 --> 02:56:49.400
[Guest]: So you know, one of the things I'm getting from the medical community is that if only

02:56:49.400 --> 02:56:54.520
[Guest]: they had known about this migrant world, for example, then some of the recommendations

02:56:54.520 --> 02:56:59.960
[Guest]: would not, because the guys who recommended our government in March, who almost all doctors,

02:56:59.960 --> 02:57:03.640
[Guest]: which is good, right, but nobody had really thought about migrants, right.

02:57:03.640 --> 02:57:07.560
[Guest]: And this is a complete sort of blind spot, which seems to have been there.

02:57:07.560 --> 02:57:11.680
[Guest]: So hopefully, I hope there are many books written on COVID and different angles of COVID.

02:57:11.680 --> 02:57:15.640
[Guest]: I think we would, I think, learn a lot about nurses and doctors and how people actually

02:57:15.640 --> 02:57:20.480
[Guest]: live, you know, especially the lives of frontline workers, which I think needs to be documented.

02:57:20.480 --> 02:57:23.040
[Guest]: There should be awards for people doing great work.

02:57:23.040 --> 02:57:26.640
[Guest]: You know, we've had 150,000 deaths due to COVID.

02:57:26.640 --> 02:57:31.880
[Guest]: But in the past, mortuary workers, you know, when you think of millions of deaths, literally,

02:57:31.880 --> 02:57:36.520
[Guest]: just imagine people burning these people or burning the bodies, so many people involved

02:57:36.520 --> 02:57:41.960
[Guest]: in the pandemic, and we need to start recognizing the labor and value, you know, of that work.

02:57:41.960 --> 02:57:46.480
[Guest]: So in the future, it's going to happen, but hopefully, we kind of sail through the next

02:57:46.480 --> 02:57:48.040
[Amit Varma]: one comfortably.

02:57:48.040 --> 02:57:52.000
[Amit Varma]: On these words of hope, I think we might as well sort of end the episode here.

02:57:52.000 --> 02:57:56.760
[Amit Varma]: Chinmay, thanks so much for giving me so much of your time and giving so much of time to

02:57:56.760 --> 02:58:02.160
[Amit Varma]: writing these wonderful books, both this one and India Moving, which I think are just remarkable

02:58:02.160 --> 02:58:07.520
[Amit Varma]: books which anyone interested in India, or pandemics in the case of this latest one should

02:58:07.520 --> 02:58:08.760
[Amit Varma]: certainly pick up.

02:58:08.760 --> 02:58:09.760
[Guest]: Thanks, man.

02:58:09.760 --> 02:58:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for having me.

02:58:39.760 --> 02:59:04.360
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

